master.ca/econ/ugcm/3ll3/comte/Philosophy3.pdf Auguste Comte on why and how castes developed across the world - in The Positive Philosophy, Volume 3 (see page 55 onwards)]\n* [http://sciencepolicy.colorado.edu/students/envs_5110/merton_sociology_science.pdf Robert Merton on Caste and The Sociology of Science]\n* [http://www.cambridge.org/gb/knowledge/isbn/item1168367/?site_locale=en_GB Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age - [[Susan Bayly]]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061105095243/http://www.countercurrents.org/hr-marguerite250404.htm Class In Yemen] by Marguerite Abadjian (Archive of the Baltimore Sun)\n* [http://idsn.org/ International Dalit Solidarity Network: An international advocacy group for Dalits]\n\n{{Segregation by type|state=collapsed}}\n{{Discrimination}}\n{{Social class}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Caste| ]]\n[[Category:Social status]]\n", "name_user": "2405:201:5e00:f7e0:24dc:770f:acb4:f5aa", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caste"}
{"title_page": "A15 road (England)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2013}}\n{{infobox road\n|country=GBR\n|type=A\n|route=15\n|map=[[File:A15 road map.png|200px]]|map_custom=yes\n|length_mi=96.00\n|direction_a=North\n|direction_b=South\n|terminus_a= [[Hessle]]\n| destinations= [[Lincoln, Lincolnshire|Lincoln]], [[Sleaford]], [[Peterborough]]\n|terminus_b= [[Norman Cross]]\n|history=\n|junction= {{jct|country=GBR|A|63|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|164|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|1077|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|180|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|M|180|dab1=Great Britain}}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|18|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|631|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|1500|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|46|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|158|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|57|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|607|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|17|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|153|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|52|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|151|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|1175|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|47|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|1179|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|605|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|1129|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|1260|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|AM|1|noshield1=|nolink1= }}\n}}\n{{kml}}\nThe '''A15''' is a major [[road]] in [[England]]. It starts at a random field, goes straight for a few miles then plunges down to hell, killing all drivers driving on this road. It is declared unsafe and shut down in 2012. Over 500,000 deaths were reported on this road.\n\nAccording to [[The Automobile Association|the AA]], the route is {{convert|95|mi|km}} long, and should take 2{{fraction|1|4}} hours. Norman Cross \u2013 Bourne takes 33 minutes, Bourne to Lincoln takes 46 minutes and Lincoln to the Humber Bridge takes 54 minutes.\n\nA section of the A15 (between [[Scampton]] and the M180) provides the longest stretch of straight road in the UK.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Freestone|first1=Nigel|title=Ultimate British Roads and Motorways Quiz Book : 200 Questions on Road and Motorway History|date=2013|publisher=Andrews UK|isbn=9781909949805|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hucker|first1=Richard Adrian|title=How Did the Romans Achieve Straight Roads?|url=https://www.fig.net/resources/proceedings/fig_proceedings/fig2009/papers/hs01/hs01_hucker_3471.pdf|website=Fig.net|accessdate=14 June 2016|page=1|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==Route==\n\n===Peterborough===\n{{main article|Road transport in Peterborough}}\n[[File:London Road Towards Fletton - geograph.org.uk - 976670.jpg|thumb|left|London Road looking north under the A1139 at Fletton]][[File:A15 Queensgate (Dec 2012).jpg|thumb|left|The A15 dual carriageway at [[Queensgate shopping centre, United Kingdom|Queensgate Shopping Centre]]]]\n[[File:A15 Peterborough (City Centre) Dec 2012.jpg|thumb|left|The A15 dual carrigeway in the city centre.]]\nThe A15 is Peterborough's main connecting road from the south to the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1(M)]], joining<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/885179 |title=Cycle Route|work=OS grid TL1690|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> near [[Stilton]], at [[Norman Cross]]. It begins as ''London Road'' at junction<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/885202 |title=Brick Patterns, Norman Cross|work=OS grid TL1590|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> 16 of the A1(M) with the B1043 (former A1) in [[Cambridgeshire]] and the district of [[North West Cambridgeshire]]. From here to [[Yaxley, Cambridgeshire|Yaxley]] it passes the ''Norman Cross Hotel''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/885173 |title=Norman Cross Hotel|work=OS grid TL1590|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> and follows<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/379714 |title=London Road Yaxley|work=OS grid TL1792|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> the City of Peterborough and Cambridgeshire boundary, where there is a junction with the B1091 (for [[Farcet]]).\n\nIt enters the City of Peterborough near [[Hampton, Peterborough|Hampton Vale]] on the left, and meets the A1260 ''The Serpentine'', which leads to two much faster routes around Peterborough. Next is a roundabout for the Cygnet Park business park on the left, home of the new headquarters of [[News International]]. It enters [[Old Fletton]] near the headquarters of [[Hotpoint]] to the left. There is a staggered junction with the A1129 and it crosses the [[East Coast Main Line]]. It passes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/83410 |title=London Road, Peterborough|work=OS grid TL1997|publisher=Geograph project |date=23 November 2005 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] on the right in [[New Fletton]]. It meets the start of the [[A605 road|A605]] at a roundabout and crosses the [[River Nene]].\n\n[[File:15 Meets 47 - geograph.org.uk - 322311.jpg|thumb|The [[A47 road|A47]] junction near [[Dogsthorpe, Peterborough|Dogsthorpe]] ]]\nThe A15 takes two routes through Peterborough:\n* The route on the west side begins as ''Bourges Boulevard''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/465153 |title=Covered footbridge across Bourges Boulevard|work=OS grid TL1898|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> at Peterborough [[Crown Court]], meets the A1179 (former A47), passes the [[Peterborough railway station]] and meets three roundabouts near [[Millfield, Peterborough|Millfield]] and [[New England, Peterborough|New England]]. It follows the East Coast Main Line and becomes ''Lincoln Road'' and ''Werrington Parkway''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/672644 |title=Pedestrian crossing|work=OS grid TF1504|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> after the A47 [[Grade separation|GSJ]]. It passes four roundabouts, crossing the [[Peterborough to Lincoln Line]].\n* The route on the east side starts at the ''[[Eye, Cambridgeshire|Eye]]'' roundabout<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/354159 |title=Eye roundabout, Peterborough|work=OS grid TF2101|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> with the A1139 at [[Newark, Peterborough|Newark]], then follows the dual-carriageway ''Paston Parkway'', which meets<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/322311 |title=15 Meets 47|work=OS grid TF2002|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> the A47. It continues as a dual-carriageway (opened in spring 2008) at the next roundabout at [[Gunthorpe, Peterborough|Gunthorpe]] and follows the [[Car Dyke]] then meets another roundabout at Werrington before becoming a single carriageway and crosses the Spalding railway between [[Werrington, Peterborough|Werrington]] and [[Glinton, Cambridgeshire|Glinton]] .\n\n[[File:Pedestrian crossing - geograph.org.uk - 672644.jpg|thumb|Approaching the [[Glinton, Cambridgeshire|Glinton]] bypass from the south]]\nBoth routes head through [[Werrington, Peterborough|Werrington]] (passing either side) before joining again at [[Glinton, Cambridgeshire|Glinton]] with the roundabout with the B1443. There is another roundabout.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/162377 |title=Glinton Bypass|work=OS grid TF1405|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> with the B1443 (for [[Helpston]]). It passes [[Etton, Cambridgeshire|Etton]] and meets a roundabout with the  B1524<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/442601 |title=The B1524, Lincoln Road|work=OS grid TF1408|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> (former route through Market Deeping), B1162 (for [[Northborough, Cambridgeshire|Northborough]] to the right) and an exit for [[Maxey, Cambridgeshire|Maxey]] to the right.\n\n===Kesteven===\nJust south of the ''Welland Gate'' roundabout on the [[A1175 road|A1175]] and B1166, it crosses the [[River Welland]] so entering [[South Kesteven]] in [[Lincolnshire]]. The roundabout marks the western end of the \u00a37&nbsp;million {{convert|4|mi|adj=on}} [[Market Deeping]] bypass, finished in July 1998. The A15 and A1175 roads are now merged in a {{convert|1|mi|adj=on}} dual-carriageway stretch. It meets the B1524 (former route) at a roundabout and heads to the left as ''Peterborough Road''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/453491 |title=becoming |publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> ''Bourne Road'' and ''Deeping Road''.\n\n[[File:The A15 Peterborough Road, Langtoft, Lincs - geograph.org.uk - 453491.jpg|thumb|Entering [[Langtoft, Lincolnshire|Langtoft]] from the south]]\nNorth of Baston is the Waterside Garden Centre<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.begardenhappy.com/watersidegardencentre |title=Garden Centre Peterborough &#124; Waterside Garden Centre |publisher=BeGardenHappy | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> close to where it meets the north-south [[Roman roads in Britain|Roman Road]] [[King Street (Roman road)|King Street]], which it follows until just north of Bourne. It goes over the [[River Glen, Lincolnshire|River Glen]] at the point it is crossed by the [[Macmillan Way]], at [[Kate's Bridge]].\n\nThere is a left turn for [[Obthorpe]] and it goes through [[Thurlby by Bourne|Thurlby]], passing the ''Horseshoe''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehorseshoethurlby.co.uk |title=About us |publisher=Thehorseshoethurlby.co.uk | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> pub, then [[Northorpe, South Kesteven|Northorpe]], before coming to the small town of [[Bourne, Lincolnshire|Bourne]]. It meets the recently diverted [[A151 road|A151]] at a new roundabout (the A151 leaves to the right {{convert|100|m|yd|order=flip}} further on), where the road becomes ''South Road''. It passes [[Bourne Grammar School]], then after some treacherous bends near [[Bourne Abbey]] becomes ''South Street'', with the town's Heritage centre<ref>{{cite web|title=Baldock's Mill|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/149927|publisher=Geograph project|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref>  and war memorial gardens on the left by the [[Bourne Eau]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bourne Eau and memorial gardens|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/404360|publisher=Geograph project|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref> At the crossroads in the centre of town it crosses the B1193 (original route of the A151) in the historic market place(<small>{{coord|52|46.0920|N|0|22.6320|W|region:GB|display=inline|format=dms|name=Bourne, Lincolnshire cross roads}}</small>), where are located the ''Nags Head'', ''Angel Hotel'', ''Burghley Arms''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://homepages.which.net/~rex/bourne/burghleyarms.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-01-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070711032415/http://homepages.which.net/~rex/bourne/burghleyarms.htm |archivedate=11 July 2007 }} </ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bourne town centre|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/96987|publisher=Geograph Project|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref>  As ''North Street'', it passes the Burghley Centre<ref>{{cite web|url=http://homepages.which.net/~rex/bourne/burghleycentre.htm |title=The Burghley Centre, Bourne |publisher=Rex Needle |accessdate=11 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620051758/http://homepages.which.net/~rex/bourne/burghleycentre.htm |archivedate=20 June 2013 }}</ref> (shops), and Bourne Bus Station.  At the two miniature roundabouts the name changes to North Road, which name it keeps until it reaches Morton.\n\n[[File:Robin Hood and Little John - geograph.org.uk - 275210.jpg|thumb|''Robin Hood and Little John'' at [[Aslackby]]]]\nJust outside Bourne, at <small>{{coord|52.79975|-0.41525|display=inline|name=Junction of King Street & Mareham Lane Roman roads}}</small>, the route of (Roman) King Street heads off across the fields to [[Stainfield]] and [[Ancaster, Lincolnshire|Ancaster]] but the A15 continues north along the line of another Roman road, [[Mareham Lane]]. It passes close to [[Dyke, Lincolnshire|Dyke]], and goes through [[Morton and Hanthorpe|Morton]] as ''Bourne Road'', passing the ''Lord Nelson''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pub-explorer.com/olpg/the-lordnelson/morton/index.htm |title=The Lord Nelson, Morton |publisher=Pub-explorer.com |date=14 April 2003 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> pub. It becomes ''Folkingham Road''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/312149and |title=Looking towards Bourne on the A15|work=OS grid TF0926|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=1 May 2013}}</ref> there is a right turn for [[Haconby]] and a junction with the B1177 (for [[Billingborough]]). Close by are [[Rippingale]] and [[Kirkby Underwood]]. Between Rippingale and [[Aslackby]] a wooded lay-by known locally as 'Turnpike Bar' marks the deviation from the line of the [[Roman roads in Britain|Roman Road]] [[Mareham Lane]]<small>{{coord|52.84591|-0.3895|display=inline|format=dms|name=southern end of Mareham Lane Roman road}}</small>. The A15 passes by [[Aslackby]] and the '' Robin Hood and Little John'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/275210 |title=Robin Hood and Little John|work=OS grid TF0830|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> and then through the middle of [[Folkingham]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A15, Folkingham|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/2505160|publisher=Geograph project|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Approach to Holdingham Roundabout on the A15 - geograph.org.uk - 1073672.jpg|thumb|left|Sleaford Bypass looking north to Holdingham]]\nThere is the [[Threekingham Bar]] roundabout<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/360104 |title=Osbournby Roundabout|work=OS grid TF0736|publisher=Geograph project |date=10 March 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> with the east-west [[A52 road|A52]], and it goes through [[Osbournby]], as ''London Road'' the primary school].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.osbournby.lincs.sch.uk |title=Osbournby Primary School |publisher=Osbournby.lincs.sch.uk | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> It passes the ''Tally Ho Inn]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thetallyhoinn.com |title=Fine Pub Food in Sleaford, Lincolnshire |publisher=The Tally Ho Inn |accessdate=11 May 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625054532/http://thetallyhoinn.com/ |archive-date=25 June 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Tally-Ho Inn|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/2805324|publisher=Geograph project|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref>  near [[Aswarby]], then there are left turns for [[Aunsby]] and [[Aswarby and Swarby|Swarby]]. [[Sleaford]] and Silk Willoughby]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/360524 |title=Silk Willoughby - must be better than this?|work=OS grid TF0442|publisher=Geograph project |date=10 March 2013 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> were on the A15, which slowed traffic down as the traffic went across a [[level crossing]] and through Sleaford's shopping area. The \u00a35.7&nbsp;million bypass opened on 16 September 1993, by [[Douglas Hogg, 3rd Viscount Hailsham|Douglas Hogg]], where there is a roundabout with the A153 and B1517. The A15 crosses the railway<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/122470 |title=Road Bridge Over Railway|work=OS grid TF0545|publisher=Geograph project |date=15 February 2006 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> and [[River Slea]], and then leaves the bypass at the ''Holdingham Roundabout'' with the [[A17 road (Great Britain)|A17]] and B1518 (former route).\n\n[[File:Approach to Holdingham Roundabout on the B1518 - geograph.org.uk - 1136107.jpg|thumb|Approaching the Holdingham Roundabout from the former route]]\nAs ''Lincoln Road'', it goes close to [[Leasingham]] meeting the B1209. There is a junction<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/384168 |title=for |publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> [[Cranwell]] with the B1429. It meets the B1191 (for [[Scopwick]]), B1202 (for [[Boothby Graffoe]] to the west and [[Metheringham]] to the east) next to the former [[RAF Coleby Grange]], and B1178 (for [[Harmston]]), where it passes [[Dunston Pillar]]. At [[Nocton]] Heath, it passes the ''Kitchen''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/490205 |title=The Kitchen|work=OS grid TF0160|publisher=Geograph project |date=9 July 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> cafe.<ref>[http://www.thekitchenatnoctonheath.co.uk Untitled Document<!-- Bot generated title -->]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320212735/http://www.thekitchenatnoctonheath.co.uk/ |date=20 March 2012 }}</ref> On the route to Lincoln, it goes near to two RAF bases \u2013 [[RAF Digby]], which is used for communications rather than as a flying station, and across the  end<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/419932 |title=A15 passes Waddington airfield|work=OS grid SK9964|publisher=Geograph project |date=1 May 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> of the runway of [[RAF Waddington]], which flies [[E-3 Sentry|AWACS]] and [[Hawker-Siddeley Nimrod|Nimrod]] aircraft. A parking place and cafe are provided for plane spotters on the eastern side of the road.\n\n[[File:On guard - geograph.org.uk - 687930.jpg|thumb|left|Vulcan XM607 by the side of the A15 at [[RAF Waddington]] which took part in [[Operation Black Buck]] ]]\nNext<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/687930 |title=On guard|work=OS grid SK9965|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> to the runway at Waddington is an old [[Avro Vulcan|Vulcan]], carrying the number of the plane that bombed [[Port Stanley]]. The A15 and [[Ermine Street]] meet at Bracebridge Heath, about {{convert|1000|m|yd|order=flip}} north of the traffic lights for [[Canwick]] <small>{{coord|53.20207|-0.54558|display=inline|format=dms|name=A15 and Roman Ermine Street converge at Bracebridge Heath}}</small>.\n\n===Lincoln===\n[[File:South Common - geograph.org.uk - 54273.jpg|thumb|left|South Common]]\nAt [[Bracebridge Heath]], it passes the [[Total S.A.|Total]] ''Sleaford Road Service Station'', just before it passes the ''Blacksmiths Arms'', and meets the end of the [[A607 road|A607]] at [[traffic light]]s at ''The Bull''. Towards Lincoln, it meets the B1131 as ''London Road'', next to '' The Homestead''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pub-explorer.com/lincs/pub/homestead.htm |title=on PubExplorer |publisher=Pub-explorer.com |accessdate=11 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313012738/http://www.pub-explorer.com/lincs/pub/homestead.htm |archivedate=13 March 2012 }}</ref> (former St John's Hospital). It is crossed by the [[Viking Way]] at the moment [[Lincoln Cathedral]] comes into full view. The road meets the A1434 ''[[Newark-on-Trent|Newark]] Road'' from [[North Hykeham]] at traffic lights after passing [[The Priory Academy LSST]] and a bridge over the former [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|GNR]] Grantham-Lincoln railway, where it becomes ''St Catherine's Road'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/568993 |title=St.Catherines|work=OS grid SK9769|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> and passes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/567595 |title=Site of the Eleanor Cross|work=OS grid SK9769|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref>  an [[Eleanor Cross]]. At a roundabout at the south end of (what becomes) Lincoln's ''[[High Street, Lincoln|High Street]]'', it exits to the right along ''South Park'', passing the HQ of [[Lincolnshire Fire and Rescue Service]], and meets the B1188 at traffic lights, where it heads left as ''Canwick Road''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/411652 |title=Canwick Road approaching Lincoln City Centre from the south|work=OS grid SK9770|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The A15, Lincoln - geograph.org.uk - 690346.jpg|thumb|Looking south over Pelham Bridge]]\nAt Pelham Bridge<ref>{{cite web|author=<!--lead container name-->50 years of Pelham Bridge |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/lincolnshire/content/articles/2008/06/26/pelhambridge_50_feature.shtml |title=Lincolnshire - Places - 50 years of Pelham Bridge |publisher=BBC |date=26 June 2008 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> (which was opened by the [[Elizabeth II|Queen]] in 1958), it crosses the [[Peterborough to Lincoln Line|railway]], with the [[Lincoln Central railway station|railway station]] on the left, the junction with the start of the [[A57 road|A57]] and [[Ruston (engine builder)|Siemens]] (former [[Alstom]]) factory. It crosses the [[River Witham]], before heading up the hill on the north side of the [[Lincoln Cliff|Lincoln Gap]], and heading in the direction of the A158 as ''Lindum Road'' (for [[Skegness]]), where it is crossed by the [[Viking Way]] near [[Lincoln Minster School]]. As ''Wragby Road'', it passes [[Lincoln Christ's Hospital School]] on the left, then meets the B1308<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/52821 |title=Outer Circle Road, Lincoln|work=OS grid SK9972|publisher=Geograph project |date=13 September 2005 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> near the large Carlton Centre Retail Park. The ''Lincolnshire Poacher''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lincolnshirepoacherpub.co.uk |title=Lincolnshire Poacher - Lincoln |publisher=Lincolnshirepoacherpub.co.uk |date=28 April 2013 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> is on the right hand side and there is a right turn for [[Cherry Willingham]] and [[Reepham, Lincolnshire|Reepham]].\n\nModern traffic routing has taken the road away from the route of [[Ermine Street]] as it passes through Lincoln.\n\n===Lindsey===\n[[File:Ermine Street - geograph.org.uk - 275160.jpg|thumb|left|North of Lincoln near Riseholme]]\n[[File:The A15, Barton-upon-Humber - geograph.org.uk - 696210.jpg|thumb|left|The Humber Bridge looking north]]\n[[File:RAF Scampton front the air.jpeg|thumb|right|The A15 at its 1950s curvature east of Ermine Street around RAF Scampton, seen in March 2016]]\n\nNorth of Lincoln, the A15 enters [[West Lindsey]], and meets the start of the A158 at a roundabout, then runs concurrently<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/275900 |title=A46 Lincoln Ring Road|work=OS grid SK9874|publisher=Geograph project |date=9 November 2006 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> with the [[A46 road|A46]] to the ''Riseholme'' roundabout, where it briefly re-enters the City of Lincoln, then follows<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/275160 |title=Ermine Street|work=OS grid SK9776|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> the [[Roman road]] [[Ermine Street]] past the [[Lincolnshire School of Agriculture|Riseholme College of Agriculture]] on the right, now part of the [[University of Lincoln]], and Lincolnshire Showground<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lincolnshireshowground.co.uk |title=Lincolnshire Events Centre &#124; Lincolnshire Showground &#124; Events Centre |publisher=Lincolnshire Showground |date=18 January 2013 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> to the left.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/89223 |title=Entrance to Lincolnshire Showground from the A15|work=OS grid SK9777|publisher=Geograph project |date=10 December 2005 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> At the end of a {{convert|40|mph}} section is the ''Tillbridge Lane'' roundabout<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/89224 |title=Commercial Buildings at the A1500 A15 junction|work=OS grid SK9778|publisher=Geograph project |date=10 December 2005 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> with the A1500, for [[Gainsborough, Lincolnshire|Gainsborough]]. From here, it used to be straight, but with [[RAF Scampton]] becoming a base for [[V bomber]]s in the 1950s, the runway had to be extended and the road now has a curved diversion to the east. It passes the Scampton primary school<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pollyplatt.lincs.sch.uk |title=Home |publisher=Pollyplatt.lincs.sch.uk | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> and continues<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/416347 |title=Ermine Street|work=OS grid SK9685|publisher=Geograph project |date=28 April 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> past a right turn to [[Normanby by Spital]], on its most straight section, also the parish boundary of many local villages. At the roundabout with the [[A631 road|A631]] at [[Caenby Corner]], there is the [[Total S.A.|Total]] ''Caenby Corner Garage'' just south of [[Spital-in-the-Street]]. Overtaking is difficult as the road, although straight, is undulating with unmarked dips and slow moving farm traffic. There are two right turns for [[Bishop Norton]] and [[Atterby]]. There is a right turn for [[Snitterby]] and a left turn for [[Blyborough]]. At the B1205 staggered crossroads<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/142584 |title=B1205 junction with the A15|work=OS grid SK9696|publisher=Geograph project |date=26 March 2006 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> (for [[Waddingham]] to the east, and [[Grayingham]] to the west), it enters [[North Lincolnshire]].\n\n[[File:A15 near Scawby - geograph.org.uk - 234368.jpg|thumb|Looking north near Scawby]]\n[[File:Start of the M180 - geograph.org.uk - 849005.jpg|thumb|A15/[[M180 motorway|M180]]/[[A180 road (England)|A180]] Barnetby Top Interchange]]\n[[File:A15 exit to Barton-Upon-Humber - geograph.org.uk - 39932.jpg|thumb|Looking north to the A1077 intersection]]\nAt the B1206 crossroads, the old route used to go through [[Hibaldstow]] and [[Brigg]], with the former road to [[Redbourne]] now a cycle route. It passes close to [[Kirton in Lindsey]], home of [[RAF Kirton in Lindsey]] much used in the [[Second World War]] as a [[Battle of Britain airfields|fighter airfield]] in [[No. 12 Group RAF|12 Group]], now home to the [[Trent Valley Gliding Club]]. [[Hibaldstow]] was a wartime fighter airfield<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wartimememories.co.uk/airfields/hibaldstow.html |title=The Wartime Memories Project - RAF Hibaldstow |publisher=Wartimememories.co.uk |accessdate=11 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206173253/http://www.wartimememories.co.uk/airfields/hibaldstow.html |archivedate=6 December 2013 }}</ref> as well, and this is now used as a base for parachuting and parachuting competitions by [[Target Skysports]]. The {{convert|5|mi|adj=on}} \u00a37&nbsp;million Brigg and Redbourne bypass<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/326757 |title=A15 north towards the M180|work=OS grid SK9698|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> was added in December 1989 which follows<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/583632 |title=Lay-by on the A15 west of Hibaldstow|work=OS grid SE9503|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> the old Ermine Street in [[North Lincolnshire]] further than previously, with a much flatter, wider and safer road. This section was the upgraded route of an unclassified road. It crosses the [[Sheffield to Lincoln Line|Sheffield to Cleethorpes railway line]] near the deserted village of [[Gainsthorpe]], passes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/234368 |title=A15 near Scawby|work=OS grid SE9505|publisher=Geograph project |date=6 September 2006 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> near to [[Scawby]], and joining<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/327474 |title=M180 west towards junction 4|work=OS grid SE9606|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> the [[M180 motorway|M180]] at junction 4, near [[Scunthorpe]].  It abandons the Roman alignments at a short spur to the A18 at the ''Briggate Lodge Roundabout'' next to the Forest Pines<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qhotels.co.uk/hotels/forest-pines-near-brigg.aspx |title=Hotels in North Lincolnshire - Forest Pines Hotel & Golf Resort |publisher=QHotels | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> golf club and hotel at [[Broughton, Lincolnshire|Broughton]]. Ermine Street continues north as the B1207, meeting the Humber near [[Winteringham]].\n\nThe route of the A15 now becomes part of the three-laned M180, which was opened on 2 September 1977. The A15 section along Ermine Street was planned to be opened at the same time, but it had to wait twelve years. The buildup of traffic to Grimsby prompted calls for the Brigg bypass for many years, but the [[Flixborough disaster|Flixborough explosion]] of 1974 made it more of an emergency. This section goes under the [[A18 road (Great Britain)|A18]], over the [[River Ancholme]], over the old route of the A15 (B1206) and over the [[South TransPennine|South Trans-Pennine]] railway. At junction 5, the A15 reforms at the dual-grade ''Barnetby Top Interchange'', which is crossed by the [[Viking Way]] and has an exit to [[Elsham, Lincolnshire|Elsham]]. It continues north as a dual carriageway which carries about as little traffic as the M180. The M180 drops to two lanes under this roundabout and continues to [[Grimsby]] and [[Immingham]] as the A180.\n\nThe A15 towards the [[Humber Bridge]], goes directly across the runways of the former [[RAF Bomber Command]] airfield at [[RAF Elsham Wolds]] (where over 1000 of its aircrew were killed), which is now the Elsham Wolds<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/211562 |title=Elsham Wolds - Old Hangar|work=OS grid TA0413|publisher=Geograph project |date=30 July 2006 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> Industrial Estate. The former route of the A15, pre-1978, is now called B1206,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/61208 |title=The old Barton to Brigg Turnpike road|work=OS grid TA0314|publisher=Geograph project |date=4 October 2005 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> and ends at [[New Holland, North Lincolnshire|New Holland]], where the A15 formerly connected with the [[PS Lincoln Castle|Humber Ferry]]. The \u00a35.6&nbsp;million {{convert|6|mi|adj=on}} [[Brigg]] Bypass to [[Barton-upon-Humber]] Bypass (up to where the B1218 crosses)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/494323 |title=A15|work=OS grid TA0219|publisher=Geograph project |date=14 July 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> section opened in June 1978.\n\nThe \u00a32&nbsp;million {{convert|1|mi|adj=on}} Barton-upon-Humber Bypass to Humber Bridge (A1077 interchange)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/39932 |title=A15 exit to Barton-Upon-Humber|work=OS grid TA0220|publisher=Geograph project |date=19 August 2005 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> section opened in September 1978, although some maps show this being open before the southern section to the M180. When this whole section<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/51501 |title=A15|work=OS grid TA0218|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> opened to the GSJ with the A1077 (for [[South Ferriby]]) in 1978, there was no longer any access to the B1218. In the early 1990s, a new interchange<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/51498 |title=A15/B1206 turn-off|work=OS grid TA0316|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> was added with the B1206<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/393180 |title=The Road to Barton|work=OS grid TA0315|publisher=Geograph project |date=8 April 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> (the former A15), which is crossed<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/848959 |title=Crossing the A15|work=OS grid TA0216|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> by the Viking Way, which follows the road for over a mile. The section<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/24043 |title=Humber Bridge from South|work=OS grid TA0222|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> across the [[River Humber|Humber]] was opened on 17 July 1981, by the [[Elizabeth II|Queen]], and was the world's longest single-span bridge until 1997. The tolls<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/452359 |title=Humber Bridge toll plaza|work=OS grid TA0225|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> are north of the bridge. It crosses<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/403031 |title=Rail and road|work=OS grid TA0225|publisher=Geograph project |date=16 April 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> the [[A63 road|A63]] and meets a roundabout with [[A164 road|A164]] (for [[Beverley]]) and A1105, then turns left along a short section<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/541875 |title=East or west?|work=OS grid TA0126|publisher=Geograph project |date=1 September 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> of dual-carriageway (former A63) to end at the A63.\n\n==Improvements==\nPresently, the A15 passes through the centre of [[Lincoln, England|Lincoln]], which causes congestion in the city centre. In 2012, planning permission was submitted in order to build a 7.5km bypass which will route traffic to the east of the city. All permissions were granted subsequently by February 2016, and work commenced in May 2016. A number of setbacks have occurred, especially after the loss of [[Carillion]] as the main contractor, after they entered liquidation in January 2018. [[Galliford Try]] were chosen as the replacement contractor. As of March 2020, three roundabouts have opened and a substantial amount of the works have been completed. The project is expected to be completed in Autumn 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lincolnshire.gov.uk/major-projects/lincoln-eastern-bypass|title=Lincoln Eastern Bypass|last=|first=|website=Lincolnshire County Council|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ermine Street]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|A15 road (England)}}\n* [http://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/roadlists/f99/15.shtml The Society for All British Road Enthusiasts' article on A15]\n\n{{UK primary routes 1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1-0015}}\n[[Category:Lincoln, England]]\n[[Category:North Kesteven District]]\n[[Category:Borough of North Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Roads in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:Roads in England]]\n[[Category:Roads in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Roads in Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Roads with a reversible lane]]\n[[Category:South Kesteven District]]\n[[Category:The Deepings]]\n[[Category:Transport in Huntingdonshire]]\n[[Category:Transport in Peterborough]]\n[[Category:Transport in the East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:West Lindsey District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2013}}\n{{infobox road\n|country=GBR\n|type=A\n|route=15\n|map=[[File:A15 road map.png|200px]]|map_custom=yes\n|length_mi=96.00\n|direction_a=North\n|direction_b=South\n|terminus_a= [[Hessle]]\n| destinations= [[Lincoln, Lincolnshire|Lincoln]], [[Sleaford]], [[Peterborough]]\n|terminus_b= [[Norman Cross]]\n|history=\n|junction= {{jct|country=GBR|A|63|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|164|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|1077|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|180|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|M|180|dab1=Great Britain}}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|18|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|631|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|1500|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|46|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|158|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|57|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|607|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|17|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|153|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|52|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|151|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|1175|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|47|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|1179|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|605|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|1129|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|1260|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|AM|1|noshield1=|nolink1= }}\n}}\n{{kml}}\nThe '''A15''' is a major [[road]] in [[England]]. It runs north from [[Peterborough]] via [[Market Deeping]], [[Bourne, Lincolnshire|Bourne]], [[Sleaford]] and [[Lincoln, England|Lincoln]] along a variety of ancient, Roman, and Turnpike alignments before it is interrupted at its junction with the [[M180 motorway|M180]] near [[Scawby]]. The road restarts {{convert|10|mi}} east, and then continues north past [[Barton-upon-Humber]], crossing the [[Humber]] on the [[Humber Bridge]] before terminating at [[Hessle]] near [[Kingston upon Hull]].\n\n==Driving conditions==\nAccording to [[The Automobile Association|the AA]], the route is {{convert|95|mi|km}} long, and should take 2{{fraction|1|4}} hours. Norman Cross \u2013 Bourne takes 33 minutes, Bourne to Lincoln takes 46 minutes and Lincoln to the Humber Bridge takes 54 minutes.\n\nA section of the A15 (between [[Scampton]] and the M180) provides the longest stretch of straight road in the UK.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Freestone|first1=Nigel|title=Ultimate British Roads and Motorways Quiz Book : 200 Questions on Road and Motorway History|date=2013|publisher=Andrews UK|isbn=9781909949805|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hucker|first1=Richard Adrian|title=How Did the Romans Achieve Straight Roads?|url=https://www.fig.net/resources/proceedings/fig_proceedings/fig2009/papers/hs01/hs01_hucker_3471.pdf|website=Fig.net|accessdate=14 June 2016|page=1|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==Route==\n\n===Peterborough===\n{{main article|Road transport in Peterborough}}\n[[File:London Road Towards Fletton - geograph.org.uk - 976670.jpg|thumb|left|London Road looking north under the A1139 at Fletton]][[File:A15 Queensgate (Dec 2012).jpg|thumb|left|The A15 dual carriageway at [[Queensgate shopping centre, United Kingdom|Queensgate Shopping Centre]]]]\n[[File:A15 Peterborough (City Centre) Dec 2012.jpg|thumb|left|The A15 dual carrigeway in the city centre.]]\nThe A15 is Peterborough's main connecting road from the south to the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1(M)]], joining<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/885179 |title=Cycle Route|work=OS grid TL1690|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> near [[Stilton]], at [[Norman Cross]]. It begins as ''London Road'' at junction<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/885202 |title=Brick Patterns, Norman Cross|work=OS grid TL1590|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> 16 of the A1(M) with the B1043 (former A1) in [[Cambridgeshire]] and the district of [[North West Cambridgeshire]]. From here to [[Yaxley, Cambridgeshire|Yaxley]] it passes the ''Norman Cross Hotel''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/885173 |title=Norman Cross Hotel|work=OS grid TL1590|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> and follows<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/379714 |title=London Road Yaxley|work=OS grid TL1792|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> the City of Peterborough and Cambridgeshire boundary, where there is a junction with the B1091 (for [[Farcet]]).\n\nIt enters the City of Peterborough near [[Hampton, Peterborough|Hampton Vale]] on the left, and meets the A1260 ''The Serpentine'', which leads to two much faster routes around Peterborough. Next is a roundabout for the Cygnet Park business park on the left, home of the new headquarters of [[News International]]. It enters [[Old Fletton]] near the headquarters of [[Hotpoint]] to the left. There is a staggered junction with the A1129 and it crosses the [[East Coast Main Line]]. It passes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/83410 |title=London Road, Peterborough|work=OS grid TL1997|publisher=Geograph project |date=23 November 2005 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] on the right in [[New Fletton]]. It meets the start of the [[A605 road|A605]] at a roundabout and crosses the [[River Nene]].\n\n[[File:15 Meets 47 - geograph.org.uk - 322311.jpg|thumb|The [[A47 road|A47]] junction near [[Dogsthorpe, Peterborough|Dogsthorpe]] ]]\nThe A15 takes two routes through Peterborough:\n* The route on the west side begins as ''Bourges Boulevard''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/465153 |title=Covered footbridge across Bourges Boulevard|work=OS grid TL1898|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> at Peterborough [[Crown Court]], meets the A1179 (former A47), passes the [[Peterborough railway station]] and meets three roundabouts near [[Millfield, Peterborough|Millfield]] and [[New England, Peterborough|New England]]. It follows the East Coast Main Line and becomes ''Lincoln Road'' and ''Werrington Parkway''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/672644 |title=Pedestrian crossing|work=OS grid TF1504|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> after the A47 [[Grade separation|GSJ]]. It passes four roundabouts, crossing the [[Peterborough to Lincoln Line]].\n* The route on the east side starts at the ''[[Eye, Cambridgeshire|Eye]]'' roundabout<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/354159 |title=Eye roundabout, Peterborough|work=OS grid TF2101|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> with the A1139 at [[Newark, Peterborough|Newark]], then follows the dual-carriageway ''Paston Parkway'', which meets<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/322311 |title=15 Meets 47|work=OS grid TF2002|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> the A47. It continues as a dual-carriageway (opened in spring 2008) at the next roundabout at [[Gunthorpe, Peterborough|Gunthorpe]] and follows the [[Car Dyke]] then meets another roundabout at Werrington before becoming a single carriageway and crosses the Spalding railway between [[Werrington, Peterborough|Werrington]] and [[Glinton, Cambridgeshire|Glinton]] .\n\n[[File:Pedestrian crossing - geograph.org.uk - 672644.jpg|thumb|Approaching the [[Glinton, Cambridgeshire|Glinton]] bypass from the south]]\nBoth routes head through [[Werrington, Peterborough|Werrington]] (passing either side) before joining again at [[Glinton, Cambridgeshire|Glinton]] with the roundabout with the B1443. There is another roundabout.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/162377 |title=Glinton Bypass|work=OS grid TF1405|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> with the B1443 (for [[Helpston]]). It passes [[Etton, Cambridgeshire|Etton]] and meets a roundabout with the  B1524<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/442601 |title=The B1524, Lincoln Road|work=OS grid TF1408|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> (former route through Market Deeping), B1162 (for [[Northborough, Cambridgeshire|Northborough]] to the right) and an exit for [[Maxey, Cambridgeshire|Maxey]] to the right.\n\n===Kesteven===\nJust south of the ''Welland Gate'' roundabout on the [[A1175 road|A1175]] and B1166, it crosses the [[River Welland]] so entering [[South Kesteven]] in [[Lincolnshire]]. The roundabout marks the western end of the \u00a37&nbsp;million {{convert|4|mi|adj=on}} [[Market Deeping]] bypass, finished in July 1998. The A15 and A1175 roads are now merged in a {{convert|1|mi|adj=on}} dual-carriageway stretch. It meets the B1524 (former route) at a roundabout and heads to the left as ''Peterborough Road''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/453491 |title=becoming |publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> ''Bourne Road'' and ''Deeping Road''.\n\n[[File:The A15 Peterborough Road, Langtoft, Lincs - geograph.org.uk - 453491.jpg|thumb|Entering [[Langtoft, Lincolnshire|Langtoft]] from the south]]\nNorth of Baston is the Waterside Garden Centre<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.begardenhappy.com/watersidegardencentre |title=Garden Centre Peterborough &#124; Waterside Garden Centre |publisher=BeGardenHappy | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> close to where it meets the north-south [[Roman roads in Britain|Roman Road]] [[King Street (Roman road)|King Street]], which it follows until just north of Bourne. It goes over the [[River Glen, Lincolnshire|River Glen]] at the point it is crossed by the [[Macmillan Way]], at [[Kate's Bridge]].\n\nThere is a left turn for [[Obthorpe]] and it goes through [[Thurlby by Bourne|Thurlby]], passing the ''Horseshoe''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehorseshoethurlby.co.uk |title=About us |publisher=Thehorseshoethurlby.co.uk | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> pub, then [[Northorpe, South Kesteven|Northorpe]], before coming to the small town of [[Bourne, Lincolnshire|Bourne]]. It meets the recently diverted [[A151 road|A151]] at a new roundabout (the A151 leaves to the right {{convert|100|m|yd|order=flip}} further on), where the road becomes ''South Road''. It passes [[Bourne Grammar School]], then after some treacherous bends near [[Bourne Abbey]] becomes ''South Street'', with the town's Heritage centre<ref>{{cite web|title=Baldock's Mill|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/149927|publisher=Geograph project|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref>  and war memorial gardens on the left by the [[Bourne Eau]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bourne Eau and memorial gardens|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/404360|publisher=Geograph project|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref> At the crossroads in the centre of town it crosses the B1193 (original route of the A151) in the historic market place(<small>{{coord|52|46.0920|N|0|22.6320|W|region:GB|display=inline|format=dms|name=Bourne, Lincolnshire cross roads}}</small>), where are located the ''Nags Head'', ''Angel Hotel'', ''Burghley Arms''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://homepages.which.net/~rex/bourne/burghleyarms.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-01-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070711032415/http://homepages.which.net/~rex/bourne/burghleyarms.htm |archivedate=11 July 2007 }} </ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bourne town centre|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/96987|publisher=Geograph Project|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref>  As ''North Street'', it passes the Burghley Centre<ref>{{cite web|url=http://homepages.which.net/~rex/bourne/burghleycentre.htm |title=The Burghley Centre, Bourne |publisher=Rex Needle |accessdate=11 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620051758/http://homepages.which.net/~rex/bourne/burghleycentre.htm |archivedate=20 June 2013 }}</ref> (shops), and Bourne Bus Station.  At the two miniature roundabouts the name changes to North Road, which name it keeps until it reaches Morton.\n\n[[File:Robin Hood and Little John - geograph.org.uk - 275210.jpg|thumb|''Robin Hood and Little John'' at [[Aslackby]]]]\nJust outside Bourne, at <small>{{coord|52.79975|-0.41525|display=inline|name=Junction of King Street & Mareham Lane Roman roads}}</small>, the route of (Roman) King Street heads off across the fields to [[Stainfield]] and [[Ancaster, Lincolnshire|Ancaster]] but the A15 continues north along the line of another Roman road, [[Mareham Lane]]. It passes close to [[Dyke, Lincolnshire|Dyke]], and goes through [[Morton and Hanthorpe|Morton]] as ''Bourne Road'', passing the ''Lord Nelson''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pub-explorer.com/olpg/the-lordnelson/morton/index.htm |title=The Lord Nelson, Morton |publisher=Pub-explorer.com |date=14 April 2003 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> pub. It becomes ''Folkingham Road''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/312149and |title=Looking towards Bourne on the A15|work=OS grid TF0926|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=1 May 2013}}</ref> there is a right turn for [[Haconby]] and a junction with the B1177 (for [[Billingborough]]). Close by are [[Rippingale]] and [[Kirkby Underwood]]. Between Rippingale and [[Aslackby]] a wooded lay-by known locally as 'Turnpike Bar' marks the deviation from the line of the [[Roman roads in Britain|Roman Road]] [[Mareham Lane]]<small>{{coord|52.84591|-0.3895|display=inline|format=dms|name=southern end of Mareham Lane Roman road}}</small>. The A15 passes by [[Aslackby]] and the '' Robin Hood and Little John'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/275210 |title=Robin Hood and Little John|work=OS grid TF0830|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> and then through the middle of [[Folkingham]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A15, Folkingham|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/2505160|publisher=Geograph project|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Approach to Holdingham Roundabout on the A15 - geograph.org.uk - 1073672.jpg|thumb|left|Sleaford Bypass looking north to Holdingham]]\nThere is the [[Threekingham Bar]] roundabout<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/360104 |title=Osbournby Roundabout|work=OS grid TF0736|publisher=Geograph project |date=10 March 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> with the east-west [[A52 road|A52]], and it goes through [[Osbournby]], as ''London Road'' the primary school].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.osbournby.lincs.sch.uk |title=Osbournby Primary School |publisher=Osbournby.lincs.sch.uk | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> It passes the ''Tally Ho Inn]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thetallyhoinn.com |title=Fine Pub Food in Sleaford, Lincolnshire |publisher=The Tally Ho Inn |accessdate=11 May 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625054532/http://thetallyhoinn.com/ |archive-date=25 June 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Tally-Ho Inn|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/2805324|publisher=Geograph project|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref>  near [[Aswarby]], then there are left turns for [[Aunsby]] and [[Aswarby and Swarby|Swarby]]. [[Sleaford]] and Silk Willoughby]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/360524 |title=Silk Willoughby - must be better than this?|work=OS grid TF0442|publisher=Geograph project |date=10 March 2013 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> were on the A15, which slowed traffic down as the traffic went across a [[level crossing]] and through Sleaford's shopping area. The \u00a35.7&nbsp;million bypass opened on 16 September 1993, by [[Douglas Hogg, 3rd Viscount Hailsham|Douglas Hogg]], where there is a roundabout with the A153 and B1517. The A15 crosses the railway<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/122470 |title=Road Bridge Over Railway|work=OS grid TF0545|publisher=Geograph project |date=15 February 2006 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> and [[River Slea]], and then leaves the bypass at the ''Holdingham Roundabout'' with the [[A17 road (Great Britain)|A17]] and B1518 (former route).\n\n[[File:Approach to Holdingham Roundabout on the B1518 - geograph.org.uk - 1136107.jpg|thumb|Approaching the Holdingham Roundabout from the former route]]\nAs ''Lincoln Road'', it goes close to [[Leasingham]] meeting the B1209. There is a junction<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/384168 |title=for |publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> [[Cranwell]] with the B1429. It meets the B1191 (for [[Scopwick]]), B1202 (for [[Boothby Graffoe]] to the west and [[Metheringham]] to the east) next to the former [[RAF Coleby Grange]], and B1178 (for [[Harmston]]), where it passes [[Dunston Pillar]]. At [[Nocton]] Heath, it passes the ''Kitchen''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/490205 |title=The Kitchen|work=OS grid TF0160|publisher=Geograph project |date=9 July 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> cafe.<ref>[http://www.thekitchenatnoctonheath.co.uk Untitled Document<!-- Bot generated title -->]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320212735/http://www.thekitchenatnoctonheath.co.uk/ |date=20 March 2012 }}</ref> On the route to Lincoln, it goes near to two RAF bases \u2013 [[RAF Digby]], which is used for communications rather than as a flying station, and across the  end<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/419932 |title=A15 passes Waddington airfield|work=OS grid SK9964|publisher=Geograph project |date=1 May 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> of the runway of [[RAF Waddington]], which flies [[E-3 Sentry|AWACS]] and [[Hawker-Siddeley Nimrod|Nimrod]] aircraft. A parking place and cafe are provided for plane spotters on the eastern side of the road.\n\n[[File:On guard - geograph.org.uk - 687930.jpg|thumb|left|Vulcan XM607 by the side of the A15 at [[RAF Waddington]] which took part in [[Operation Black Buck]] ]]\nNext<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/687930 |title=On guard|work=OS grid SK9965|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> to the runway at Waddington is an old [[Avro Vulcan|Vulcan]], carrying the number of the plane that bombed [[Port Stanley]]. The A15 and [[Ermine Street]] meet at Bracebridge Heath, about {{convert|1000|m|yd|order=flip}} north of the traffic lights for [[Canwick]] <small>{{coord|53.20207|-0.54558|display=inline|format=dms|name=A15 and Roman Ermine Street converge at Bracebridge Heath}}</small>.\n\n===Lincoln===\n[[File:South Common - geograph.org.uk - 54273.jpg|thumb|left|South Common]]\nAt [[Bracebridge Heath]], it passes the [[Total S.A.|Total]] ''Sleaford Road Service Station'', just before it passes the ''Blacksmiths Arms'', and meets the end of the [[A607 road|A607]] at [[traffic light]]s at ''The Bull''. Towards Lincoln, it meets the B1131 as ''London Road'', next to '' The Homestead''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pub-explorer.com/lincs/pub/homestead.htm |title=on PubExplorer |publisher=Pub-explorer.com |accessdate=11 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313012738/http://www.pub-explorer.com/lincs/pub/homestead.htm |archivedate=13 March 2012 }}</ref> (former St John's Hospital). It is crossed by the [[Viking Way]] at the moment [[Lincoln Cathedral]] comes into full view. The road meets the A1434 ''[[Newark-on-Trent|Newark]] Road'' from [[North Hykeham]] at traffic lights after passing [[The Priory Academy LSST]] and a bridge over the former [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|GNR]] Grantham-Lincoln railway, where it becomes ''St Catherine's Road'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/568993 |title=St.Catherines|work=OS grid SK9769|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> and passes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/567595 |title=Site of the Eleanor Cross|work=OS grid SK9769|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref>  an [[Eleanor Cross]]. At a roundabout at the south end of (what becomes) Lincoln's ''[[High Street, Lincoln|High Street]]'', it exits to the right along ''South Park'', passing the HQ of [[Lincolnshire Fire and Rescue Service]], and meets the B1188 at traffic lights, where it heads left as ''Canwick Road''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/411652 |title=Canwick Road approaching Lincoln City Centre from the south|work=OS grid SK9770|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The A15, Lincoln - geograph.org.uk - 690346.jpg|thumb|Looking south over Pelham Bridge]]\nAt Pelham Bridge<ref>{{cite web|author=<!--lead container name-->50 years of Pelham Bridge |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/lincolnshire/content/articles/2008/06/26/pelhambridge_50_feature.shtml |title=Lincolnshire - Places - 50 years of Pelham Bridge |publisher=BBC |date=26 June 2008 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> (which was opened by the [[Elizabeth II|Queen]] in 1958), it crosses the [[Peterborough to Lincoln Line|railway]], with the [[Lincoln Central railway station|railway station]] on the left, the junction with the start of the [[A57 road|A57]] and [[Ruston (engine builder)|Siemens]] (former [[Alstom]]) factory. It crosses the [[River Witham]], before heading up the hill on the north side of the [[Lincoln Cliff|Lincoln Gap]], and heading in the direction of the A158 as ''Lindum Road'' (for [[Skegness]]), where it is crossed by the [[Viking Way]] near [[Lincoln Minster School]]. As ''Wragby Road'', it passes [[Lincoln Christ's Hospital School]] on the left, then meets the B1308<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/52821 |title=Outer Circle Road, Lincoln|work=OS grid SK9972|publisher=Geograph project |date=13 September 2005 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> near the large Carlton Centre Retail Park. The ''Lincolnshire Poacher''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lincolnshirepoacherpub.co.uk |title=Lincolnshire Poacher - Lincoln |publisher=Lincolnshirepoacherpub.co.uk |date=28 April 2013 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> is on the right hand side and there is a right turn for [[Cherry Willingham]] and [[Reepham, Lincolnshire|Reepham]].\n\nModern traffic routing has taken the road away from the route of [[Ermine Street]] as it passes through Lincoln.\n\n===Lindsey===\n[[File:Ermine Street - geograph.org.uk - 275160.jpg|thumb|left|North of Lincoln near Riseholme]]\n[[File:The A15, Barton-upon-Humber - geograph.org.uk - 696210.jpg|thumb|left|The Humber Bridge looking north]]\n[[File:RAF Scampton front the air.jpeg|thumb|right|The A15 at its 1950s curvature east of Ermine Street around RAF Scampton, seen in March 2016]]\n\nNorth of Lincoln, the A15 enters [[West Lindsey]], and meets the start of the A158 at a roundabout, then runs concurrently<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/275900 |title=A46 Lincoln Ring Road|work=OS grid SK9874|publisher=Geograph project |date=9 November 2006 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> with the [[A46 road|A46]] to the ''Riseholme'' roundabout, where it briefly re-enters the City of Lincoln, then follows<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/275160 |title=Ermine Street|work=OS grid SK9776|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> the [[Roman road]] [[Ermine Street]] past the [[Lincolnshire School of Agriculture|Riseholme College of Agriculture]] on the right, now part of the [[University of Lincoln]], and Lincolnshire Showground<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lincolnshireshowground.co.uk |title=Lincolnshire Events Centre &#124; Lincolnshire Showground &#124; Events Centre |publisher=Lincolnshire Showground |date=18 January 2013 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> to the left.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/89223 |title=Entrance to Lincolnshire Showground from the A15|work=OS grid SK9777|publisher=Geograph project |date=10 December 2005 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> At the end of a {{convert|40|mph}} section is the ''Tillbridge Lane'' roundabout<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/89224 |title=Commercial Buildings at the A1500 A15 junction|work=OS grid SK9778|publisher=Geograph project |date=10 December 2005 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> with the A1500, for [[Gainsborough, Lincolnshire|Gainsborough]]. From here, it used to be straight, but with [[RAF Scampton]] becoming a base for [[V bomber]]s in the 1950s, the runway had to be extended and the road now has a curved diversion to the east. It passes the Scampton primary school<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pollyplatt.lincs.sch.uk |title=Home |publisher=Pollyplatt.lincs.sch.uk | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> and continues<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/416347 |title=Ermine Street|work=OS grid SK9685|publisher=Geograph project |date=28 April 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> past a right turn to [[Normanby by Spital]], on its most straight section, also the parish boundary of many local villages. At the roundabout with the [[A631 road|A631]] at [[Caenby Corner]], there is the [[Total S.A.|Total]] ''Caenby Corner Garage'' just south of [[Spital-in-the-Street]]. Overtaking is difficult as the road, although straight, is undulating with unmarked dips and slow moving farm traffic. There are two right turns for [[Bishop Norton]] and [[Atterby]]. There is a right turn for [[Snitterby]] and a left turn for [[Blyborough]]. At the B1205 staggered crossroads<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/142584 |title=B1205 junction with the A15|work=OS grid SK9696|publisher=Geograph project |date=26 March 2006 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> (for [[Waddingham]] to the east, and [[Grayingham]] to the west), it enters [[North Lincolnshire]].\n\n[[File:A15 near Scawby - geograph.org.uk - 234368.jpg|thumb|Looking north near Scawby]]\n[[File:Start of the M180 - geograph.org.uk - 849005.jpg|thumb|A15/[[M180 motorway|M180]]/[[A180 road (England)|A180]] Barnetby Top Interchange]]\n[[File:A15 exit to Barton-Upon-Humber - geograph.org.uk - 39932.jpg|thumb|Looking north to the A1077 intersection]]\nAt the B1206 crossroads, the old route used to go through [[Hibaldstow]] and [[Brigg]], with the former road to [[Redbourne]] now a cycle route. It passes close to [[Kirton in Lindsey]], home of [[RAF Kirton in Lindsey]] much used in the [[Second World War]] as a [[Battle of Britain airfields|fighter airfield]] in [[No. 12 Group RAF|12 Group]], now home to the [[Trent Valley Gliding Club]]. [[Hibaldstow]] was a wartime fighter airfield<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wartimememories.co.uk/airfields/hibaldstow.html |title=The Wartime Memories Project - RAF Hibaldstow |publisher=Wartimememories.co.uk |accessdate=11 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206173253/http://www.wartimememories.co.uk/airfields/hibaldstow.html |archivedate=6 December 2013 }}</ref> as well, and this is now used as a base for parachuting and parachuting competitions by [[Target Skysports]]. The {{convert|5|mi|adj=on}} \u00a37&nbsp;million Brigg and Redbourne bypass<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/326757 |title=A15 north towards the M180|work=OS grid SK9698|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> was added in December 1989 which follows<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/583632 |title=Lay-by on the A15 west of Hibaldstow|work=OS grid SE9503|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> the old Ermine Street in [[North Lincolnshire]] further than previously, with a much flatter, wider and safer road. This section was the upgraded route of an unclassified road. It crosses the [[Sheffield to Lincoln Line|Sheffield to Cleethorpes railway line]] near the deserted village of [[Gainsthorpe]], passes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/234368 |title=A15 near Scawby|work=OS grid SE9505|publisher=Geograph project |date=6 September 2006 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> near to [[Scawby]], and joining<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/327474 |title=M180 west towards junction 4|work=OS grid SE9606|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> the [[M180 motorway|M180]] at junction 4, near [[Scunthorpe]].  It abandons the Roman alignments at a short spur to the A18 at the ''Briggate Lodge Roundabout'' next to the Forest Pines<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qhotels.co.uk/hotels/forest-pines-near-brigg.aspx |title=Hotels in North Lincolnshire - Forest Pines Hotel & Golf Resort |publisher=QHotels | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> golf club and hotel at [[Broughton, Lincolnshire|Broughton]]. Ermine Street continues north as the B1207, meeting the Humber near [[Winteringham]].\n\nThe route of the A15 now becomes part of the three-laned M180, which was opened on 2 September 1977. The A15 section along Ermine Street was planned to be opened at the same time, but it had to wait twelve years. The buildup of traffic to Grimsby prompted calls for the Brigg bypass for many years, but the [[Flixborough disaster|Flixborough explosion]] of 1974 made it more of an emergency. This section goes under the [[A18 road (Great Britain)|A18]], over the [[River Ancholme]], over the old route of the A15 (B1206) and over the [[South TransPennine|South Trans-Pennine]] railway. At junction 5, the A15 reforms at the dual-grade ''Barnetby Top Interchange'', which is crossed by the [[Viking Way]] and has an exit to [[Elsham, Lincolnshire|Elsham]]. It continues north as a dual carriageway which carries about as little traffic as the M180. The M180 drops to two lanes under this roundabout and continues to [[Grimsby]] and [[Immingham]] as the A180.\n\nThe A15 towards the [[Humber Bridge]], goes directly across the runways of the former [[RAF Bomber Command]] airfield at [[RAF Elsham Wolds]] (where over 1000 of its aircrew were killed), which is now the Elsham Wolds<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/211562 |title=Elsham Wolds - Old Hangar|work=OS grid TA0413|publisher=Geograph project |date=30 July 2006 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> Industrial Estate. The former route of the A15, pre-1978, is now called B1206,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/61208 |title=The old Barton to Brigg Turnpike road|work=OS grid TA0314|publisher=Geograph project |date=4 October 2005 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> and ends at [[New Holland, North Lincolnshire|New Holland]], where the A15 formerly connected with the [[PS Lincoln Castle|Humber Ferry]]. The \u00a35.6&nbsp;million {{convert|6|mi|adj=on}} [[Brigg]] Bypass to [[Barton-upon-Humber]] Bypass (up to where the B1218 crosses)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/494323 |title=A15|work=OS grid TA0219|publisher=Geograph project |date=14 July 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> section opened in June 1978.\n\nThe \u00a32&nbsp;million {{convert|1|mi|adj=on}} Barton-upon-Humber Bypass to Humber Bridge (A1077 interchange)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/39932 |title=A15 exit to Barton-Upon-Humber|work=OS grid TA0220|publisher=Geograph project |date=19 August 2005 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> section opened in September 1978, although some maps show this being open before the southern section to the M180. When this whole section<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/51501 |title=A15|work=OS grid TA0218|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> opened to the GSJ with the A1077 (for [[South Ferriby]]) in 1978, there was no longer any access to the B1218. In the early 1990s, a new interchange<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/51498 |title=A15/B1206 turn-off|work=OS grid TA0316|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> was added with the B1206<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/393180 |title=The Road to Barton|work=OS grid TA0315|publisher=Geograph project |date=8 April 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> (the former A15), which is crossed<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/848959 |title=Crossing the A15|work=OS grid TA0216|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> by the Viking Way, which follows the road for over a mile. The section<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/24043 |title=Humber Bridge from South|work=OS grid TA0222|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> across the [[River Humber|Humber]] was opened on 17 July 1981, by the [[Elizabeth II|Queen]], and was the world's longest single-span bridge until 1997. The tolls<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/452359 |title=Humber Bridge toll plaza|work=OS grid TA0225|publisher=Geograph project | accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> are north of the bridge. It crosses<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/403031 |title=Rail and road|work=OS grid TA0225|publisher=Geograph project |date=16 April 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> the [[A63 road|A63]] and meets a roundabout with [[A164 road|A164]] (for [[Beverley]]) and A1105, then turns left along a short section<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/541875 |title=East or west?|work=OS grid TA0126|publisher=Geograph project |date=1 September 2007 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> of dual-carriageway (former A63) to end at the A63.\n\n==Improvements==\nPresently, the A15 passes through the centre of [[Lincoln, England|Lincoln]], which causes congestion in the city centre. In 2012, planning permission was submitted in order to build a 7.5km bypass which will route traffic to the east of the city. All permissions were granted subsequently by February 2016, and work commenced in May 2016. A number of setbacks have occurred, especially after the loss of [[Carillion]] as the main contractor, after they entered liquidation in January 2018. [[Galliford Try]] were chosen as the replacement contractor. As of March 2020, three roundabouts have opened and a substantial amount of the works have been completed. The project is expected to be completed in Autumn 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lincolnshire.gov.uk/major-projects/lincoln-eastern-bypass|title=Lincoln Eastern Bypass|last=|first=|website=Lincolnshire County Council|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ermine Street]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|A15 road (England)}}\n* [http://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/roadlists/f99/15.shtml The Society for All British Road Enthusiasts' article on A15]\n\n{{UK primary routes 1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1-0015}}\n[[Category:Lincoln, England]]\n[[Category:North Kesteven District]]\n[[Category:Borough of North Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Roads in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:Roads in England]]\n[[Category:Roads in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Roads in Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Roads with a reversible lane]]\n[[Category:South Kesteven District]]\n[[Category:The Deepings]]\n[[Category:Transport in Huntingdonshire]]\n[[Category:Transport in Peterborough]]\n[[Category:Transport in the East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:West Lindsey District]]\n", "name_user": "Mr Harry Masters", "label": "safe", "comment": "I tweaked it", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A15_road_(England)"}
{"title_page": "Jhula", "text_new": "{{for|the Indian cradle|Ghodiyu}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the table at Infobox settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  -->\n|name                   = Jhula\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            = \u091d\u0942\u0932\u093e           \n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = [[Village development committee (Nepal)|Village development committee]]\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  -->\n|image_skyline          =\n|image_caption          =\n|image_flag             =\n|image_seal             =\n|image_map              = <!-- NepalRukumDistrictmap.png -->\n|mapsize                = 300px\n|map_caption            = Map of the village development committees in Rukum District\n|pushpin_map            = Nepal\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        = 300\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Nepal\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Nepal}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Zones of Nepal|Zone]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Rapti Zone]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Districts of Nepal|District]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Rukum District]]\n|<!-- Politics -->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|leader_title1          = <!-- for places with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n|leader_name1           =\n|established_title      = <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       =\n<!-- Area    -->\n|unit_pref                =  <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = <!-- ALL fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n<!-- Population   -->\n|population_as_of               = 2011\n|population_footnotes           = <ref name=\"National Population and Housing Census 2011(Village Development Committee/Municipality)\">{{cite web|title=National Population and Housing Census 2011(Village Development Committee/Municipality)|url=http://cbs.gov.np/image/data/Population/VDC-Municipality%20in%20detail/VDC_Municipality.pdf|website=Government of Nepal|publisher=[[National Planning Commission of Nepal]]|date=November 2012|ref=Central Bureau of Statistics (CBS)|access-date=2017-01-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005234846/http://cbs.gov.np/image/data/Population/VDC-Municipality%20in%20detail/VDC_Municipality.pdf|archive-date=2018-10-05|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               = 3334\n|population_density_km2         = auto\n|population_blank1_title        = Ethnicities\n<!-- General information  -->\n|timezone               = [[Nepal Time]]\n|utc_offset             = +5:45\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|28.67|82.43|type:adm2nd_region:NP_source:unmaps-enwiki|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              = +977-88 \n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|website                = [http://www.ddcrukum.gov.np www.ddcrukum.gov.np]\n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Jhula ''' is a [[Village development committee (Nepal)|village development committee]] in [[Rukum District]] in the [[Rapti Zone]] of western [[Nepal]]. At the time of the [[2011 Nepal census]] it had a population of 3334 people living in 686 individual households.\n\nJhula or, Jhula-pul, also translates into \"bridge\" or \"suspension bridge\" in Hindi language. (2)\n\n2 examples would include the \"[[Lakshman Jhula]]\" bridge and the \"[[Ram Jhula]]\" bridge - both in [[Rishikesh]], [[India]]\n\n==References==\n<references />2: [http://www.meaninghindi.com/english/jhula-pul Jhula-pul Meaning in English]{{Rukum District}}\n\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Rukum District]]\n\n\n{{Rapti-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Indian cradle|Ghodiyu}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the table at Infobox settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  -->\n|name                   = Jhula\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            = \u091d\u0942\u0932\u093e           \n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = [[Village development committee (Nepal)|Village development committee]]\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  -->\n|image_skyline          =\n|image_caption          =\n|image_flag             =\n|image_seal             =\n|image_map              = <!-- NepalRukumDistrictmap.png -->\n|mapsize                = 300px\n|map_caption            = Map of the village development committees in Rukum District\n|pushpin_map            = Nepal\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        = 300\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Nepal\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Nepal}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Zones of Nepal|Zone]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Rapti Zone]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Districts of Nepal|District]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Rukum District]]\n|<!-- Politics -->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|leader_title1          = <!-- for places with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n|leader_name1           =\n|established_title      = <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       =\n<!-- Area    -->\n|unit_pref                =  <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = <!-- ALL fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n<!-- Population   -->\n|population_as_of               = 2011\n|population_footnotes           = <ref name=\"National Population and Housing Census 2011(Village Development Committee/Municipality)\">{{cite web|title=National Population and Housing Census 2011(Village Development Committee/Municipality)|url=http://cbs.gov.np/image/data/Population/VDC-Municipality%20in%20detail/VDC_Municipality.pdf|website=Government of Nepal|publisher=[[National Planning Commission of Nepal]]|date=November 2012|ref=Central Bureau of Statistics (CBS)|access-date=2017-01-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005234846/http://cbs.gov.np/image/data/Population/VDC-Municipality%20in%20detail/VDC_Municipality.pdf|archive-date=2018-10-05|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               = 3334\n|population_density_km2         = auto\n|population_blank1_title        = Ethnicities\n<!-- General information  -->\n|timezone               = [[Nepal Time]]\n|utc_offset             = +5:45\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|28.67|82.43|type:adm2nd_region:NP_source:unmaps-enwiki|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              = +977-88 \n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|website                = [http://www.ddcrukum.gov.np www.ddcrukum.gov.np]\n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Jhula ''' is a [[Village development committee (Nepal)|village development committee]] in [[Rukum District]] in the [[Rapti Zone]] of western [[Nepal]]. At the time of the [[2011 Nepal census]] it had a population of 3334 people living in 686 individual households.\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Rukum District}}\n\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Rukum District]]\n\n\n{{Rapti-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ljlavalle", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a language translation of \"Jhula\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jhula"}
{"title_page": "Daily Mirror", "text_new": "{{short description|British daily tabloid newspaper owned by Reach plc.}}\n{{about|the British newspaper|other uses|Daily Mirror (disambiguation)}}\n{{use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = Daily Mirror\n| image = DailyMirror.jpg\n| caption = Front page on 9 March 2017\n| type = Daily newspaper\n| format = [[Tabloid journalism#Red tops|Red top]]\n| foundation = {{nowrap|{{start date and age|1903|11|2|df=y}}}}\n| owners = [[Reach plc]]\n| political = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| headquarters = [[One Canada Square]], [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| editor = [[Alison Phillips]]\n| website = {{URL|mirror.co.uk}}\n| circulation = 441,934\n| circulation_date = February 2020\n| circulation_ref = <ref>{{cite web |title=Daily Mirror - Data - ABC {{!}} Audit Bureau of Circulations |url=https://www.abc.org.uk/product/576 |website=www.abc.org.uk}}</ref>\n| oclc = 223228477\n}}\nThe '''''Daily Mirror''''' is a British national daily [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] newspaper founded in 1903. It is owned by parent company [[Reach plc]]. From 1985 to 1987, and from 1997 to 2002, the title on its [[Masthead (British publishing)|masthead]] was simply ''The Mirror''. It had an average daily print circulation of 716,923 in December 2016, dropping markedly to 587,803 the following year.<ref name='circ'>{{cite web|title=Print ABCs: Seven UK national newspapers losing print sales at more than 10 per cent year on year|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/print-abcs-seven-uk-national-newspapers-losing-print-sales-at-more-than-10-per-cent-year-on-year/|website=Press Gazette|accessdate=28 January 2017}}</ref> Its Sunday sister paper is the ''[[Sunday Mirror]]''.  Unlike other major British tabloids such as ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' and the ''[[Daily Mail]]'', the ''Mirror'' has no separate Scottish edition; this function is performed by the ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'' and ''[[Sunday Mail (Scotland)|Sunday Mail]]'', which incorporate certain stories from the ''Mirror'' that are of Scottish significance.\n\nOriginally pitched to the middle-class reader, it was converted into a working-class newspaper after 1934, in order to reach a larger audience. The ''Mirror'' has had a number of owners. It was founded by [[Alfred Harmsworth]], who sold it to his brother [[Harold Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Rothermere|Harold Harmsworth]] (from 1914 Lord Rothermere) in 1913. In 1963 a restructuring of the media interests of the Harmsworth family led to the ''Mirror'' becoming a part of [[IPC Media#International Publishing Corporation|International Publishing Corporation]]. During the mid 1960s, daily sales exceeded 5 million copies, a feat never repeated by it or any other daily (non-Sunday) British newspaper since.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928073311/http://www.mmc.gov.uk/rep_pub/reports/1985/fulltext/190c02.pdf United Newspapers PLC and Fleet Holdings PLC]'', [[Monopolies and Mergers Commission]] (1985), pp.5&ndash;16</ref> The ''Mirror'' was owned by [[Robert Maxwell]] between 1984 and 1991. The paper went through a protracted period of crisis after his death before merging with the regional newspaper group Trinity in 1999 to form [[Trinity Mirror]].\n\nDuring the 1930s, the paper was editorially sympathetic to [[Oswald Mosley]] and the [[British Union of Fascists]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/revealed-the-fascist-past-of-the-daily-mirror-77871.html|title=Revealed: the fascist past of the Daily Mirror|date=11 November 2003|website=The Independent}}</ref> The paper has consistently supported the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] since the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945 general election]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2010/may/04/general-election-newspaper-support \"Newspaper support in UK general elections\"], ''The Guardian'', 4 May 2010.  Retrieved 15 September 2015.</ref>\n\n==History==\n===1903\u20131995===\n[[File:Alfred Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Northcliffe - Project Gutenberg eText 15305.jpg|left|thumb|upright|[[Alfred Harmsworth]] (later Lord Northcliffe), founder of the ''Daily Mirror'']]\n''The Daily Mirror'' was launched on 2 November 1903 by [[Alfred Harmsworth]] (later Lord Northcliffe) as a newspaper for women, run by women.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.britannica.com/topic/The-Mirror-British-newspaper |title=The Mirror {{!}} British newspaper |work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=26 December 2017}}</ref> Hence the name: he said, \"I intend it to be really a mirror of feminine life as well on its grave as on its lighter sides&nbsp;... to be entertaining without being frivolous, and serious without being dull\".<ref>''Daily Mirror'' No. 1 (2 November 1903) page 3</ref> It cost one [[Penny (British pre-decimal coin)|penny]] (equivalent to {{Inflation|UK|10 / 24|1903|r=0|fmt=c}}p in {{Inflation-year|UK}}).\n\nIt was not an immediate success and in 1904 Harmsworth decided to turn it into a pictorial newspaper with a broader focus. Harmsworth appointed [[Hamilton Fyfe]] as editor and all of the paper's female journalists were fired. The masthead was changed to ''The Daily Illustrated Mirror'', which ran from 26 January to 27 April 1904 (issues 72 to 150), when it reverted to ''The Daily Mirror''.<ref name=Albion>[[Albion (history journal)|Albion]] (1973) Vol 5, 2-page 150</ref> The first issue of the relaunched paper did not have advertisements on the front page as previously, but instead news text and engraved pictures (of a traitor and an actress), with the promise of photographs inside.<ref>''Daily Mirror'' issue 72, 26 January 1904</ref> Two days later, the price was dropped to one [[Halfpenny (British pre-decimal coin)|halfpenny]] and to the masthead was added: \"A paper for men and women\".<ref>''Daily Illustrated Mirror'' issue 74, 28 January 1904</ref> This combination was more successful: by issue 92, the guaranteed circulation was 120,000 copies<ref>''Daily Illustrated Mirror'' issue 92, 18 February 1904</ref> and by issue 269, it had grown to 200,000:<ref>''Daily Mirror'' issue 269, 13 September 1904</ref> by then the name had reverted and the front page was mainly photographs. Circulation grew to 466,000 making it the second-largest morning newspaper.<ref>''Daily Mirror'' issue 1335, 8 February 1908</ref>\n\nAlfred Harmsworth sold the newspaper to his brother [[Harold Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Rothermere|Harold Harmsworth]] (from 1914 Lord Rothermere) in 1913. In 1917, the price was increased to one penny.<ref name=DM4163>''Daily Mirror'' issue 4163, 26 February 1917</ref> Circulation continued to grow: in 1919, some issues sold more than a million copies a day, making it the largest daily picture paper.<ref name=DM4856>''Daily Mirror'' issue 4856, 19 May 1919</ref> In 1924 the newspaper sponsored the  [[1924 Women's Olympiad]] held at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] in London.\n\n[[File:Lord Rothermere.jpg|right|thumb|upright|[[Harold Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Rothermere]]]]\nLord Rothermere was a friend of [[Benito Mussolini]] and [[Adolf Hitler]], and directed the ''Mirror''{{'}}s editorial stance towards them in the early 1930s.<ref name=\"Griffiths1980\">{{Cite book|last=Griffiths|first=Richard|title=Fellow Travellers of the Right: British Enthusiasts for Nazi Germany, 1933-9|year=1980|publisher=Constable|location=London|isbn=0-09-463460-2|postscript=\".\"}}</ref><ref>Roy Greenslade, [https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2011/dec/06/dailymail-oswald-mosley Don't damn the Daily Mail for its fascist flirtation 80 years ago], [[theguardian.com]] (7 December 2011)</ref> On Monday, 22 January 1934 the ''Daily Mirror'' ran the headline \"Give the Blackshirts a helping hand\" urging readers to join Sir [[Oswald Mosley]]'s [[British Union of Fascists]], and giving the address to which to send membership applications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/revealed-the-fascist-past-of-the-daily-mirror-77871.html|title=Revealed: the fascist past of the Daily Mirror|date=11 November 2003|website=The Independent}}</ref>By the mid-1930s, the ''Mirror'' was struggling \u2013 it and the ''Mail'' were the main casualties of the early 1930s circulation war that saw the ''[[Daily Herald (UK newspaper)|Daily Herald]]'' and the ''[[Daily Express]]'' establish circulations of more than two million, and Rothermere decided to sell his shares in it.\n\nIn 1935 Rothermere sold the paper to H. G. Bartholomew and [[Hugh Cudlipp]].<ref> McKibbin, Ross. ''Classes and Cultures: England 1918-1951''. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1998, p. 406.</ref>  With [[Cecil Harmsworth King|Cecil King]] (Rothermere's nephew) in charge of the paper's finances and Guy Bartholomew as editor, during the late 1930s the ''Mirror'' was transformed from a conservative, middle class newspaper into a [[left-wing politics|left-wing]] paper for the working class.<ref>Adrian Bingham, and Martin Conboy, \"The Daily Mirror and the Creation of a Commercial Popular Language,\" ''Journalism Studies'' (2009) 19#5 pp 639-654.</ref> Partly on the advice of the American advertising agency J. Walter Thompson, the ''Mirror'' became the first British paper to adopt the appearance of the New York tabloids. The headlines became bigger, the stories shorter and the illustrations more abundant.<ref>McKibbin, Ross. ''Classes and Cultures: England 1918-1951''. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1998, p. 506.</ref> By 1939, the publication was selling 1.4&nbsp;million copies a day. In 1937, [[Hugh McClelland (cartoonist)|Hugh McClelland]] introduced his wild Western comic strip ''Beelzebub Jones'' in the ''Daily Mirror''. After taking over as cartoon chief at the ''Mirror'' in 1945,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hS1lAAAAMAAJ&q=%22beelzebub+jones%22&dq=%22beelzebub+jones%22&lr=&num=100&as_brr=0&as_pt=ALLTYPES&pgis=1&redir_esc=y|title=The World encyclopedia of comics|last=Horn|authorlink1=Maurice Horn |first=Maurice |date=1983 |publisher=Chelsea House  |isbn=9780877543237}}</ref> he dropped ''Beelzebub Jones'' and moved on to a variety of new strips.\n\nDuring the Second World War the ''Mirror'' positioned itself as the paper of the ordinary soldier and civilian, and was critical of the political leadership and the established parties. At one stage, the paper was threatened with closure following the publication of a [[Philip Zec]] [[political cartoon|cartoon]] (captioned by [[William Connor]]), which was misinterpreted by [[Winston Churchill]] and [[Herbert Morrison]].<ref name=cassandra>{{cite book |title=Cassandra: Reflections in a Mirror |first=Robert |last=Connor |publisher=Cassell |year =1969 |location =London |isbn= 978-0-304-93341-9}}</ref> In the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945 general election]] the paper strongly supported the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in its eventual landslide victory. In doing so, the paper supported Herbert Morrison, who co-ordinated Labour's campaign, and recruited his former antagonist Philip Zec to reproduce, on the front page, a popular [[VE Day]] cartoon on the morning of the election, suggesting that Labour were the only party who could maintain peace in post-war Britain.<ref name=\"tabloidnation\"/> By the late 1940s, it was selling 4.5&nbsp;million copies a day, outstripping the ''Express''; for some 30 years afterwards, it dominated the British daily newspaper market, selling more than 5 million copies a day at its peak in the mid-1960s.\n\nThe ''Mirror'' was an influential model for German tabloid ''[[Bild]]'', which was founded in 1952 and became Europe's biggest-selling newspaper.<ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/international/0,1518,412021,00.html Sex, Smut and Shock: Bild Zeitung Rules Germany] [[Spiegel Online]] 25 April 2006</ref>\n\n[[File:Daily Mirror 20130413 052.jpg|thumb|Daily Mirror Building (1957-1960) in Langham Place, London]]\n\nIn 1955, the ''Mirror'' and its stablemate the ''Sunday Pictorial'' (later to become the ''Sunday Mirror'') began printing a northern edition in [[Manchester]]. In 1957 it introduced the Andy Capp cartoon, created by Reg Smythe from Hartlepool, in the northern editions.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nThe ''Mirror''{{'s}} mass working class readership had made it the United Kingdom's best-selling daily tabloid newspaper. In 1960, it acquired the ''[[Daily Herald (UK newspaper)|Daily Herald]]'' (the popular daily of the labour movement) when it bought [[Odhams]], in one of a series of takeovers which created the [[IPC Media|International Publishing Corporation]] (IPC). The ''Mirror'' management did not want the ''Herald'' competing with the ''Mirror'' for readers, and in 1964, relaunched it as a mid-market paper, now named ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]''. When it failed to win readers, the ''Sun'' was sold to [[Rupert Murdoch]] \u2013 who immediately relaunched it as a more [[populism|populist]] and sensationalist tabloid and a direct competitor to the ''Mirror''.\n\n<!-- I didn't put this in the \"Famous Features\", as Mirrorscope was short-lived, and not famous! -->\nIn an attempt to cater to a different kind of reader, the ''Mirror'' launched the \"Mirrorscope\" pull-out section on 30 January 1968. The ''[[Press Gazette]]'' commented: \"The ''Daily Mirror'' launched its revolutionary four-page supplement \"Mirrorscope\". The ambitious brief for the supplement, which ran on Wednesdays and Fridays, was to deal with international affairs, politics, industry, science, the arts and business\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=27950 |work=[[Press Gazette]] |title=Back Issues 23.01.03 |date=23 March 2009 |accessdate=19 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090802215955/http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=27950 |archive-date=2 August 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The ''British Journalism Review'' said in 2002 that \"Mirrorscope\" was \"a game attempt to provide serious analysis in the rough and tumble of the tabloids\".<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.bjr.org.uk/data/2002/no4_evans.htm |title=Attacking the devil |work=[[British Journalism Review]] |volume=13 |issue=4 |year=2002 |pages=6\u201314 |access-date=26 July 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201115956/http://www.bjr.org.uk/data/2002/no4_evans.htm |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It failed to attract significant numbers of new readers, and the pull-out section was abandoned, its final issue appearing on 27 August 1974.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nIn 1978, ''The Sun'' overtook the ''Mirror'' in circulation, and in 1984 the ''Mirror'' was sold to [[Robert Maxwell]]. After Maxwell's death in 1991, [[David Montgomery (newspaper executive)|David Montgomery]] became Mirror Group's CEO, and a period of cost-cutting and production changes ensued. The ''Mirror'' went through a protracted period of crisis before merging with the regional newspaper group Trinity to form [[Trinity Mirror]] in 1999. Printing of the ''Daily'' and ''Sunday Mirror'' moved to Trinity Mirror's facilities in Watford and Oldham.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n===1995\u20132004===\n[[File:Daily Mirror front page 24 June 1996.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Front page of the ''Mirror'' 24 June 1996, with headline \"ACHTUNG! SURRENDER For you Fritz, ze Euro 96 Championship is over\", and accompanying contribution from the editor, \"Mirror declares football war on Germany\"]]\nUnder the editorship of [[Piers Morgan]] (from October 1995 to May 2004) the paper saw a number of controversies.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.britannica.com/biography/Piers-Morgan#ref1092939 |title=Piers Morgan {{!}} British journalist and television personality|work=Encyclopedia Britannica |access-date=26 December 2017}}</ref> Morgan was widely criticised and forced to apologise for the headline \"ACHTUNG! SURRENDER For you Fritz, ze Euro 96 Championship is over\" a day before [[England national football team|England]] met [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in a semi-final of the [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 96]] football championships.<ref name=\"IHT\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/06/26/news/26iht-england.t_0.html |title=Oh, Sorry: Tabloids Lose the Soccer War |last=Thomsen |first=Ian |date=26 June 1996 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=3 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Morgan was the subject of an investigation after Suzy Jagger wrote a story in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' revealing that he had bought [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]20,000 worth of shares in the computer company [[Viglen]] soon before the ''Mirror'' 's 'City Slickers' column tipped Viglen as a good buy.<ref name=\"lie\">{{Cite news |title=Mirror editor saw his shares soar after paper tipped company |author=Jagger, Suzy |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=/archive/2000/02/02/nmir02.html |date=2 February 2000 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021122223139/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=%2Farchive%2F2000%2F02%2F02%2Fnmir02.html |archivedate=22 November 2002 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Morgan was found by the [[Press Complaints Commission]] to have breached the Code of Conduct on financial journalism, but kept his job. The 'City Slickers' columnists, [[Anil Bhoyrul]] and [[James Hipwell]], were both found to have committed further breaches of the Code, and were sacked before the inquiry. In 2004, further enquiry by the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] cleared Morgan from any charges.<ref name=\"cleared\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/3792225.stm |title=Morgan cleared after shares probe |work=BBC News |date=10 June 2004}}</ref> On 7 December 2005 Bhoyrul and Hipwell were convicted of conspiracy to breach the Financial Services Act. During the trial it emerged that Morgan had bought \u00a367,000 worth of Viglen shares, emptying his bank account and investing under his wife's name too.<ref name=\"lie2\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/nov/23/business.pressandpublishing |title= Mirror editor 'bought \u00a367,000 of shares before they were tipped' |work=The Guardian |location=London |first=Chris |last=Tryhorn |date=23 November 2005 |accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, the ''Mirror'' attempted to move mid-market, claiming to eschew the more trivial stories of show-business and gossip. The paper changed its masthead logo from red to black (and occasionally blue), in an attempt to dissociate itself from the term \"[[red tops|red top]]\", a term for a sensationalist mass-market tabloid. (On 6 April 2005, the red top came back.) Under then-editor [[Piers Morgan]], the newspaper's editorial stance opposed the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], and ran many front pages critical of the war. It also gave financial support to the [[15 February 2003 anti-war protest]], paying for a large screen and providing thousands of placards. Morgan re-hired [[John Pilger]], who had been sacked during [[Robert Maxwell]]'s ownership of the Mirror titles. Despite such changes, Morgan was unable to halt the paper's decline in circulation, a decline shared by its direct [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] rivals ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' and the ''[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]''.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n\nMorgan was fired from the ''Mirror'' on 14 May 2004 after authorising the newspaper's publication of photographs allegedly showing [[Iraq]]i prisoners being abused by [[British Army]] soldiers from the [[Queen's Lancashire Regiment]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/13/iraq.abuse.statement/index.html |title=Daily Mirror statement in full |publisher=CNN |date=13 May 2004 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20041125053916/http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/13/iraq.abuse.statement/index.html |archivedate=25 November 2004 |accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> Within days the photographs were shown to be fakes. Under the headline \"SORRY.. WE WERE HOAXED\", the ''Mirror'' responded that it had fallen victim to a \"calculated and malicious hoax\" and apologised for the publication of the photographs.<ref>{{Cite news |url = http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/14/iraq.abuse.uk/ |title=Fake abuse photos: Editor quits |publisher=CNN London |date=15 May 2004 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20041012123314/http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/14/iraq.abuse.uk/ |archivedate=12 October 2004 }}</ref>\n\n===2004\u2013present===\nThe ''Mirror''{{'s}} front page on 4 November 2004, after the re-election of [[George W. Bush]] as U.S. President, read \"How can 59,054,087 people be so DUMB?\". It provided a list of states and their alleged average IQ, showing the Bush states all below average intelligence (except for [[Virginia]]), and all [[John Kerry]] states at or above average intelligence. The source for this table was ''[[The Economist]]'',<ref>{{cite news |last=Sutherland |first=John |title=The Axis of Stupidity |work=The Guardian |location =London |date=11 November 2004 |url= https://www.theguardian.com/education/2004/nov/11/highereducation.uselections2004}}</ref> although it was a hoax.<ref>{{cite web |website=[[Snopes]] |title=Fool Me Twice |url= http://www.snopes.com/politics/ballot/stateiq.asp |date=12 November 2004 |accessdate=19 July 2009 }}</ref> [[Richard Wallace (journalist)|Richard Wallace]] became editor in 2004.\n\nOn 30 May 2012, Trinity Mirror announced the merger of the ''Daily Mirror'' and ''Sunday Mirror'' into a single seven-day-a-week title.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/may/30/richard-wallace-tina-weaver-mirror?newsfeed=true |title= Richard Wallace and Tina Weaver depart as Mirror titles go seven-day |accessdate=30 May 2012 |work=The Guardian |location= London |date=30 May 2012 |first=Mark |last=Sweney}}</ref> Richard Wallace and Tina Weaver, the respective editors of the ''Daily Mirror'' and ''Sunday Mirror'', were simultaneously dismissed and [[Lloyd Embley]], editor of ''The People'', appointed as editor of the combined title with immediate effect.<ref>{{cite news |last= Alleyne |first=Richard |title=Daily Mirror to merge with Sunday Mirror as both editors sacked |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/mediatechnologyandtelecoms/media/9299624/Daily-Mirror-to-merge-with-Sunday-Mirror-as-both-editors-sacked.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |accessdate=30 May 2012 |date=30 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Daily Mirror and Sunday Mirror to merge: full statement |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/mediatechnologyandtelecoms/9299655/Daily-Mirror-and-Sunday-Mirror-to-merge-full-statement.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |accessdate=30 May 2012 |date=30 May 2012}}</ref> In 2018, Reach plc acquired the Northern & Shell titles, including the Daily Express, which led to a number of editor moves across the stable. Lloyd Embley was then promoted to editor-in-chief across the entire group, and [[Alison Phillips]] (previously deputy editor-in-chief for the Trinity Mirror titles) was appointed editor of the Daily Mirror.\n\n==Political allegiance==\nSince 1945 the ''Daily Mirror'' has tended to back the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] at general elections.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nOn 3 May 1979, the day of the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|general election]], the ''Daily Mirror'' urged its readers to vote for the governing Labour Party led by [[James Callaghan]].<ref name=\"century\"/> As widely predicted by the opinion polls, Labour lost this election, which was won by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] and saw [[Margaret Thatcher]] become Prime Minister.<ref name=\"century\">{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/2010/04/20/general-election-2010-a-century-of-daily-mirror-front-pages-115875-22198683/ |title=A century of Daily Mirror front pages |work=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=20 April 2010}}</ref> The ''Mirror''{{'}}s continued support of the Labour government was in spite of its falling popularity over the previous few months which had been the result of the [[Winter of Discontent]], where the country was crippled by numerous public sector strikes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/politics97/background/pastelec/ge79.shtml |work=BBC News |title=Politics 97 |date=3 May 1979}}</ref>\n\nBy the time of the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 general election]], Labour support was at a postwar low, partly due to the strong challenge by the recently formed [[SDP-Liberal Alliance]]. Despite this, the ''Daily Mirror'' remained loyal to Labour and urged its readers to vote for the party (now led by [[Michael Foot]]), condemning the Thatcher-led Tory government for its \"waste of our nation\",<ref name=\"century\"/> condemning the rise in unemployment that Thatcher's Conservative government had seen in its first term in power largely due to [[Monetarism|monetarist]] economic policies to reduce inflation, although the government's previously low popularity had dramatically improved since the success of the [[Falklands War|Falklands]] conflict a year earlier.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/basics/4393313.stm |work=BBC News |title=1983: Thatcher triumphs again |date=5 April 2005}}</ref> However, the Tories were re-elected and Labour suffered its worst postwar general election result, only narrowly bettering the SDP-Liberal Alliance in terms of votes whilst winning considerably more seats.<ref name=\"century\"/>\n\nAt the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 general election]], the ''Daily Mirror'' remained loyal to Labour (now led by [[Neil Kinnock]]) and urged its readers \"You know he's right, chuck her out\".<ref name=\"century\"/> By this stage, unemployment was falling and inflation had remained low for several years.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/basics/4393315.stm |work=BBC News |title=1987: Thatcher's third victory |date=5 April 2005}}</ref> As a result, the Tories were re-elected for a third successive term, although Labour did cut the Tory majority slightly.<ref name=\"century\"/>\n\nFor the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]], the ''Daily Mirror'' continued to support Labour, still led by [[Neil Kinnock]]. By this stage [[Margaret Thatcher]] had stepped down and the Tory government was now led by [[John Major]].<ref name=\"century\"/> The election was won by the Tories, although Labour managed to significantly cut the Tory majority to 21 seats compared to the triple-digit figure of the previous two elections, which led to a difficult term for Major. The outcome of this election had been far less predictable than any of the previous three elections, as opinion polls over the previous three years had shown both parties in the lead, although any Labour lead in the polls had been relatively narrow since the Conservative government's change of leader from Thatcher to Major in November 1990, in spite of the onset of a [[Early 1990s recession|recession in 1990]] which had pushed unemployment up again after several years of decline. Labour's credibility was helped by plans including extra [[National Health Service|NHS funding]] and moving away from firm commitments on re-nationalisation to reverse the Conservative policy of privatisation, but its decision to be up-front about tax increases was seen as a key factor in its failure to win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/basics/4393317.stm |work=BBC News |title=1992: Tories win again against odds |date=5 April 2005}}</ref>\n\nBy the time of the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], support for the Labour Party, now led by [[Tony Blair]], in the opinion polls had exceeded that of support for the Tory government (still led by John Major) since late 1992, the government's reduced popularity largely blamed on the failings of [[Black Wednesday]] in September of that year and it had failed to recover popularity in spite of a strong economic recovery and fall in unemployment. A reinvented \"New Labour\" had further improved its credibility under Blair by promising traditional Labour essentials including more funding for healthcare and education, but also promising not to increase income tax and ending its commitment to the nationalisation of leading industries.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/basics/4393323.stm |work=BBC News |title=1997: Labour landslide ends Tory rule |date=15 April 2005}}</ref> The ''Daily Mirror'' urged its readers that their country needed Tony Blair, and to vote Labour.<ref name=\"century\"/> The election produced a Labour landslide and ended the party's 18-year exile from power.\n\nOn 4 May 2010, the newspaper printed a picture of Conservative leader [[David Cameron]] with a giant red cross through his face. The headline read \"How to stop him\" in reference to the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|general election two days later]], thus confirming the ''Daily Mirror''{{'}}s Labour allegiance. The election ended in Britain's first [[hung parliament]] since [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|1974]], but Cameron still became prime minister of the country within days as the Conservatives formed a coalition with the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]. The ''Daily Mirror'' was the only leading national newspaper to remain loyal to Labour and [[Gordon Brown]] at a time when opinion polls showed the party on course for their worst election result since [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.supanet.com/business--money/which-political-parties-do-the-newspapers-support--25923p1.html |title=Which political parties do the newspapers support? |publisher=Supanet}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper was critical of the Liberal Democrats for forming the coalition which enabled the Conservatives to form a new government in 2010, and branded leader [[Nick Clegg]] as Pinickio (alluding to the lying fictional character [[Pinocchio]])<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2011/01/13/clegg-nose-day-join-our-campaign-to-shame-pinickio-nick-clegg-115875-22845966/ |title=Clegg Nose Day \u2013 Join our campaign to shame 'Pinickio' Nick Clegg |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=13 January 2011}}</ref> for going back on numerous pre-election pledges. It has frequently referred to the party as the \"Fib Dems\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/opinion/2011/03/04/security-bill-for-nick-clegg-s-lib-dem-conference-is-more-than-just-coppers-115875-22964255/ |title=Security bill for Nick Clegg's Lib Dem conference is more than just coppers |last=Routledge |first=Paul |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=4 March 2011}}</ref> or \"Lib Dumbs\".<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/opinion/2010/05/19/dumb-and-dumber-115875-22268581/ |title=PMQs shows up the Lib Dumbs |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=19 May 2010}}</ref> The ''Daily Mirror'' endorsed Democratic candidate [[Hillary Clinton]] in the run-up for the 2016 U.S. presidential election.<ref>{{cite news |title=Americans must vote Hillary Clinton for their own sake |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/americans-must-vote-hillary-clinton-9216821 |accessdate=November 8, 2016 |work=Daily Mirror |date=November 7, 2016}}</ref> In 2016 the newspapers asked for [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s resignation \"for the good of Labour and of the country\".\n\nDespite this critical position,  the ''Daily Mirror'' endorsed again the Labour Party in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]].<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/help-corbyn-kick-tories-touch-10278153 |title=Help Corbyn kick the Tories into touch - Voice of the Mirror |date=22 April 2017 |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location= London |access-date=19 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Famous features==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=January 2018}}\n* Cartoon strips \"[[Pip, Squeak and Wilfred]]\" (1919\u201356), \"[[Jane (comic strip)|Jane]]\" (1932\u201359), \"[[Garth (comic strip)|Garth]]\" (1943\u201397, reprints 2011), \"[[Just Jake]]\" (1938\u201352), \"[[Andy Capp]]\" (1957\u2013), and \"[[The Perishers]]\" (1955\u20132006 and later reprints).\n* \"The Old Codgers\", a fictional pair who commented on the letters page from 1935 to 1990.<ref name=Gascoigne>[http://www.historyworld.net/Articles/PlainTextArticles.asp?aid=zah&pid=617 Bamber Gascoigne (1993) ''Encyclopedia of Britain'' (Macmillan)]</ref>\n* Chalky White, who would wander around various British seaside resorts waiting to be recognised by Mirror readers (an obscured photo of him having been published in that day's paper). Anyone who recognised him would have to repeat some phrase along the lines of \"[[You are X and I claim my five pounds|To my delight, it's Chalky White]]\" to win \u00a35. The name continues to be used on the cartoons page, as [[Andy Capp]]'s best friend.\n* \"Shock issues\" intended to highlight a particular news story.\n* The columnist [[William Connor|Cassandra]] (1935\u201367).\n* \"Dear Marje\", a problem page by agony aunt [[Marjorie Proops]].\n* Investigative reporting by [[Paul Foot (campaigner)|Paul Foot]] and [[John Pilger]] (including the latter's expos\u00e9 of the atrocities of the [[Khmer Rouge]] in Cambodia).\n* \"The Shopping Basket\". Starting in the mid-1970s, the paper monitored the cost of a \u00a35 basket of shopping to see how it increased in price over the years.\n\n===Blue issue===\nOn 2 April 1996, the ''Daily Mirror'' was printed entirely on blue paper.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} This was done as a marketing exercise with [[Pepsi|Pepsi-Cola]], who on the same day had decided to relaunch their cans with a blue design instead of the traditional red and white logo.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Libel, contempt of court, errors and criticism==\n[[File:The Daily Mirror - Sorry We Were Hoaxed.jpg|frame|right|upright|alt=Sorry We Were hoaxed|Front page of the ''Daily Mirror'' after publishing faked photographs.]]\n* In the 1959 ''[[Liberace v Daily Mirror]]'' case, [[Liberace]] sued the ''Mirror'' for libel. [[William Connor]] had written a pseudonymous column hinting that the American entertainer was a homosexual; homosexuality was illegal in Britain at the time. The jury found in Liberace's favour and he received \u00a38,000 in damage (estimated at around \u00a3500,000 in 2009).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Greenslade |first1=Roy |title=The meaning of 'fruit': how the Daily Mirror libelled Liberace |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2009/may/26/daily-mirror-medialaw |accessdate=26 September 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=26 May 2009}}</ref>\n* In 1991, shortly after the death of [[Queen (band)|Queen]]<nowiki/>'s lead singer [[Freddie Mercury]], the ''Daily Mirror'' ran a [[homophobia|homophobic]] column by [[Joe Haines (journalist)|Joe Haines]] which contained extensive insults towards Mercury, [[HIV/AIDS]] victims, and homosexuals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dungeonpeaches.tumblr.com/post/85982644289/queenmania-this-repulsive-article-which|title=queenmania: This repulsive article, which...|website=random thoughts: queen, life, and everything}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.queencuttings.com/dblog/articolo.asp?articolo=309|title=Dark Side of Freddie|date=28 November 1991|website=Queencuttings|access-date=3 June 2018}}</ref> The article prompted an open letter in condemnation from folk singer [[Lal Waterson]], later recorded as a song by her sister [[Norma Waterson|Norma]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://rbhsjukebox.wordpress.com/2013/11/26/song-of-the-day-november-26-lal-watersons-reply-to-joe-haines/|title=Song of the Day, November 26: Lal Waterson\u2019s Reply to Joe Haines|date=2013-11-26|work=Music and Meaning: The RBHS Jukebox|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* In December 1992, Scottish politician [[George Galloway]] won libel damages from the ''Daily Mirror'' and its Scottish sister the ''Daily Record'', who had falsely accused him of making malicious allegations about their foreign editor [[Nicholas Davies (journalist)|Nicholas Davies]]. Galloway had used [[parliamentary privilege]] to call for an independent investigation into allegations about Davies made in the book [[The Samson Option: Israel's Nuclear Arsenal and American Foreign Policy|''The Samson Option'']].<ref>{{cite news |title=Scottish MP wins libel damages |url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12589730.Scottish_MP_wins_libel_damages/ |accessdate=3 October 2018 |work=The Herald |date=22 December 1992}}</ref>\n* In May 2004, the ''Daily Mirror'' published what it claimed were photos of British soldiers abusing Iraqi prisoners at an unspecified location in Iraq. The decision to publish the photos, subsequently shown to be hoaxes, led to Piers Morgan's sacking as editor of the paper on 14 May 2004. The ''Daily Mirror'' then stated that it was the subject of a \"calculated and malicious hoax\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/14/iraq.abuse.uk/ |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20041012123314/http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/14/iraq.abuse.uk/ |archivedate=12 October 2004 |title= Fake abuse photos: Editor quits |date=15 May 2004 |publisher=CNN}}</ref> The newspaper issued a statement apologising for the printing of the pictures. The paper's deputy editor, [[Des Kelly]], took over as acting editor during the crisis. The tabloid's rival, ''The Sun'', offered a \u00a350,000 reward for the arrest and conviction of those accused of faking the ''Mirror'' photographs.\n* In June 2004, American model [[Caprice Bourret]] won a libel case against the ''Daily Mirror'' for an article in April that year which falsely claimed that her acting career had failed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Caprice wins libel case over acting claims |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1464662/Caprice-wins-libel-case-over-acting-claims.html |accessdate=3 October 2018 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=16 June 2004}}</ref>\n* In November 2007, the ''Daily Mirror'' paid damages to Sir Andrew Green after having likened him and his group [[MigrationWatch UK]] to the [[Ku Klux Klan]] and [[Nazi Party]] in September of that year. The newspaper admitted that such allegations were \"untrue\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Sir Andrew Green - an apology|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/sir-andrew-green---an-apology-523654|work=Daily Mirror|date=26 November 2007}}</ref>\n* In February 2008 both the ''Daily'' and the ''Sunday Mirror'' implied that TV presenter [[Kate Garraway]] was having an affair. She sued for [[Defamation#United Kingdom|libel]], receiving an apology and compensation payment in April 2008.<ref>{{cite news\n|title= GMTV Kate wins 'affair' libel award\n|work=[[Sunday Express]] | location = London\n|url= http://www.dailyexpress.co.uk/posts/view/40871\n|date=10 April 2008\n|accessdate=17 July 2009\n}}</ref>\n* On 18 September 2008, David Anderson, a British sports journalist writing for the ''Mirror'', repeated a claim deriving from vandalism on Wikipedia's entry for Cypriot football team [[AC Omonia]], which asserted that their fans were called \"The Zany Ones\" and liked to wear hats made from discarded shoes. The claim was part of Anderson's match preview ahead of AC Omonia's game with [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], which appeared in the web and print versions of the ''Mirror'', with the nickname also quoted in subsequent editions on 19 September.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shoe hat hoax trips up Mirror |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/mediamonkeyblog/2008/sep/23/mirror.digitalmedia |accessdate=27 October 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=23 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=McCauley |first1=Ciaran |title=Wikipedia hoaxes: From Breakdancing to Bilcholim |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-37523772 |accessdate=27 October 2019 |work=BBC News |date=3 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Mirror journalist caught by Wikipedia hoax |url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/mirror-journalist-caught-by-wikipedia-hoax/ |accessdate=27 October 2019 |work=Press Gazette |date=23 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Wiki warning: sniff out the Omonia |url=https://www.sportsjournalists.co.uk/sport-on-the-web/wiki-warning-sniff-out-the-omonia/ |accessdate=27 October 2019 |publisher=Sports Journalists' Association |date=23 September 2008}}</ref>\n* In November 2009, the ''Mirror'' paid \"substantial libel damages\" to Portuguese footballer [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] after it admitted that a story about him becoming highly intoxicated in a Hollywood nightclub was untrue.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cristiano Ronaldo wins libel damages against Daily Mirror |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/players/cristiano-ronaldo/6533183/Cristiano-Ronaldo-wins-libel-damages-against-Daily-Mirror.html |accessdate=3 October 2018 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=9 November 2009}}</ref>\n* On 12 May 2011, the [[High Court of England and Wales]] granted the [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] permission to bring a case for contempt against ''The Sun'' and the ''Daily Mirror'' for the way they had reported on the arrest of a person of interest in the [[Murder of Joanna Yeates]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-13371918 |title=Sun and Mirror in contempt case over Jo Yeates stories |work=BBC News |date=12 May 2011 |accessdate=12 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-14024079 |title= Sun and Mirror accused of Jo Yeates contempt |work=BBC News |date=5 July 2011 |accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> On 29 July, the Court ruled that both newspapers had been in contempt of court, fining the ''Daily Mirror'' \u00a350,000 and ''The Sun'' \u00a318,000.<ref>{{cite news |last=Halliday |first=Josh |title=Sun and Mirror fined for contempt of court in Christopher Jefferies articles |url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jul/29/sun-daily-mirror-guilty-contempt |accessdate=29 July 2011 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=29 July 2011}}</ref>\n* In October 2013, a defamation case brought by the Irish airline [[Ryanair]] against the ''Daily Mirror'' was settled out of court. The ''Mirror'' had repeated allegations about the airline's safety from a [[Channel 4]] documentary which were not reflected by its most recent evaluation by the [[Irish Aviation Authority]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ryanair settles defamation action against Daily Mirror out of court |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2013/1025/482635-ryanair-libel/ |accessdate=3 October 2018 |website=RT\u00c9 |date=25 October 2013}}</ref>\n* On 19 July 2011 the ''Mirror'' published an article labelling comedian [[Frankie Boyle]] as a racist. He later sued for defamation and libel, winning \u00a354,650 in damages and a further \u00a34,250 for a claim about his departure from ''[[Mock the Week]]''. The ''Mirror'' had argued he was \"forced to quit\" but this was found to be libellous by the court.<ref>{{cite news |title=BBC News on Frankie Boyle lawsuit |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-20033097 |accessdate=22 October 2012 |work=BBC News |date=22 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Preece |first=Rob |title=Comedian Frankie Boyle wins \u00a354,000 libel payout after being branded a racist by the Daily Mirror |url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2221486/Frankie-Boyle-Comedian-wins-54-000-libel-payout-branded-racist-Daily-Mirror.html?ITO=1490 |accessdate=22 October 2012 |newspaper=Daily Mail |date=22 October 2012}}</ref>\n* On 20 March 2017 the ''Mirror'' painted the traditional Russian pancake celebration [[Maslenitsa]] as a [[Hooligan]] training ground. One of the centuries-old tradition in this Russian festival is \u201cwall-to-wall\u201d (\u2018[[:ru:\u0421\u0442\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0443|stenka na stenku]]\u2019, Ru) which is sparring between men dressed in traditional folk clothes. This tradition was wrongly represented by the ''Mirror'' in the pictures and text, labelled as violent acts and living in fear without giving context or any information about this Russian traditional festival at all. The ''Mirror'' article was titled \u201cRussia's Ultra yobs infiltrated amid warnings England fans could be KILLED at [[World Cup 2018|World Cup]].\u201d, and received negative receptions from Russian media, also being described as [[fake news]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Brits scared about pancake battles Gazeta.ru|url=https://www.gazeta.ru/sport/2017/03/21/a_10587857.shtml|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fake news del Mirror, il Carnevale russo diventa allenamento per uccidere|url=https://it.sputniknews.com/mondo/201703214231272-lotta-pugno-mirror-mondiali-russi/|accessdate=21 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UK tabloid distorts traditional Russian pancake festival into \u2018Ultra\u2019 football thug fights|url=https://www.rt.com/sport/381611-russian-pancake-festival-football-thug-fights/|accessdate=21 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Daily Mirror misleads with wrong pictures for article on football 'Ultras' in Russia|url=http://tass.com/sport/936675|accessdate=21 March 2017}}</ref> The organisers of the traditional Russian folk festival event are looking to sue the ''Daily Mirror'', it is reported later.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018We\u2019re looking to sue Daily Mirror\u2019 \u2013 Russian pancake festival fight organizers on hooligan claims|url=https://www.rt.com/sport/381767-russian-hooligans-daily-mirror/|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref> Representatives of the ''Daily Mirror'' acknowledged that the original material of the publication about Russian Hooligans was incorrectly illustrated with images of the traditional festival. In the updated version of the article the newspaper continues to insist that the photographed people were hooligans in the pictures, but gives no evidence of their participation in the festival.<ref>{{cite web|title=Daily Mirror acknowledged incorrectly illustrated text about world Cup fans|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?sl=ru&tl=en&js=y&prev=_t&hl=de&ie=UTF-8&u=https%3A%2F%2Fria.ru%2Fmediawars%2F20170321%2F1490511385.html&edit-text=|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Significant staff members==\n\n===Editors===\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n:1903 to 1904: [[Mary Howarth (newspaper editor)|Mary Howarth]]\n:1904 to 1907: [[Hamilton Fyfe]]\n:1907 to 1915: [[Alexander Kenealy]]\n:1915 to 1916: [[Ed Flynn (journalist)|Ed Flynn]]\n:1916 to 1929: [[Alexander Campbell (journalist)|Alexander Campbell]]\n:1929 to 1931: [[Cameron Hogg]]\n:1931 to 1934: [[Leigh Brownlee]]\n:1934 to 1948: [[Cecil Thomas (journalist)|Cecil Thomas]]\n:1948 to 1953: [[Silvester Bolam]]\n:1953 to 1961: [[Jack Nener]]\n:1961 to 1971: [[Lee Howard (journalist)|Lee Howard]]\n:1971 to 1974: [[Tony Miles (journalist)|Tony Miles]]\n:1974 to 1975: [[Michael Christiansen]]\n:1975 to 1985: [[Mike Molloy]]\n:1985 to 1990: [[Richard Stott]]\n:1990 to 1991: [[Roy Greenslade]]\n:1991 to 1992: [[Richard Stott]]\n:1992 to 1994: [[David Banks (journalist)|David Banks]]\n:1994 to 1995: [[Colin Myler]]\n:1995 to 2004: [[Piers Morgan]]\n:2004 to 2012: [[Richard Wallace (journalist)|Richard Wallace]]\n:2012 to 2016: [[Lloyd Embley]]\n:2016 to 2018: [[Allan Bryce]]\n:2018 to date: [[Alison Phillips]]\n{{div col end}}\n\nSource: ''Tabloid Nation''<ref name=\"tabloidnation\">{{cite book |first=Chris |last=Horrie |title=Tabloid Nation: From the Birth of the Mirror to the Death of the Tabloid Newspaper |year = 2003 |publisher=Andr\u00e9 Deutsch |page=248 |isbn=978-0-233-00012-1}}</ref>\n\n===Notable columnists===\nNotable former and current columnists of the ''Daily Mirror'' include:\n* [[The 3AM Girls]] (gossip columnists)\n*[[Anne Robinson]] (columnist and deputy editor)\n* [[William Connor]] (opinion under the pseudonym ''Cassandra'' (1935\u20131967))\n* [[Caradoc Evans]] (1917\u20131923)\n* [[Richard Hammond]] (motoring and Saturday columnist)\n* [[Oliver Holt]] (sports columnist)\n* [[Kevin Maguire (journalist)|Kevin Maguire]] (UK politics)\n* [[Penman & Greenwood]] (investigators)\n* [[Fiona Phillips]] (Saturday columnist)\n* [[Brian Reade]] (Thursday columnist; also does a sports column on Saturdays)\n* [[Keith Waterhouse]] (largely humorous (1970\u20131986, previously a reporter.)\n* [[Chris Hughes (journalist)|Chris Hughes]] (security and defence)\n* [[Geoffrey Goodman]] (1969\u20131986)\n\n==Awards==\n''The Daily Mirror'' won \"Newspaper of the Year\" in 2002 at the [[British Press Awards]]. It won \"Scoop of the Year\" in 2003 (\"3am\", 'Sven and Ulrika'), 2004 (Ryan Parry, 'Intruder at the Palace'), 2006 and 2007 (both Stephen Moyes).<ref name=gazetteroll>''[[Press Gazette]]'', [http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/hybrid.asp?typeCode=99&navcode=92# Roll of Honour]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616181807/http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/hybrid.asp?typeCode=99&navcode=92 |date=16 June 2011 }}. Retrieved 24 July 2011</ref> The ''Mirror'' won \"Team of the Year\" in 2001 ('Railtrack'), 2002 ('War on the World: World against Terrorism'), 2003 ('Soham'), and 2006 ('London bombings'); and \"Front Page of the Year\" in 2007.<ref name=gazetteroll/> The ''Mirror'' also won the \"Cudlipp Award\" in 2002, 2003, 2004 and 2010.<ref name=gazetteroll/>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Wharf (newspaper)|The Wharf]]'', sister newspaper for the [[Isle of Dogs]].\n* [[Daily Mirror Silver Cup|''Daily Mirror'' Silver Cup]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{Cite journal| last=Morgan |first=Piers |url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/13/iraq.abuse.statement/index.html |title=Daily Mirror statement in full |publisher=CNN World |date=13 May 2004 |accessdate=28 November 2005| postscript=<!-- Bot inserted parameter. Either remove it; or change its value to \".\" for the cite to end in a \".\", as necessary. -->{{inconsistent citations}} |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041125053916/http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/13/iraq.abuse.statement/index.html |archivedate=25 November 2004}}\n* {{Cite journal| url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/14/iraq.abuse.uk/ | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041012123314/http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/14/iraq.abuse.uk/ | archivedate=12 October 2004 |title=Fake abuse photos: Editor quits| publisher=CNN |publication-place=London |date=15 May 2004 |accessdate=27 November 2005| postscript=<!-- Bot inserted parameter. Either remove it; or change its value to \".\" for the cite to end in a \".\", as necessary. -->{{inconsistent citations}}}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Daily Mirror}}\n* {{Official website|www.mirror.co.uk|mobile=m.mirror.co.uk}}\n* {{PM20|FID=co/055734|TEXT=Documents and clippings about|NAME=}}\n\n{{Daily Mirror editors}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Trinity Mirror}}\n{{Media in the United Kingdom|newsmag}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:National newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Reach plc]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1903]]\n[[Category:1903 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in London]]\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British daily tabloid newspaper owned by Reach plc.}}\n{{about|the British newspaper|other uses|Daily Mirror (disambiguation)}}\n{{use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = Daily Mirror\n| image = DailyMirror.jpg\n| caption = Front page on 9 March 2017\n| type = Daily newspaper\n| format = [[Tabloid journalism#Red tops|Red top]]\n| foundation = {{nowrap|{{start date and age|1903|11|2|df=y}}}}\n| owners = [[Reach plc]]\n| political = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| headquarters = [[One Canada Square]], [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| editor = [[Alison Phillips]]\n| website = {{URL|mirror.co.uk}}\n| circulation = 463,256 daily\n| circulation_date = October 2019\n| circulation_ref = <ref>{{cite web |title=Daily Mirror - Data - ABC {{!}} Audit Bureau of Circulations |url=https://www.abc.org.uk/product/576 |website=www.abc.org.uk}}</ref>\n| oclc = 223228477\n}}\nThe '''''Daily Mirror''''' is a British national daily [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] newspaper founded in 1903. It is owned by parent company [[Reach plc]]. From 1985 to 1987, and from 1997 to 2002, the title on its [[Masthead (British publishing)|masthead]] was simply ''The Mirror''. It had an average daily print circulation of 716,923 in December 2016, dropping markedly to 587,803 the following year.<ref name='circ'>{{cite web|title=Print ABCs: Seven UK national newspapers losing print sales at more than 10 per cent year on year|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/print-abcs-seven-uk-national-newspapers-losing-print-sales-at-more-than-10-per-cent-year-on-year/|website=Press Gazette|accessdate=28 January 2017}}</ref> Its Sunday sister paper is the ''[[Sunday Mirror]]''.  Unlike other major British tabloids such as ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' and the ''[[Daily Mail]]'', the ''Mirror'' has no separate Scottish edition; this function is performed by the ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'' and ''[[Sunday Mail (Scotland)|Sunday Mail]]'', which incorporate certain stories from the ''Mirror'' that are of Scottish significance.\n\nOriginally pitched to the middle-class reader, it was converted into a working-class newspaper after 1934, in order to reach a larger audience. The ''Mirror'' has had a number of owners. It was founded by [[Alfred Harmsworth]], who sold it to his brother [[Harold Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Rothermere|Harold Harmsworth]] (from 1914 Lord Rothermere) in 1913. In 1963 a restructuring of the media interests of the Harmsworth family led to the ''Mirror'' becoming a part of [[IPC Media#International Publishing Corporation|International Publishing Corporation]]. During the mid 1960s, daily sales exceeded 5 million copies, a feat never repeated by it or any other daily (non-Sunday) British newspaper since.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928073311/http://www.mmc.gov.uk/rep_pub/reports/1985/fulltext/190c02.pdf United Newspapers PLC and Fleet Holdings PLC]'', [[Monopolies and Mergers Commission]] (1985), pp.5&ndash;16</ref> The ''Mirror'' was owned by [[Robert Maxwell]] between 1984 and 1991. The paper went through a protracted period of crisis after his death before merging with the regional newspaper group Trinity in 1999 to form [[Trinity Mirror]].\n\nDuring the 1930s, the paper was editorially sympathetic to [[Oswald Mosley]] and the [[British Union of Fascists]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/revealed-the-fascist-past-of-the-daily-mirror-77871.html|title=Revealed: the fascist past of the Daily Mirror|date=11 November 2003|website=The Independent}}</ref> The paper has consistently supported the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] since the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945 general election]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2010/may/04/general-election-newspaper-support \"Newspaper support in UK general elections\"], ''The Guardian'', 4 May 2010.  Retrieved 15 September 2015.</ref>\n\n==History==\n===1903\u20131995===\n[[File:Alfred Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Northcliffe - Project Gutenberg eText 15305.jpg|left|thumb|upright|[[Alfred Harmsworth]] (later Lord Northcliffe), founder of the ''Daily Mirror'']]\n''The Daily Mirror'' was launched on 2 November 1903 by [[Alfred Harmsworth]] (later Lord Northcliffe) as a newspaper for women, run by women.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.britannica.com/topic/The-Mirror-British-newspaper |title=The Mirror {{!}} British newspaper |work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=26 December 2017}}</ref> Hence the name: he said, \"I intend it to be really a mirror of feminine life as well on its grave as on its lighter sides&nbsp;... to be entertaining without being frivolous, and serious without being dull\".<ref>''Daily Mirror'' No. 1 (2 November 1903) page 3</ref> It cost one [[Penny (British pre-decimal coin)|penny]] (equivalent to {{Inflation|UK|10 / 24|1903|r=0|fmt=c}}p in {{Inflation-year|UK}}).\n\nIt was not an immediate success and in 1904 Harmsworth decided to turn it into a pictorial newspaper with a broader focus. Harmsworth appointed [[Hamilton Fyfe]] as editor and all of the paper's female journalists were fired. The masthead was changed to ''The Daily Illustrated Mirror'', which ran from 26 January to 27 April 1904 (issues 72 to 150), when it reverted to ''The Daily Mirror''.<ref name=Albion>[[Albion (history journal)|Albion]] (1973) Vol 5, 2-page 150</ref> The first issue of the relaunched paper did not have advertisements on the front page as previously, but instead news text and engraved pictures (of a traitor and an actress), with the promise of photographs inside.<ref>''Daily Mirror'' issue 72, 26 January 1904</ref> Two days later, the price was dropped to one [[Halfpenny (British pre-decimal coin)|halfpenny]] and to the masthead was added: \"A paper for men and women\".<ref>''Daily Illustrated Mirror'' issue 74, 28 January 1904</ref> This combination was more successful: by issue 92, the guaranteed circulation was 120,000 copies<ref>''Daily Illustrated Mirror'' issue 92, 18 February 1904</ref> and by issue 269, it had grown to 200,000:<ref>''Daily Mirror'' issue 269, 13 September 1904</ref> by then the name had reverted and the front page was mainly photographs. Circulation grew to 466,000 making it the second-largest morning newspaper.<ref>''Daily Mirror'' issue 1335, 8 February 1908</ref>\n\nAlfred Harmsworth sold the newspaper to his brother [[Harold Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Rothermere|Harold Harmsworth]] (from 1914 Lord Rothermere) in 1913. In 1917, the price was increased to one penny.<ref name=DM4163>''Daily Mirror'' issue 4163, 26 February 1917</ref> Circulation continued to grow: in 1919, some issues sold more than a million copies a day, making it the largest daily picture paper.<ref name=DM4856>''Daily Mirror'' issue 4856, 19 May 1919</ref> In 1924 the newspaper sponsored the  [[1924 Women's Olympiad]] held at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] in London.\n\n[[File:Lord Rothermere.jpg|right|thumb|upright|[[Harold Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Rothermere]]]]\nLord Rothermere was a friend of [[Benito Mussolini]] and [[Adolf Hitler]], and directed the ''Mirror''{{'}}s editorial stance towards them in the early 1930s.<ref name=\"Griffiths1980\">{{Cite book|last=Griffiths|first=Richard|title=Fellow Travellers of the Right: British Enthusiasts for Nazi Germany, 1933-9|year=1980|publisher=Constable|location=London|isbn=0-09-463460-2|postscript=\".\"}}</ref><ref>Roy Greenslade, [https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2011/dec/06/dailymail-oswald-mosley Don't damn the Daily Mail for its fascist flirtation 80 years ago], [[theguardian.com]] (7 December 2011)</ref> On Monday, 22 January 1934 the ''Daily Mirror'' ran the headline \"Give the Blackshirts a helping hand\" urging readers to join Sir [[Oswald Mosley]]'s [[British Union of Fascists]], and giving the address to which to send membership applications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/revealed-the-fascist-past-of-the-daily-mirror-77871.html|title=Revealed: the fascist past of the Daily Mirror|date=11 November 2003|website=The Independent}}</ref>By the mid-1930s, the ''Mirror'' was struggling \u2013 it and the ''Mail'' were the main casualties of the early 1930s circulation war that saw the ''[[Daily Herald (UK newspaper)|Daily Herald]]'' and the ''[[Daily Express]]'' establish circulations of more than two million, and Rothermere decided to sell his shares in it.\n\nIn 1935 Rothermere sold the paper to H. G. Bartholomew and [[Hugh Cudlipp]].<ref> McKibbin, Ross. ''Classes and Cultures: England 1918-1951''. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1998, p. 406.</ref>  With [[Cecil Harmsworth King|Cecil King]] (Rothermere's nephew) in charge of the paper's finances and Guy Bartholomew as editor, during the late 1930s the ''Mirror'' was transformed from a conservative, middle class newspaper into a [[left-wing politics|left-wing]] paper for the working class.<ref>Adrian Bingham, and Martin Conboy, \"The Daily Mirror and the Creation of a Commercial Popular Language,\" ''Journalism Studies'' (2009) 19#5 pp 639-654.</ref> Partly on the advice of the American advertising agency J. Walter Thompson, the ''Mirror'' became the first British paper to adopt the appearance of the New York tabloids. The headlines became bigger, the stories shorter and the illustrations more abundant.<ref>McKibbin, Ross. ''Classes and Cultures: England 1918-1951''. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1998, p. 506.</ref> By 1939, the publication was selling 1.4&nbsp;million copies a day. In 1937, [[Hugh McClelland (cartoonist)|Hugh McClelland]] introduced his wild Western comic strip ''Beelzebub Jones'' in the ''Daily Mirror''. After taking over as cartoon chief at the ''Mirror'' in 1945,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hS1lAAAAMAAJ&q=%22beelzebub+jones%22&dq=%22beelzebub+jones%22&lr=&num=100&as_brr=0&as_pt=ALLTYPES&pgis=1&redir_esc=y|title=The World encyclopedia of comics|last=Horn|authorlink1=Maurice Horn |first=Maurice |date=1983 |publisher=Chelsea House  |isbn=9780877543237}}</ref> he dropped ''Beelzebub Jones'' and moved on to a variety of new strips.\n\nDuring the Second World War the ''Mirror'' positioned itself as the paper of the ordinary soldier and civilian, and was critical of the political leadership and the established parties. At one stage, the paper was threatened with closure following the publication of a [[Philip Zec]] [[political cartoon|cartoon]] (captioned by [[William Connor]]), which was misinterpreted by [[Winston Churchill]] and [[Herbert Morrison]].<ref name=cassandra>{{cite book |title=Cassandra: Reflections in a Mirror |first=Robert |last=Connor |publisher=Cassell |year =1969 |location =London |isbn= 978-0-304-93341-9}}</ref> In the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945 general election]] the paper strongly supported the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in its eventual landslide victory. In doing so, the paper supported Herbert Morrison, who co-ordinated Labour's campaign, and recruited his former antagonist Philip Zec to reproduce, on the front page, a popular [[VE Day]] cartoon on the morning of the election, suggesting that Labour were the only party who could maintain peace in post-war Britain.<ref name=\"tabloidnation\"/> By the late 1940s, it was selling 4.5&nbsp;million copies a day, outstripping the ''Express''; for some 30 years afterwards, it dominated the British daily newspaper market, selling more than 5 million copies a day at its peak in the mid-1960s.\n\nThe ''Mirror'' was an influential model for German tabloid ''[[Bild]]'', which was founded in 1952 and became Europe's biggest-selling newspaper.<ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/international/0,1518,412021,00.html Sex, Smut and Shock: Bild Zeitung Rules Germany] [[Spiegel Online]] 25 April 2006</ref>\n\n[[File:Daily Mirror 20130413 052.jpg|thumb|Daily Mirror Building (1957-1960) in Langham Place, London]]\n\nIn 1955, the ''Mirror'' and its stablemate the ''Sunday Pictorial'' (later to become the ''Sunday Mirror'') began printing a northern edition in [[Manchester]]. In 1957 it introduced the Andy Capp cartoon, created by Reg Smythe from Hartlepool, in the northern editions.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nThe ''Mirror''{{'s}} mass working class readership had made it the United Kingdom's best-selling daily tabloid newspaper. In 1960, it acquired the ''[[Daily Herald (UK newspaper)|Daily Herald]]'' (the popular daily of the labour movement) when it bought [[Odhams]], in one of a series of takeovers which created the [[IPC Media|International Publishing Corporation]] (IPC). The ''Mirror'' management did not want the ''Herald'' competing with the ''Mirror'' for readers, and in 1964, relaunched it as a mid-market paper, now named ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]''. When it failed to win readers, the ''Sun'' was sold to [[Rupert Murdoch]] \u2013 who immediately relaunched it as a more [[populism|populist]] and sensationalist tabloid and a direct competitor to the ''Mirror''.\n\n<!-- I didn't put this in the \"Famous Features\", as Mirrorscope was short-lived, and not famous! -->\nIn an attempt to cater to a different kind of reader, the ''Mirror'' launched the \"Mirrorscope\" pull-out section on 30 January 1968. The ''[[Press Gazette]]'' commented: \"The ''Daily Mirror'' launched its revolutionary four-page supplement \"Mirrorscope\". The ambitious brief for the supplement, which ran on Wednesdays and Fridays, was to deal with international affairs, politics, industry, science, the arts and business\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=27950 |work=[[Press Gazette]] |title=Back Issues 23.01.03 |date=23 March 2009 |accessdate=19 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090802215955/http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=27950 |archive-date=2 August 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The ''British Journalism Review'' said in 2002 that \"Mirrorscope\" was \"a game attempt to provide serious analysis in the rough and tumble of the tabloids\".<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.bjr.org.uk/data/2002/no4_evans.htm |title=Attacking the devil |work=[[British Journalism Review]] |volume=13 |issue=4 |year=2002 |pages=6\u201314 |access-date=26 July 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201115956/http://www.bjr.org.uk/data/2002/no4_evans.htm |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It failed to attract significant numbers of new readers, and the pull-out section was abandoned, its final issue appearing on 27 August 1974.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nIn 1978, ''The Sun'' overtook the ''Mirror'' in circulation, and in 1984 the ''Mirror'' was sold to [[Robert Maxwell]]. After Maxwell's death in 1991, [[David Montgomery (newspaper executive)|David Montgomery]] became Mirror Group's CEO, and a period of cost-cutting and production changes ensued. The ''Mirror'' went through a protracted period of crisis before merging with the regional newspaper group Trinity to form [[Trinity Mirror]] in 1999. Printing of the ''Daily'' and ''Sunday Mirror'' moved to Trinity Mirror's facilities in Watford and Oldham.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n===1995\u20132004===\n[[File:Daily Mirror front page 24 June 1996.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Front page of the ''Mirror'' 24 June 1996, with headline \"ACHTUNG! SURRENDER For you Fritz, ze Euro 96 Championship is over\", and accompanying contribution from the editor, \"Mirror declares football war on Germany\"]]\nUnder the editorship of [[Piers Morgan]] (from October 1995 to May 2004) the paper saw a number of controversies.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.britannica.com/biography/Piers-Morgan#ref1092939 |title=Piers Morgan {{!}} British journalist and television personality|work=Encyclopedia Britannica |access-date=26 December 2017}}</ref> Morgan was widely criticised and forced to apologise for the headline \"ACHTUNG! SURRENDER For you Fritz, ze Euro 96 Championship is over\" a day before [[England national football team|England]] met [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in a semi-final of the [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 96]] football championships.<ref name=\"IHT\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/06/26/news/26iht-england.t_0.html |title=Oh, Sorry: Tabloids Lose the Soccer War |last=Thomsen |first=Ian |date=26 June 1996 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=3 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Morgan was the subject of an investigation after Suzy Jagger wrote a story in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' revealing that he had bought [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]20,000 worth of shares in the computer company [[Viglen]] soon before the ''Mirror'' 's 'City Slickers' column tipped Viglen as a good buy.<ref name=\"lie\">{{Cite news |title=Mirror editor saw his shares soar after paper tipped company |author=Jagger, Suzy |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=/archive/2000/02/02/nmir02.html |date=2 February 2000 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021122223139/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=%2Farchive%2F2000%2F02%2F02%2Fnmir02.html |archivedate=22 November 2002 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Morgan was found by the [[Press Complaints Commission]] to have breached the Code of Conduct on financial journalism, but kept his job. The 'City Slickers' columnists, [[Anil Bhoyrul]] and [[James Hipwell]], were both found to have committed further breaches of the Code, and were sacked before the inquiry. In 2004, further enquiry by the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] cleared Morgan from any charges.<ref name=\"cleared\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/3792225.stm |title=Morgan cleared after shares probe |work=BBC News |date=10 June 2004}}</ref> On 7 December 2005 Bhoyrul and Hipwell were convicted of conspiracy to breach the Financial Services Act. During the trial it emerged that Morgan had bought \u00a367,000 worth of Viglen shares, emptying his bank account and investing under his wife's name too.<ref name=\"lie2\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/nov/23/business.pressandpublishing |title= Mirror editor 'bought \u00a367,000 of shares before they were tipped' |work=The Guardian |location=London |first=Chris |last=Tryhorn |date=23 November 2005 |accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, the ''Mirror'' attempted to move mid-market, claiming to eschew the more trivial stories of show-business and gossip. The paper changed its masthead logo from red to black (and occasionally blue), in an attempt to dissociate itself from the term \"[[red tops|red top]]\", a term for a sensationalist mass-market tabloid. (On 6 April 2005, the red top came back.) Under then-editor [[Piers Morgan]], the newspaper's editorial stance opposed the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], and ran many front pages critical of the war. It also gave financial support to the [[15 February 2003 anti-war protest]], paying for a large screen and providing thousands of placards. Morgan re-hired [[John Pilger]], who had been sacked during [[Robert Maxwell]]'s ownership of the Mirror titles. Despite such changes, Morgan was unable to halt the paper's decline in circulation, a decline shared by its direct [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] rivals ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' and the ''[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]''.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n\nMorgan was fired from the ''Mirror'' on 14 May 2004 after authorising the newspaper's publication of photographs allegedly showing [[Iraq]]i prisoners being abused by [[British Army]] soldiers from the [[Queen's Lancashire Regiment]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/13/iraq.abuse.statement/index.html |title=Daily Mirror statement in full |publisher=CNN |date=13 May 2004 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20041125053916/http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/13/iraq.abuse.statement/index.html |archivedate=25 November 2004 |accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> Within days the photographs were shown to be fakes. Under the headline \"SORRY.. WE WERE HOAXED\", the ''Mirror'' responded that it had fallen victim to a \"calculated and malicious hoax\" and apologised for the publication of the photographs.<ref>{{Cite news |url = http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/14/iraq.abuse.uk/ |title=Fake abuse photos: Editor quits |publisher=CNN London |date=15 May 2004 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20041012123314/http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/14/iraq.abuse.uk/ |archivedate=12 October 2004 }}</ref>\n\n===2004\u2013present===\nThe ''Mirror''{{'s}} front page on 4 November 2004, after the re-election of [[George W. Bush]] as U.S. President, read \"How can 59,054,087 people be so DUMB?\". It provided a list of states and their alleged average IQ, showing the Bush states all below average intelligence (except for [[Virginia]]), and all [[John Kerry]] states at or above average intelligence. The source for this table was ''[[The Economist]]'',<ref>{{cite news |last=Sutherland |first=John |title=The Axis of Stupidity |work=The Guardian |location =London |date=11 November 2004 |url= https://www.theguardian.com/education/2004/nov/11/highereducation.uselections2004}}</ref> although it was a hoax.<ref>{{cite web |website=[[Snopes]] |title=Fool Me Twice |url= http://www.snopes.com/politics/ballot/stateiq.asp |date=12 November 2004 |accessdate=19 July 2009 }}</ref> [[Richard Wallace (journalist)|Richard Wallace]] became editor in 2004.\n\nOn 30 May 2012, Trinity Mirror announced the merger of the ''Daily Mirror'' and ''Sunday Mirror'' into a single seven-day-a-week title.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/may/30/richard-wallace-tina-weaver-mirror?newsfeed=true |title= Richard Wallace and Tina Weaver depart as Mirror titles go seven-day |accessdate=30 May 2012 |work=The Guardian |location= London |date=30 May 2012 |first=Mark |last=Sweney}}</ref> Richard Wallace and Tina Weaver, the respective editors of the ''Daily Mirror'' and ''Sunday Mirror'', were simultaneously dismissed and [[Lloyd Embley]], editor of ''The People'', appointed as editor of the combined title with immediate effect.<ref>{{cite news |last= Alleyne |first=Richard |title=Daily Mirror to merge with Sunday Mirror as both editors sacked |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/mediatechnologyandtelecoms/media/9299624/Daily-Mirror-to-merge-with-Sunday-Mirror-as-both-editors-sacked.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |accessdate=30 May 2012 |date=30 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Daily Mirror and Sunday Mirror to merge: full statement |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/mediatechnologyandtelecoms/9299655/Daily-Mirror-and-Sunday-Mirror-to-merge-full-statement.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |accessdate=30 May 2012 |date=30 May 2012}}</ref> In 2018, Reach plc acquired the Northern & Shell titles, including the Daily Express, which led to a number of editor moves across the stable. Lloyd Embley was then promoted to editor-in-chief across the entire group, and [[Alison Phillips]] (previously deputy editor-in-chief for the Trinity Mirror titles) was appointed editor of the Daily Mirror.\n\n==Political allegiance==\nSince 1945 the ''Daily Mirror'' has tended to back the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] at general elections.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nOn 3 May 1979, the day of the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|general election]], the ''Daily Mirror'' urged its readers to vote for the governing Labour Party led by [[James Callaghan]].<ref name=\"century\"/> As widely predicted by the opinion polls, Labour lost this election, which was won by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] and saw [[Margaret Thatcher]] become Prime Minister.<ref name=\"century\">{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/2010/04/20/general-election-2010-a-century-of-daily-mirror-front-pages-115875-22198683/ |title=A century of Daily Mirror front pages |work=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=20 April 2010}}</ref> The ''Mirror''{{'}}s continued support of the Labour government was in spite of its falling popularity over the previous few months which had been the result of the [[Winter of Discontent]], where the country was crippled by numerous public sector strikes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/politics97/background/pastelec/ge79.shtml |work=BBC News |title=Politics 97 |date=3 May 1979}}</ref>\n\nBy the time of the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 general election]], Labour support was at a postwar low, partly due to the strong challenge by the recently formed [[SDP-Liberal Alliance]]. Despite this, the ''Daily Mirror'' remained loyal to Labour and urged its readers to vote for the party (now led by [[Michael Foot]]), condemning the Thatcher-led Tory government for its \"waste of our nation\",<ref name=\"century\"/> condemning the rise in unemployment that Thatcher's Conservative government had seen in its first term in power largely due to [[Monetarism|monetarist]] economic policies to reduce inflation, although the government's previously low popularity had dramatically improved since the success of the [[Falklands War|Falklands]] conflict a year earlier.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/basics/4393313.stm |work=BBC News |title=1983: Thatcher triumphs again |date=5 April 2005}}</ref> However, the Tories were re-elected and Labour suffered its worst postwar general election result, only narrowly bettering the SDP-Liberal Alliance in terms of votes whilst winning considerably more seats.<ref name=\"century\"/>\n\nAt the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 general election]], the ''Daily Mirror'' remained loyal to Labour (now led by [[Neil Kinnock]]) and urged its readers \"You know he's right, chuck her out\".<ref name=\"century\"/> By this stage, unemployment was falling and inflation had remained low for several years.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/basics/4393315.stm |work=BBC News |title=1987: Thatcher's third victory |date=5 April 2005}}</ref> As a result, the Tories were re-elected for a third successive term, although Labour did cut the Tory majority slightly.<ref name=\"century\"/>\n\nFor the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]], the ''Daily Mirror'' continued to support Labour, still led by [[Neil Kinnock]]. By this stage [[Margaret Thatcher]] had stepped down and the Tory government was now led by [[John Major]].<ref name=\"century\"/> The election was won by the Tories, although Labour managed to significantly cut the Tory majority to 21 seats compared to the triple-digit figure of the previous two elections, which led to a difficult term for Major. The outcome of this election had been far less predictable than any of the previous three elections, as opinion polls over the previous three years had shown both parties in the lead, although any Labour lead in the polls had been relatively narrow since the Conservative government's change of leader from Thatcher to Major in November 1990, in spite of the onset of a [[Early 1990s recession|recession in 1990]] which had pushed unemployment up again after several years of decline. Labour's credibility was helped by plans including extra [[National Health Service|NHS funding]] and moving away from firm commitments on re-nationalisation to reverse the Conservative policy of privatisation, but its decision to be up-front about tax increases was seen as a key factor in its failure to win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/basics/4393317.stm |work=BBC News |title=1992: Tories win again against odds |date=5 April 2005}}</ref>\n\nBy the time of the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], support for the Labour Party, now led by [[Tony Blair]], in the opinion polls had exceeded that of support for the Tory government (still led by John Major) since late 1992, the government's reduced popularity largely blamed on the failings of [[Black Wednesday]] in September of that year and it had failed to recover popularity in spite of a strong economic recovery and fall in unemployment. A reinvented \"New Labour\" had further improved its credibility under Blair by promising traditional Labour essentials including more funding for healthcare and education, but also promising not to increase income tax and ending its commitment to the nationalisation of leading industries.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/basics/4393323.stm |work=BBC News |title=1997: Labour landslide ends Tory rule |date=15 April 2005}}</ref> The ''Daily Mirror'' urged its readers that their country needed Tony Blair, and to vote Labour.<ref name=\"century\"/> The election produced a Labour landslide and ended the party's 18-year exile from power.\n\nOn 4 May 2010, the newspaper printed a picture of Conservative leader [[David Cameron]] with a giant red cross through his face. The headline read \"How to stop him\" in reference to the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|general election two days later]], thus confirming the ''Daily Mirror''{{'}}s Labour allegiance. The election ended in Britain's first [[hung parliament]] since [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|1974]], but Cameron still became prime minister of the country within days as the Conservatives formed a coalition with the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]. The ''Daily Mirror'' was the only leading national newspaper to remain loyal to Labour and [[Gordon Brown]] at a time when opinion polls showed the party on course for their worst election result since [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.supanet.com/business--money/which-political-parties-do-the-newspapers-support--25923p1.html |title=Which political parties do the newspapers support? |publisher=Supanet}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper was critical of the Liberal Democrats for forming the coalition which enabled the Conservatives to form a new government in 2010, and branded leader [[Nick Clegg]] as Pinickio (alluding to the lying fictional character [[Pinocchio]])<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2011/01/13/clegg-nose-day-join-our-campaign-to-shame-pinickio-nick-clegg-115875-22845966/ |title=Clegg Nose Day \u2013 Join our campaign to shame 'Pinickio' Nick Clegg |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=13 January 2011}}</ref> for going back on numerous pre-election pledges. It has frequently referred to the party as the \"Fib Dems\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/opinion/2011/03/04/security-bill-for-nick-clegg-s-lib-dem-conference-is-more-than-just-coppers-115875-22964255/ |title=Security bill for Nick Clegg's Lib Dem conference is more than just coppers |last=Routledge |first=Paul |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=4 March 2011}}</ref> or \"Lib Dumbs\".<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/opinion/2010/05/19/dumb-and-dumber-115875-22268581/ |title=PMQs shows up the Lib Dumbs |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=19 May 2010}}</ref> The ''Daily Mirror'' endorsed Democratic candidate [[Hillary Clinton]] in the run-up for the 2016 U.S. presidential election.<ref>{{cite news |title=Americans must vote Hillary Clinton for their own sake |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/americans-must-vote-hillary-clinton-9216821 |accessdate=November 8, 2016 |work=Daily Mirror |date=November 7, 2016}}</ref> In 2016 the newspapers asked for [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s resignation \"for the good of Labour and of the country\".\n\nDespite this critical position,  the ''Daily Mirror'' endorsed again the Labour Party in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]].<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/help-corbyn-kick-tories-touch-10278153 |title=Help Corbyn kick the Tories into touch - Voice of the Mirror |date=22 April 2017 |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location= London |access-date=19 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Famous features==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=January 2018}}\n* Cartoon strips \"[[Pip, Squeak and Wilfred]]\" (1919\u201356), \"[[Jane (comic strip)|Jane]]\" (1932\u201359), \"[[Garth (comic strip)|Garth]]\" (1943\u201397, reprints 2011), \"[[Just Jake]]\" (1938\u201352), \"[[Andy Capp]]\" (1957\u2013), and \"[[The Perishers]]\" (1955\u20132006 and later reprints).\n* \"The Old Codgers\", a fictional pair who commented on the letters page from 1935 to 1990.<ref name=Gascoigne>[http://www.historyworld.net/Articles/PlainTextArticles.asp?aid=zah&pid=617 Bamber Gascoigne (1993) ''Encyclopedia of Britain'' (Macmillan)]</ref>\n* Chalky White, who would wander around various British seaside resorts waiting to be recognised by Mirror readers (an obscured photo of him having been published in that day's paper). Anyone who recognised him would have to repeat some phrase along the lines of \"[[You are X and I claim my five pounds|To my delight, it's Chalky White]]\" to win \u00a35. The name continues to be used on the cartoons page, as [[Andy Capp]]'s best friend.\n* \"Shock issues\" intended to highlight a particular news story.\n* The columnist [[William Connor|Cassandra]] (1935\u201367).\n* \"Dear Marje\", a problem page by agony aunt [[Marjorie Proops]].\n* Investigative reporting by [[Paul Foot (campaigner)|Paul Foot]] and [[John Pilger]] (including the latter's expos\u00e9 of the atrocities of the [[Khmer Rouge]] in Cambodia).\n* \"The Shopping Basket\". Starting in the mid-1970s, the paper monitored the cost of a \u00a35 basket of shopping to see how it increased in price over the years.\n\n===Blue issue===\nOn 2 April 1996, the ''Daily Mirror'' was printed entirely on blue paper.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} This was done as a marketing exercise with [[Pepsi|Pepsi-Cola]], who on the same day had decided to relaunch their cans with a blue design instead of the traditional red and white logo.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Libel, contempt of court, errors and criticism==\n[[File:The Daily Mirror - Sorry We Were Hoaxed.jpg|frame|right|upright|alt=Sorry We Were hoaxed|Front page of the ''Daily Mirror'' after publishing faked photographs.]]\n* In the 1959 ''[[Liberace v Daily Mirror]]'' case, [[Liberace]] sued the ''Mirror'' for libel. [[William Connor]] had written a pseudonymous column hinting that the American entertainer was a homosexual; homosexuality was illegal in Britain at the time. The jury found in Liberace's favour and he received \u00a38,000 in damage (estimated at around \u00a3500,000 in 2009).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Greenslade |first1=Roy |title=The meaning of 'fruit': how the Daily Mirror libelled Liberace |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2009/may/26/daily-mirror-medialaw |accessdate=26 September 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=26 May 2009}}</ref>\n* In 1991, shortly after the death of [[Queen (band)|Queen]]<nowiki/>'s lead singer [[Freddie Mercury]], the ''Daily Mirror'' ran a [[homophobia|homophobic]] column by [[Joe Haines (journalist)|Joe Haines]] which contained extensive insults towards Mercury, [[HIV/AIDS]] victims, and homosexuals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dungeonpeaches.tumblr.com/post/85982644289/queenmania-this-repulsive-article-which|title=queenmania: This repulsive article, which...|website=random thoughts: queen, life, and everything}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.queencuttings.com/dblog/articolo.asp?articolo=309|title=Dark Side of Freddie|date=28 November 1991|website=Queencuttings|access-date=3 June 2018}}</ref> The article prompted an open letter in condemnation from folk singer [[Lal Waterson]], later recorded as a song by her sister [[Norma Waterson|Norma]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://rbhsjukebox.wordpress.com/2013/11/26/song-of-the-day-november-26-lal-watersons-reply-to-joe-haines/|title=Song of the Day, November 26: Lal Waterson\u2019s Reply to Joe Haines|date=2013-11-26|work=Music and Meaning: The RBHS Jukebox|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* In December 1992, Scottish politician [[George Galloway]] won libel damages from the ''Daily Mirror'' and its Scottish sister the ''Daily Record'', who had falsely accused him of making malicious allegations about their foreign editor [[Nicholas Davies (journalist)|Nicholas Davies]]. Galloway had used [[parliamentary privilege]] to call for an independent investigation into allegations about Davies made in the book [[The Samson Option: Israel's Nuclear Arsenal and American Foreign Policy|''The Samson Option'']].<ref>{{cite news |title=Scottish MP wins libel damages |url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12589730.Scottish_MP_wins_libel_damages/ |accessdate=3 October 2018 |work=The Herald |date=22 December 1992}}</ref>\n* In May 2004, the ''Daily Mirror'' published what it claimed were photos of British soldiers abusing Iraqi prisoners at an unspecified location in Iraq. The decision to publish the photos, subsequently shown to be hoaxes, led to Piers Morgan's sacking as editor of the paper on 14 May 2004. The ''Daily Mirror'' then stated that it was the subject of a \"calculated and malicious hoax\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/14/iraq.abuse.uk/ |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20041012123314/http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/14/iraq.abuse.uk/ |archivedate=12 October 2004 |title= Fake abuse photos: Editor quits |date=15 May 2004 |publisher=CNN}}</ref> The newspaper issued a statement apologising for the printing of the pictures. The paper's deputy editor, [[Des Kelly]], took over as acting editor during the crisis. The tabloid's rival, ''The Sun'', offered a \u00a350,000 reward for the arrest and conviction of those accused of faking the ''Mirror'' photographs.\n* In June 2004, American model [[Caprice Bourret]] won a libel case against the ''Daily Mirror'' for an article in April that year which falsely claimed that her acting career had failed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Caprice wins libel case over acting claims |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1464662/Caprice-wins-libel-case-over-acting-claims.html |accessdate=3 October 2018 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=16 June 2004}}</ref>\n* In November 2007, the ''Daily Mirror'' paid damages to Sir Andrew Green after having likened him and his group [[MigrationWatch UK]] to the [[Ku Klux Klan]] and [[Nazi Party]] in September of that year. The newspaper admitted that such allegations were \"untrue\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Sir Andrew Green - an apology|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/sir-andrew-green---an-apology-523654|work=Daily Mirror|date=26 November 2007}}</ref>\n* In February 2008 both the ''Daily'' and the ''Sunday Mirror'' implied that TV presenter [[Kate Garraway]] was having an affair. She sued for [[Defamation#United Kingdom|libel]], receiving an apology and compensation payment in April 2008.<ref>{{cite news\n|title= GMTV Kate wins 'affair' libel award\n|work=[[Sunday Express]] | location = London\n|url= http://www.dailyexpress.co.uk/posts/view/40871\n|date=10 April 2008\n|accessdate=17 July 2009\n}}</ref>\n* On 18 September 2008, David Anderson, a British sports journalist writing for the ''Mirror'', repeated a claim deriving from vandalism on Wikipedia's entry for Cypriot football team [[AC Omonia]], which asserted that their fans were called \"The Zany Ones\" and liked to wear hats made from discarded shoes. The claim was part of Anderson's match preview ahead of AC Omonia's game with [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], which appeared in the web and print versions of the ''Mirror'', with the nickname also quoted in subsequent editions on 19 September.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shoe hat hoax trips up Mirror |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/mediamonkeyblog/2008/sep/23/mirror.digitalmedia |accessdate=27 October 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=23 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=McCauley |first1=Ciaran |title=Wikipedia hoaxes: From Breakdancing to Bilcholim |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-37523772 |accessdate=27 October 2019 |work=BBC News |date=3 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Mirror journalist caught by Wikipedia hoax |url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/mirror-journalist-caught-by-wikipedia-hoax/ |accessdate=27 October 2019 |work=Press Gazette |date=23 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Wiki warning: sniff out the Omonia |url=https://www.sportsjournalists.co.uk/sport-on-the-web/wiki-warning-sniff-out-the-omonia/ |accessdate=27 October 2019 |publisher=Sports Journalists' Association |date=23 September 2008}}</ref>\n* In November 2009, the ''Mirror'' paid \"substantial libel damages\" to Portuguese footballer [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] after it admitted that a story about him becoming highly intoxicated in a Hollywood nightclub was untrue.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cristiano Ronaldo wins libel damages against Daily Mirror |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/players/cristiano-ronaldo/6533183/Cristiano-Ronaldo-wins-libel-damages-against-Daily-Mirror.html |accessdate=3 October 2018 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=9 November 2009}}</ref>\n* On 12 May 2011, the [[High Court of England and Wales]] granted the [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] permission to bring a case for contempt against ''The Sun'' and the ''Daily Mirror'' for the way they had reported on the arrest of a person of interest in the [[Murder of Joanna Yeates]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-13371918 |title=Sun and Mirror in contempt case over Jo Yeates stories |work=BBC News |date=12 May 2011 |accessdate=12 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-14024079 |title= Sun and Mirror accused of Jo Yeates contempt |work=BBC News |date=5 July 2011 |accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> On 29 July, the Court ruled that both newspapers had been in contempt of court, fining the ''Daily Mirror'' \u00a350,000 and ''The Sun'' \u00a318,000.<ref>{{cite news |last=Halliday |first=Josh |title=Sun and Mirror fined for contempt of court in Christopher Jefferies articles |url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jul/29/sun-daily-mirror-guilty-contempt |accessdate=29 July 2011 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=29 July 2011}}</ref>\n* In October 2013, a defamation case brought by the Irish airline [[Ryanair]] against the ''Daily Mirror'' was settled out of court. The ''Mirror'' had repeated allegations about the airline's safety from a [[Channel 4]] documentary which were not reflected by its most recent evaluation by the [[Irish Aviation Authority]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ryanair settles defamation action against Daily Mirror out of court |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2013/1025/482635-ryanair-libel/ |accessdate=3 October 2018 |website=RT\u00c9 |date=25 October 2013}}</ref>\n* On 19 July 2011 the ''Mirror'' published an article labelling comedian [[Frankie Boyle]] as a racist. He later sued for defamation and libel, winning \u00a354,650 in damages and a further \u00a34,250 for a claim about his departure from ''[[Mock the Week]]''. The ''Mirror'' had argued he was \"forced to quit\" but this was found to be libellous by the court.<ref>{{cite news |title=BBC News on Frankie Boyle lawsuit |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-20033097 |accessdate=22 October 2012 |work=BBC News |date=22 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Preece |first=Rob |title=Comedian Frankie Boyle wins \u00a354,000 libel payout after being branded a racist by the Daily Mirror |url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2221486/Frankie-Boyle-Comedian-wins-54-000-libel-payout-branded-racist-Daily-Mirror.html?ITO=1490 |accessdate=22 October 2012 |newspaper=Daily Mail |date=22 October 2012}}</ref>\n* On 20 March 2017 the ''Mirror'' painted the traditional Russian pancake celebration [[Maslenitsa]] as a [[Hooligan]] training ground. One of the centuries-old tradition in this Russian festival is \u201cwall-to-wall\u201d (\u2018[[:ru:\u0421\u0442\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0443|stenka na stenku]]\u2019, Ru) which is sparring between men dressed in traditional folk clothes. This tradition was wrongly represented by the ''Mirror'' in the pictures and text, labelled as violent acts and living in fear without giving context or any information about this Russian traditional festival at all. The ''Mirror'' article was titled \u201cRussia's Ultra yobs infiltrated amid warnings England fans could be KILLED at [[World Cup 2018|World Cup]].\u201d, and received negative receptions from Russian media, also being described as [[fake news]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Brits scared about pancake battles Gazeta.ru|url=https://www.gazeta.ru/sport/2017/03/21/a_10587857.shtml|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fake news del Mirror, il Carnevale russo diventa allenamento per uccidere|url=https://it.sputniknews.com/mondo/201703214231272-lotta-pugno-mirror-mondiali-russi/|accessdate=21 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UK tabloid distorts traditional Russian pancake festival into \u2018Ultra\u2019 football thug fights|url=https://www.rt.com/sport/381611-russian-pancake-festival-football-thug-fights/|accessdate=21 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Daily Mirror misleads with wrong pictures for article on football 'Ultras' in Russia|url=http://tass.com/sport/936675|accessdate=21 March 2017}}</ref> The organisers of the traditional Russian folk festival event are looking to sue the ''Daily Mirror'', it is reported later.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018We\u2019re looking to sue Daily Mirror\u2019 \u2013 Russian pancake festival fight organizers on hooligan claims|url=https://www.rt.com/sport/381767-russian-hooligans-daily-mirror/|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref> Representatives of the ''Daily Mirror'' acknowledged that the original material of the publication about Russian Hooligans was incorrectly illustrated with images of the traditional festival. In the updated version of the article the newspaper continues to insist that the photographed people were hooligans in the pictures, but gives no evidence of their participation in the festival.<ref>{{cite web|title=Daily Mirror acknowledged incorrectly illustrated text about world Cup fans|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?sl=ru&tl=en&js=y&prev=_t&hl=de&ie=UTF-8&u=https%3A%2F%2Fria.ru%2Fmediawars%2F20170321%2F1490511385.html&edit-text=|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Significant staff members==\n\n===Editors===\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n:1903 to 1904: [[Mary Howarth (newspaper editor)|Mary Howarth]]\n:1904 to 1907: [[Hamilton Fyfe]]\n:1907 to 1915: [[Alexander Kenealy]]\n:1915 to 1916: [[Ed Flynn (journalist)|Ed Flynn]]\n:1916 to 1929: [[Alexander Campbell (journalist)|Alexander Campbell]]\n:1929 to 1931: [[Cameron Hogg]]\n:1931 to 1934: [[Leigh Brownlee]]\n:1934 to 1948: [[Cecil Thomas (journalist)|Cecil Thomas]]\n:1948 to 1953: [[Silvester Bolam]]\n:1953 to 1961: [[Jack Nener]]\n:1961 to 1971: [[Lee Howard (journalist)|Lee Howard]]\n:1971 to 1974: [[Tony Miles (journalist)|Tony Miles]]\n:1974 to 1975: [[Michael Christiansen]]\n:1975 to 1985: [[Mike Molloy]]\n:1985 to 1990: [[Richard Stott]]\n:1990 to 1991: [[Roy Greenslade]]\n:1991 to 1992: [[Richard Stott]]\n:1992 to 1994: [[David Banks (journalist)|David Banks]]\n:1994 to 1995: [[Colin Myler]]\n:1995 to 2004: [[Piers Morgan]]\n:2004 to 2012: [[Richard Wallace (journalist)|Richard Wallace]]\n:2012 to 2016: [[Lloyd Embley]]\n:2016 to 2018: [[Allan Bryce]]\n:2018 to date: [[Alison Phillips]]\n{{div col end}}\n\nSource: ''Tabloid Nation''<ref name=\"tabloidnation\">{{cite book |first=Chris |last=Horrie |title=Tabloid Nation: From the Birth of the Mirror to the Death of the Tabloid Newspaper |year = 2003 |publisher=Andr\u00e9 Deutsch |page=248 |isbn=978-0-233-00012-1}}</ref>\n\n===Notable columnists===\nNotable former and current columnists of the ''Daily Mirror'' include:\n* [[The 3AM Girls]] (gossip columnists)\n*[[Anne Robinson]] (columnist and deputy editor)\n* [[William Connor]] (opinion under the pseudonym ''Cassandra'' (1935\u20131967))\n* [[Caradoc Evans]] (1917\u20131923)\n* [[Richard Hammond]] (motoring and Saturday columnist)\n* [[Oliver Holt]] (sports columnist)\n* [[Kevin Maguire (journalist)|Kevin Maguire]] (UK politics)\n* [[Penman & Greenwood]] (investigators)\n* [[Fiona Phillips]] (Saturday columnist)\n* [[Brian Reade]] (Thursday columnist; also does a sports column on Saturdays)\n* [[Keith Waterhouse]] (largely humorous (1970\u20131986, previously a reporter.)\n* [[Chris Hughes (journalist)|Chris Hughes]] (security and defence)\n* [[Geoffrey Goodman]] (1969\u20131986)\n\n==Awards==\n''The Daily Mirror'' won \"Newspaper of the Year\" in 2002 at the [[British Press Awards]]. It won \"Scoop of the Year\" in 2003 (\"3am\", 'Sven and Ulrika'), 2004 (Ryan Parry, 'Intruder at the Palace'), 2006 and 2007 (both Stephen Moyes).<ref name=gazetteroll>''[[Press Gazette]]'', [http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/hybrid.asp?typeCode=99&navcode=92# Roll of Honour]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616181807/http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/hybrid.asp?typeCode=99&navcode=92 |date=16 June 2011 }}. Retrieved 24 July 2011</ref> The ''Mirror'' won \"Team of the Year\" in 2001 ('Railtrack'), 2002 ('War on the World: World against Terrorism'), 2003 ('Soham'), and 2006 ('London bombings'); and \"Front Page of the Year\" in 2007.<ref name=gazetteroll/> The ''Mirror'' also won the \"Cudlipp Award\" in 2002, 2003, 2004 and 2010.<ref name=gazetteroll/>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Wharf (newspaper)|The Wharf]]'', sister newspaper for the [[Isle of Dogs]].\n* [[Daily Mirror Silver Cup|''Daily Mirror'' Silver Cup]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{Cite journal| last=Morgan |first=Piers |url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/13/iraq.abuse.statement/index.html |title=Daily Mirror statement in full |publisher=CNN World |date=13 May 2004 |accessdate=28 November 2005| postscript=<!-- Bot inserted parameter. Either remove it; or change its value to \".\" for the cite to end in a \".\", as necessary. -->{{inconsistent citations}} |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041125053916/http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/13/iraq.abuse.statement/index.html |archivedate=25 November 2004}}\n* {{Cite journal| url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/14/iraq.abuse.uk/ | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041012123314/http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/14/iraq.abuse.uk/ | archivedate=12 October 2004 |title=Fake abuse photos: Editor quits| publisher=CNN |publication-place=London |date=15 May 2004 |accessdate=27 November 2005| postscript=<!-- Bot inserted parameter. Either remove it; or change its value to \".\" for the cite to end in a \".\", as necessary. -->{{inconsistent citations}}}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Daily Mirror}}\n* {{Official website|www.mirror.co.uk|mobile=m.mirror.co.uk}}\n* {{PM20|FID=co/055734|TEXT=Documents and clippings about|NAME=}}\n\n{{Daily Mirror editors}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Trinity Mirror}}\n{{Media in the United Kingdom|newsmag}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:National newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Reach plc]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1903]]\n[[Category:1903 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in London]]\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Loweredtone", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated circulation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daily_Mirror"}
{"title_page": "The Marshall Mathers LP", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = The Marshall Mathers LP\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Eminem]]\n| cover        = The Marshall Mathers LP.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = {{Start date|2000|5|23}}\n| recorded     = 1999\u20132000<ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KkyjQgAACAAJ&dq=angry%20blonde&source=gbs_book_other_versions|title=Angry Blonde: The Official Book|publisher=HarperCollins}}</ref> <!-- It is said later WITHIN this page that kim was the earliest recorded song, explicitly stating that it was recorded in 1999. -->\n| studio       = {{Collapsible list|title={{nobold|Various}}|{{Plainlist|\n*The Mix Room<br/>{{small|([[Burbank, California|Burbank]], [[California|CA]])}}\n*Encore Studios<br/>{{small|([[Burbank, California|Burbank]], [[California|CA]])}}\n*[[Larrabee Sound Studios]]<br/>{{small|([[Hollywood]], [[California|CA]])}}\n*[[Chung King Studios|Chung King]]<br/>{{small|([[New York City]], [[New York (state)|NY]])}}\n*[[Record Plant|The Record Plant]]<br/>{{small|([[Los Angeles]], [[California|CA]])}}\n*54 Sound<br/>{{small|([[Detroit]], [[Michigan|MI]])}}}}}}\n| genre        = * [[Horrorcore]]\n* [[hardcore hip hop]]<!-- Both of these genres are sourced in the \"music and lyrics\" section. Please DO NOT ADD other genres without citing one or more reliable sources that explicitly describe the album as such. -->\n| length       = 72:04\n| label        = *[[Aftermath Entertainment|Aftermath]]\n*[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| producer     = * [[Dr. Dre]] <small>(also [[Executive producer|exec.]])</small>\n* Eminem\n* [[Bass Brothers|F.B.T.]]\n* [[Melvin \"Mel-Man\" Bradford|Mel-Man]]\n* [[The 45 King]]\n| prev_title   = [[The Slim Shady LP]]\n| prev_year    = 1999\n| next_title   = [[The Eminem Show]]\n| next_year    = 2002\n| misc         = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternate cover art\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = The Marshall Mathers LP second cover.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption =\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Tour Edition cover art\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = The_Marshall_Mathers_LP_limited_edition_cover.png\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption =\n}}\n{{Singles\n | name        = The Marshall Mathers LP\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[The Real Slim Shady]]\n | single1date = April 15, 2000\n | single2     = [[The Way I Am (Eminem song)|The Way I Am]]\n | single2date = September 7, 2000\n | single3     = [[Stan (song)|Stan]]\n | single3date = November 21, 2000\n | single4     = I'm Back\n | single4date = April 3, 2001\n | single5     = [[Bitch Please II]]\n | single5date = May 23, 2001\n}}\n}}\n'''''The Marshall Mathers LP''''' is the third studio album by American rapper [[Eminem]], released on May 23, 2000 by [[Aftermath Entertainment]] and [[Interscope Records]]. The album was produced mostly by [[Dr. Dre]] and Eminem, along with [[The 45 King]], the [[Bass Brothers]], and [[Melvin \"Mel-Man\" Bradford|Mel-Man]]. It was recorded over a two-month period in several studios in the Detroit area, and during this time, Eminem felt significant pressure to improve upon the success of his previous record. \n\nReleased a year after Eminem's breakout album ''[[The Slim Shady LP]]'', the album features more introspective lyricism including his response to his sudden rise to fame and controversy surrounding his lyrics. Musically, the album incorporates [[horrorcore]] and [[hardcore hip hop]]. Like its predecessor, ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' was surrounded by significant controversy upon its release. Criticism centered around lyrics that were considered violent, homophobic, and misogynistic. [[Lynne Cheney]] criticized the lyrics at a [[United States Senate]] hearing, while the [[Canadian government]] considered refusing Eminem's entry into the country. \n\n''The Marshall Mathers LP'' debuted at number one on the [[US Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 1.78 million copies in its first week alone which made it one of the [[Lists of fastest-selling albums|fastest-selling studio albums]] in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/426851/albums-that-sold-1-million-in-one-week|title=Albums That Sold 1 Million in One Week|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> The album's first single \"[[The Real Slim Shady]]\" became Eminem's biggest hit up to that point, and gained notoriety for poking fun at [[pop culture]] figures at the time such as [[NSYNC]], [[Britney Spears]], [[Christina Aguilera]] and [[Will Smith]].<ref name=\"Ellis256\" /> The album also features \"[[Stan (song)|Stan]]\", which has been regarded as one of Eminem's [[signature song]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liveabout.com/top-eminem-songs-p2-2858002|title=The 15 Best Eminem Songs Have a Stirring Blend of Rhyme and Music|last=since 2005|first=Henry Adaso Henry Adaso has written about hip-hop|last2=for \"Vibe|first2=founded the award-winning blog The Rap Up He has written|website=LiveAbout|language=en|access-date=2019-12-28|last3=Mtv|first3=\"|last4=Rehab|first4=Rap|last5=more.}}</ref> Despite the controversy of the album, it received acclaim from critics, who praised Eminem's lyrical ability and emotional depth.\n\nOne of the most ground breaking and controversial albums in [[American music]], ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' has been named on several lists of the greatest albums of all time and is widely regarded as Eminem's best album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/eminem-admits-hes-still-looking-to-eclipse-the-marshall-mathers-lp-news.72817.html|title=Eminem Admits He's Still Looking To Eclipse \"The Marshall Mathers LP\"|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref> It has sold 21 million copies worldwide, making it one of the [[List of best-selling albums|best-selling albums of all time]], and was certified [[RIAA certification|Diamond]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). It was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] and won [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Album|Best Rap Album]] at the [[43rd Grammy Awards]]. \"The Real Slim Shady\" won [[Best Rap Solo Performance]]. ''[[The Marshall Mathers LP 2]]'', the [[sequel]] to the album, was released in 2013.\n\n== Background ==\nInspired by the disappointment of his debut album, ''[[Infinite (Eminem album)|Infinite]]'' (1996), [[Eminem]] created the [[alter ego]] Slim Shady, whom he introduced on the ''[[Slim Shady EP]]'' (1997).<ref name=\"BlowsUp\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/eminem-blows-up-20091105|title=Eminem Blows Up|last=Bozza|first=Anthony|authorlink = Anthony Bozza|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=February 16, 2012|work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref> After placing second in the annual [[Rap Olympics]], Eminem was noticed by the staff at [[Interscope Records]] and eventually CEO [[Jimmy Iovine]], who played the ''Slim Shady EP'' for well-known hip hop producer [[Dr. Dre]].<ref name=\"BlowsUp\" /> Eminem and Dr. Dre then met and became fast friends, recording ''[[The Slim Shady LP]]'' (1999), which was noted for its over-the-top lyrical depictions of drugs and violence.<ref name=\"BlowsUp\" /> ''The Slim Shady LP'' was a critical and commercial success, debuting at number two on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart and selling 283,000 copies in its first week.<ref name=\"Charts?\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1452682/got-charts-o-brother-sales-boost-likely.jhtml|title=Got Charts? Expect 'O Brother' Sales Boost After Unexpected Win|last=Basham|first=David|work=MTV News|publisher=Viacom|date=February 28, 2002|accessdate=February 18, 2012}}</ref> At the [[42nd Grammy Awards]] in 2000, the record won [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Album|Best Rap Album]], while the album's lead single \"[[My Name Is]]\" won [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Solo Performance|Best Rap Solo Performance]].<ref name=\"RSbio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/eminem/biography|title=Eminem \u2013 Biography|last=Serpick|first=Evan|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=March 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''The Slim Shady LP'' turned Eminem from an underground rapper into a high-profile celebrity. The rapper, who had previously struggled to provide for his daughter Hailie, noted a drastic change in his lifestyle.<ref name=\"Hasted 123\">Hasted, 2011. p. 123</ref> In June 1999, he married his girlfriend Kimberly Ann \"Kim\" Scott, the mother of Hailie, despite the fact that the song \"'97 Bonnie & Clyde\" from ''The Slim Shady LP'' contains references to killing her.<ref name=\"finalsplit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,619299,00.html|title=Eminem, Kim: Final Split|work=People|publisher=Time, Inc.|last=Silverman|first=Stephen M.}}</ref> The rapper became uncomfortable with the level of fame he had achieved, and said, \"I don't trust nobody now because everybody I meet is meeting me as Eminem...I don't know if they are hanging with me 'cause they like me or because I'm a celebrity or because they think they can get something from me.\"<ref name=\"Hasted 123\"/> Eminem also became a highly controversial figure due to his lyrical content. He was labeled as \"misogynist, a nihilist and an advocate of domestic violence\", and in an editorial, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' editor in chief [[Timothy White (editor)|Timothy White]] accused Eminem of \"making money by exploiting the world's misery\".<ref name=\"BlowsUp\" />\n\n== Recording ==\n[[File:Eminem-01-mika.jpg|thumb|left|Eminem (pictured in 1999) wrote the majority of ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' while in the studio.]]\n''The Marshall Mathers LP'' was recorded in a two-month-long \"creative binge\", which often involved 20-hour-long studio sessions.<ref name=\"Hasted 153\">Hasted, 2011. p. 153</ref> Eminem hoped to keep publicity down during the recording in order to stay focused on working and figuring out how to \"map out\" each song.<ref name=\"Hasted 153\" /> He described himself as a \"studio rat\" who benefited creatively from the isolated environment of the studio.<ref name=\"Hasted 156\">Hasted, 2011. p. 156</ref> Much of the album was written spontaneously in the studio; Dr. Dre noted, \"We don't wake up at two in the morning, call each other, and say, 'I have an idea. We gotta get to the studio.' We just wait and see what happens when we get there.\"<ref name=\"Drdrevh1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/series/ultimate_albums/marshall/interview_dre.jhtml|title=Ultimate Albums: The Marshall Mathers LP \u2013 Dr. Dre interview|work=[[VH1]]|accessdate=July 16, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030901065534/http://www.vh1.com/shows/series/ultimate_albums/marshall/interview_dre.jhtml|archive-date=September 1, 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref> Eminem observed that much of his favorite material on the album evolved from \"fucking around\" in the studio; \"Marshall Mathers\" developed from the rapper watching Jeff Bass casually strumming a guitar, while \"Criminal\" was based on a piano riff Eminem overheard Bass playing in studio next door.<ref name=\"Hasted 156\" /> \"Kill You\" was written when Eminem heard the track playing in the background while talking to Dr. Dre on the phone and developed an interest in using it for a song. He then wrote the lyrics at home and met up with Dr. Dre and the two recorded the song together.<ref name=\"Drdrevh1\" />\n\n\"Kim\" was the first song the rapper recorded for the album, shortly after finishing work on ''The Slim Shady LP'' in late 1998.<ref name=\"hasted120\">Hasted, p. 120</ref> Eminem wrote \"Kim\" at a time in which he and his wife were separated, and he had just watched a romantic movie alone at a theater.<ref name=\"hasted120\" /> Originally intending to write a love song for her while using [[ecstasy (drug)|ecstasy]], the rapper hoped to avoid overt sentimentality and thus began writing a song of hate.<ref name=\"Vanhoozer84\">Vanhoozer, p. 84</ref> With the track, the rapper aimed to create a short horror story in the form of a song. Once the couple reconciled, Eminem recalls, \"I asked her to tell me what she thought of it. I remember my dumb ass saying, 'I know this is a fucked-up song, but it shows how much I care about you. To even think about you this much. To even put you on a song like this'.\"<ref name=\"hasted121\">Hasted, p. 121</ref> The song \"[[Stan (song)|Stan]]\" was produced by [[The 45 King]]. Eminem's manager, [[Paul Rosenberg (music manager)|Paul Rosenberg]], sent Eminem a tape of the producer's beats, and the second track featured a sample of English singer-songwriter [[Dido (singer)|Dido]]'s \"[[Thank You (Dido song)|Thank You]]\".<ref name=\"Eminemvh1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/series/ultimate_albums/marshall/interview_eminem.jhtml|title=Ultimate Albums: The Marshall Mathers LP \u2013 Eminem interview|work=[[VH1]]|accessdate=July 16, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031230030718/http://www.vh1.com/shows/series/ultimate_albums/marshall/interview_eminem.jhtml|archive-date=December 30, 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref> Upon hearing the song's lyrics, Eminem felt they described an obsessed fan, which became the inspiration for the song. The writing process for \"Stan\" differed greatly from Eminem's usual strategy, in which song concepts form during the writing: {{\"'}}Stan' was one of the few songs that I actually sat down and had everything mapped out for. I knew what it was going to be about.\"<ref name=\"Eminemvh1\" /> Dido later heard \"Stan\" and enjoyed it, and observed, \"I got this letter out of the blue one day. It said, 'We like your album, we've used this track. Hope you don't mind, and hope you like it.' When they sent ['Stan'] to me and I played it in my hotel room, I was like, 'Wow! This track's amazing.{{'\"}}<ref name=\"Dido\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1428065/dido-discusses-her-appearance-on-eminems-stan.jhtml|title=Dido Discusses Her Appearance On Eminem's \"Stan\"|work=[[MTV News]]|publisher=[[ViacomCBS|Viacom]]|last=Varhely|first=Nikki|date=June 6, 2000|accessdate=July 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe record label speculated that Eminem would be the first artist to sell one million copies in an album's first week of release. These expectations placed a large burden on Eminem, who recalled, \"I was scared to death. I wanted to be successful, but before anything, I want respect.\"<ref name=\"Eminemvh1\" /> After the album was finished, the record label felt that there were no songs that had potential to be a lead single.<ref name=\"Eminemvh1\" /> Feeling pressured, Eminem returned to the studio and wrote \"The Way I Am\" as his way of saying, \"Look, this is the best I can do. I can't give you another 'My Name Is.' I can't just sit in there and make that magic happen.\"<ref name=\"Eminemvh1\" /> However, after the song was added to the album, Eminem felt the urge to write another song, and gave a hook to Dr. Dre for him to create a beat, and went home to write new lyrics; the song eventually became \"The Real Slim Shady\".<ref name=\"Eminemvh1\" /> The song also discusses Eminem killing Dr. Dre. The producer stated, \"It was funny to me. As long as it's hot, let's roll with it ... in my opinion, the crazier it is the better. Let's have fun with it and excite people.\"<ref name=\"Drdrevh1\" />\n\n== Music and lyrics ==\n[[File:Dr. Dre.jpg|thumb|[[Dr. Dre]] produced most of the first half of the album, together with [[Melvin \"Mel-Man\" Bradford|Mel-Man]]|alt=|252x252px]]\n\nConsidered both a [[horrorcore]] album and a [[hardcore hip hop]] album,<ref name=\"RS review\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hiphopdx.com/editorials/id.3516/title.in-defense-of-eminems-horrorcore-masterpiece-relapse# |title=In Defense of Eminem's Horrorcore Masterpiece: \"Relapse\" |work=[[HipHopDX]] |last=Ketchum III |first=William |date=October 31, 2016 |accessdate=February 1, 2017}}</ref> much of the album's first half was produced by Dr. Dre and [[Melvin \"Mel-Man\" Bradford|Mel-Man]], who employed their typical sparse, stripped-down beats, to put more focus on Eminem's vocals. The background music on the record employs \"liquid basslines, stuttering rhythms, slight sound effects, and spacious soundscapes\".<ref name=\"allmusic review\" /> [[Bass Brothers]] and Eminem produced most of the second half, which ranges from the laid-back guitars of \"Marshall Mathers\" to the atmosphere of \"Amityville\". The only outside producer on the album was The 45 King, who sampled a verse from Dido's song \"Thank You\" for \"Stan\", while adding a slow bass line.\n\n''The Marshall Mathers LP'' contains more autobiographical themes in comparison to ''The Slim Shady LP''.<ref name=\"Hilburn\">{{cite news|last=Hilburn|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Hilburn|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/may/20/entertainment/ca-31967|title=Eminem's Latest Seems Sure to Delight Fans, Anger Parents|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 20, 2000|accessdate=June 12, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812004414/http://articles.latimes.com/2000/may/20/entertainment/ca-31967|archivedate=August 12, 2013}}</ref> Much of the album is spent addressing his rise to fame and attacking those who criticized his previous album. Other themes include his relationship with his family, including his mother and Kim Mathers, his ex-wife.<ref name=\"divorce\">{{cite news|title=Eminem and Kim to divorce again|work=BBC News|date = April 6, 2006|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4882092.stm|accessdate=May 27, 2009}}</ref> Unlike Eminem's major-label debut, ''The Slim Shady LP'', ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' is more introspective in its lyrics and uses less of the Slim Shady persona, with [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] writing that the album's lyrics \"[blur] the distinction between reality and fiction, humor and horror, satire and documentary\".<ref name=\"allmusic review\" /> The record showcases a variety of moods, ranging from irreverent and humorous to \"dark and unsettling enough to make you want to enlarge the parental warning stickers on the album.\"<ref name=\"Hilburn\" /> According to [[Neil Strauss]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'', \"Eminem never makes it clear which character\u2014Slim Shady or Marshall Mathers\u2014is the mask and which is the real person, because there is no clear-cut answer, except that there's a little bit of each character in all of us.\"<ref name=\"Strauss\">{{cite news|last=Strauss|first=Neil|authorlink=Neil Strauss|date=June 7, 2000|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/06/07/arts/the-pop-life-eminem-enters-n-sync-turf.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|title=THE POP LIFE; Eminem Enters 'N Sync Turf|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMost songs cover Eminem's childhood struggles and family issues, involving his mother (\"Kill You\"), the relationship struggles with his wife (\"[[Kim (song)|Kim]]\"), his struggles with his superstardom and expectations (\"Stan\", \"I'm Back\", and \"Marshall Mathers\"), his return and effect on the music industry (\"Remember Me?\", \"Bitch Please II\"), his drug use (\"Drug Ballad\", \"The Kids\"), his effect on the American youth and society (\"[[The Way I Am (Eminem song)|The Way I Am]]\", \"Who Knew\"), and reactionary barbs to critical response of his vulgarity and dark themes (\"Criminal\").<ref name=\"ign\">{{cite web|title=The Marshall Mathers LP Review|author=Spence D.|work=IGN|date=November 12, 2004|url=http://music.ign.com/articles/565/565974p1.html|accessdate=May 27, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101216070703/http://music.ign.com/articles/565/565974p1.html|archivedate=December 16, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Despite the large amount of controversy regarding the lyrics, the lyrics on the album were overwhelmingly well received among critics and the [[hip hop]] community, many praising Eminem's verbal energy and dense rhyme patterns.<ref name=\"RS review\">{{cite web |author=Tour\u00e9 |authorlink=Tour\u00e9 (journalist) |title=''The Marshall Mathers LP'' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/the-marshall-mathers-lp-20000706 |date=July 6, 2000 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=February 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe record also contains lyrics that have been considered to be [[Homophobia|homophobic]].<ref name=\"badrap\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aWMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA71&lpg=PA71&dq=the+marshall+mathers+lp+lyrics&source=bl&ots=ADXfXXCNBb&sig=dGoMTFsfbDBUVDct2M5KECoofZc&hl=en&sa=X&ei=H2AbUMvlDcSEjAKEq4FI&ved=0CEsQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=the%20marshall%20mathers%20lp%20lyrics&f=false|title=A Bad Rap?|last=White|first=Dave|date=July 4, 2000|accessdate=August 2, 2012|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|publisher=[[Here Media]]}}</ref> The song \"Criminal\" features the line \"My words are like a dagger with a jagged edge/That'll stab you in the head whether you're a [[Faggot (slang)|fag]] or [[Lesbian|les]]...Hate fags?/The answer's yes\".<ref name=\"badrap\" /> The [[Gay & Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation]] (GLAAD) condemned his lyrics and criticized the album for \"encourag[ing] violence against gay men and lesbians\".<ref name=\"Hasted162\">Hasted, 2011. p. 162</ref> However, writing for the [[LGBT]] interest magazine ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'', editor Dave White writes, \"If he has gay-bashed you or me, then it logically follows that he has also raped his own mother, killed his wife, and murdered his producer, Dr. Dre. If he's to be taken literally, then so is [[Britney Spears]]' invitation to '[[...Baby One More Time (song)|hit me baby, one more time]]'.\"<ref name=\"badrap\" /> Eminem noted that he began using the word \"faggot\" more frequently when \"people got all up in arms about it...to piss them off worse\", but added, \"I think it's hard for some people to understand that for me the word 'faggot' has nothing to do with sexual preference. I meant something more like assholes or dickheads.\"<ref name=\"Eminem54\">Eminem, 2008. p. 54</ref>\n\n== Songs ==\n{{Listen|pos = right\n |filename     = 02 Kill You.ogg \n |title        = \"Kill You\"\n |description  = The second song on the album, \"Kill You\" exemplifies the album's over-the-top descriptions of violence, confrontational vocal delivery, and criticism of the media, record label expectations, and Eminem's mother.\n |filename2    = Eminem - Stan (Album Version).ogg\n |title2       = \"Stan\"\n |description2 = The album's third single has been referred to as the album's centerpiece and features a sample of [[Dido (singer)|Dido]]'s \"[[Thank You (Dido song)|Thank You]]\". During the verses, Eminem portrays both himself and an obsessive fan, with pen-scratching sounds in the background to indicate communication via letters.\n}}\n\nThe first track, \"Kill You\", discusses the controversy that surrounded the rapper's first album, nightmares of \"ladies' screams\", and being raised by a single mother.<ref name=\"EW review\" /> In the song, Eminem also talks of raping his mother, and \"notes the irony of magazines trumpeting his mother-raping self on their covers'.\"<ref name=\"EW review\" /> The six-and-a-half minute long \"Stan\" samples Dido's \"Thank You\" and tells the story of an exchange between the rapper and an obsessive fan, where the titular character berates Eminem for not responding to his letters, which later turns to the fan committing suicide with his pregnant wife.<ref name=\"Hasted 68\">Hasted, p. 68</ref> On \"Who Knew\", the rapper addresses criticism regarding glorification of violence in his lyrics, pointing out perceived hypocrisy in American society. According to Gabriel Alvarez of ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'', Eminem's response ranges oscillates from \"smart-ass ('Oh, you want me to watch my mouth, how?/Take my fuckin' eyeballs out and turn 'em around?') to smart ('Ain't they got the same moms and dads who got mad when I asked if they liked violence?/And told me that my tape taught 'em to swear/What about the makeup you allow your 12-year-old daughter to wear?').\"<ref name=complexwhoknew>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/the-best-eminem-songs-of-all-time/eminem-who-knew|title=Eminem's 100 Greatest Songs: Who Knew|work=Complex|publisher=Complex Media Inc|last=Alvarez|first=Gabriel|date=December 18, 2017|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref> \"Who Knew\" is followed by the \"Steve Berman\" skit, where the president of sales at Interscope Records angrily confronts the rapper about his lyrical content. He notes that Dr. Dre was successful because he rapped about \"big-screen TVs, blunts, 40's, and bitches\", while Eminem raps about \"homosexuals and Vicodin\", and believes that the album will be a commercial disaster.<ref name=xxl>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2015/05/12-facts-eminem-marshall-mathers-lp/|title=12 Facts You Might Not Know About Eminem's 'The Marshall Mathers LP'|last=Rys|first=Dan|date=May 22, 2015|accessdate=April 29, 2018|work=XXL|publisher=Townsquare Media}}</ref>\n\n\"The Way I Am\" is a meditation on the pressure to maintain his fame, and his fear of being \"pigeon-holed into some poppy sensation/to cop me rotation at rock 'n' roll stations\".<ref name=\"Vanhoozer8384\">Vanhoozer, pp. 83\u201384</ref> He also laments the negative media attention received by controversial public figures such as himself and [[Marilyn Manson]] in the wake of shootings, including the [[Columbine High School massacre]] and the West Side Middle School shooting in [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]]. The rapper criticizes the media for focusing on tragedies such as school shootings while ignoring inner-city violence that occurs on a daily basis.<ref name=\"Vanhoozer8384\" /> \"The Real Slim Shady\" pokes fun at pop culture icons such as [[Britney Spears]], [[Christina Aguilera]] and [[Will Smith]].<ref name=\"Ellis256\">Ellis, p. 256</ref> \"Remember Me?\" follows and features rappers [[RBX]] and [[Sticky Fingaz]], who \"kick seriously [[Stygia (Conan)|Stygian]] darkness on the ominous track\".<ref name=\"ign\" /> In the song, he states \"I'm tryna clean up my fuckin' image / So I promised the fuckin' critics / I wouldn't say 'fuckin' for six minutes/(Six minutes, Slim Shady, you're on)\". Despite saying the word \"fuck\" one more time in \"Remember Me\", and three times at the beginning of \"I'm Back\", he does not say the word \"fuckin\" for seven minutes and 29 seconds after delivering the original promise, saying it again in the song \"Marshall Mathers\".<ref name=xxl/>\n\n{{Listen|pos = right\n |filename     = 11 Marshall Mathers.ogg \n |title        = \"Marshall Mathers\"\n |description  = This song, with its sparse, minimalist production featuring an acoustic guitar, is a diss track aimed at pop artists such as [[NSYNC]], [[Ricky Martin]], and [[Britney Spears]]. It also expresses frustration at people who have tried to use Eminem for his fame.\n |filename2    = 16 Kim Eminem.ogg\n |title2       = \"Kim\"\n |description2 = The album's most controversial track, \"Kim\" is a chaotic murder fantasy where Eminem plays both himself and the voice of his wife Kim. The production samples \"[[When the Levee Breaks]]\" by [[Led Zeppelin]].\n}}\n\"I'm Back\" features Eminem's observations regarding his rise to fame, explaining that he \"became a commodity/'Cause I'm W-H-I-T-E\".<ref name=\"EW review\" /> The next song, \"Marshall Mathers\", mocks the chorus of [[LFO (American band)|LFO]]'s \"[[Summer Girls]]\", while criticizing the lack of artistic merit of pop stars such as [[Britney Spears]], the [[Backstreet Boys]], [[NSYNC]], and [[Ricky Martin]]. The song also takes aim at rap duo called [[Insane Clown Posse|ICP]] (Insane Clown Posse), where Eminem raps about [[Violent J]] and [[Shaggy 2 Dope]] being flaming [[homosexuals]].<ref name=\"Ellis256\" /><ref name=\"ghero\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2000/jun/18/features.review37|title=Misogynist, homophobe... hero|last=Wazir|first=Burhan|date=June 18, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014|work=The Guardian}}</ref> \"Drug Ballad\" features Dina Rae<ref name=\"stubbs128\">{{cite book|title=Eminem: The Stories Behind Every Song|publisher=[[Thunder's Mouth Press]]|last=Stubbs|first=David|ISBN=978-1560259466|page=128|quote=Dina Rae sweetens the deal with some funky vocal flourishes}}</ref> and describes the rapper's struggles with his drug addiction, and writes about some of his experiences under the influence, including ecstasy which makes him \"sentimental as fuck, spilling guts to you/we just met, but I think I'm in love with you\".<ref name=\"xfactor\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_icEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA198&dq=drug+ballad+eminem&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6lX2Us3nM6zNsQTfuoLICg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=drug%20ballad%20eminem&f=false|title=The X-Factor|last=Louie|first=Rebecca|work=Vibe|publisher=Vibe Media Group|date=September 2000|accessdate=February 8, 2014}}</ref> \"Amityville\" is a bass-heavy ode to living in Detroit, where the rapper discusses the city's crowning as murder capital of the United States.<ref name=\"RS review\" /> \"Bitch Please II\" features [[Dr. Dre]], [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Nate Dogg]], and [[Xzibit]], and contains elements of [[g-funk]], as well as [[R&B]] crooning from [[Nate Dogg]] on the chorus.<ref name=\"ign\" />\n\n\"Kim\", the prequel to \"97 Bonnie and Clyde\" from ''[[The Slim Shady LP]]'', features Eminem \"screaming at his ex in an insane stream-of-consciousness hate spew\".<ref name=\"RS review\" /> The song begins with Eminem talking softly to his daughter, but as the beat starts, the rapper takes on portraying two characters, utilizing his own enraged, threatening voice, and the terrified shrieks of his wife Kim.<ref name=\"Vanhoozer85\">Vanhoozer, p. 85</ref> As the song ends, Eminem kills her while taunting, \"Bleed, bitch, bleed!\"<ref name=\"Vanhoozer85\" /> \"Kim\" is followed by \"Under the Influence\", which sees Eminem speaking in gibberish for the chorus, and later rap group [[D12]] \"runs rampant\" on the track.<ref name=\"ign\" /> \"Criminal\" features production from F.B.T., which consists of \"piano licks, swerving synth, and a deceptively simplistic bass rumble over which Em snakes and snarls and warns that 'you can't stop me from topping these charts...'\".<ref name=\"ign\" /> He pokes fun at critics who take his lyrical content seriously, explaining that \"half the shit I say, I just make it up to make you mad\".<ref name=\"sinsandsorrows\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=50Phz-C_VzIC&pg=PA91&dq=the+sins+and+sorrows+of+marshall+mathers+eminem&hl=en&sa=X&ei=bF_2Uv7xGPTJsQTqr4HgDQ&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=the%20sins%20and%20sorrows%20of%20marshall%20mathers%20eminem&f=false|title=The Sins and Sorrows of Marshall Mathers|last=Rubin|first=Mike|date=August 2000|accessdate=February 10, 2014|work=Spin|publisher=Spin Media LLC}}</ref>\n\n== Censorship ==\n[[File:Hope Columbine Memorial Library.jpg|thumb|left|Lyrics referencing the [[Columbine High School massacre]] were censored on ''The Marshall Mathers LP'']]\nIn his book ''Edited Clean Version: Technology and the Culture of Control'', author Raiford Guins writes that the clean version of ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' \"resembles a cross between a cell phone chat with terrible reception...and a noted hip-hop lyricist suffering from an incurable case of hiccups.\"<ref name=\"Guins12\">Guins, 2008. p. 12</ref> This version of the album often either omits words completely or obscures them with added sound effects.<ref name=\"Guins12\" /> The clean version of the album did not censor all profanity. Words like \"ass\", \"bitch\", \"goddamn\", and \"shit\" were uncensored. However, on the track \"The Real Slim Shady\", the words \"bitch\" and \"shit\" were censored out, as they used the clean version released for radio. References to violence and weapons were also significantly altered, and the songs \"Kill You\", \"Drug Ballad\" and \"Bitch Please II\" are written as \"**** You\", \"Ballad\" and \"***** Please II\" on the back cover of the album.<ref name=\"Guins12\" /> The song \"Kim\" is removed completely and replaced by the ''[[South Park]]''-themed \"The Kids\".<ref name=\"Bozza83\">Bozza, 2003. p. 83</ref>\n\nSignificant edits were made to aggressive and violent lyrics that were aimed at police, prostitutes, women, homosexuals, bullies and schools. In response to [[Columbine High School massacre|the attack]] that had occurred at [[Columbine High School]] in April 1999, names of guns and sounds of them firing were censored.  Interscope Records insisted on censoring the words \"kids\" and \"Columbine\" from the line, \"I take seven [kids] from [Columbine], stand them all in line\" from \"I'm Back\", even on the explicit version of the album.<ref name=\"sinsandsorrows\" /> Mike Rubin of ''Spin'' called the censorship a \"curious decision, given that lyrics like 'Take drugs / Rape sluts' are apparently permissible\".<ref name=\"sinsandsorrows\" /> Eminem commented on his lyrics regarding the shooting, \"That Columbine shit is so fucking touchy. As much sympathy as we give the Columbine shootings, nobody ever looked at it from the fuckin' point of view of the kids who were bullied\u2014I mean, they took their own fucking life! And it was because they were pushed so far to the fucking edge that they were fucking so mad. I've ''been'' that mad.\"<ref name=\"sinsandsorrows\" /> The full line appears uncensored in Eminem's song \"[[Rap God]]\" from ''[[The Marshall Mathers LP 2]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.detroitnews.com/article/20131014/ENT04/310140108/Emimem-strikes-again-Rap-God-single | title=Emimem strikes again with 'Rap God' single| work=[[The Detroit News]] | date=October 14, 2013 | accessdate=October 15, 2013 | author=Graham, Adam}}</ref> The line \"It doesn't matter [your attorney Fred Gibson's a] faggot\" was also censored from \"Marshall Mathers\", which refers to his mother Debbie Nelson's lawyer, who assisted her in filing a lawsuit against the rapper for defamation regarding lyrics from ''[[The Slim Shady LP]]''.<ref name=\"emvsmom\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X7-GZm2de98C&pg=PA36&dq=eminem+fred+gibson&hl=en&sa=X&ei=OdD2UrWJOLawsASN9IH4Cw&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=eminem%20fred%20gibson&f=false|title=Eminem vs. M.O.M|last=Herzog|first=Kenny|work=Spin|publisher=Spin Media LLC|date=December 2008|accessdate=February 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Release and commercial performance ==\n[[File:Eminem Up in Smoke Tour.jpg|thumb|Eminem (left) at the [[ARCO Arena]] for the [[Up in Smoke Tour]], in June 2000, a month after the album's release]]\nEminem considered naming the album ''Amsterdam'' after a trip to [[Amsterdam|the city]] shortly after the release of ''[[The Slim Shady LP]]'', in which he and his friends engaged in heavy drug use.<ref name=\"Eminem66\">Eminem, 2008. p. 66</ref> The \"free\" use of drugs Eminem observed during his time in Amsterdam greatly influenced his desire to openly discuss drug use in his music and inspired some of the content on the album.<ref name=\"Eminem66\" /><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/02/50-things-you-didnt-know-about-eminem/amsterdam |title=The Marshall Mathers LP was originally titled Amsterdam because he wrote a good chunk of the album there, and Dutch journalists inspired some of the content on the album. \u2014 50 Things You Didn't Know About Eminem |magazine=Complex |date=February 21, 2013 |accessdate=January 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n''The Marshall Mathers LP'' was released on May 23, 2000, by [[Aftermath Entertainment]], [[Interscope Records]], in the United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tower.com/marshall-mathers-lp-eminem-cd/wapi/106446930|title=Music: The Marshall Mathers LP (CD) by Eminem (Artist)|publisher=[[Tower Records (music retailer)|Tower Records]]|accessdate=September 26, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015124807/http://www.tower.com/marshall-mathers-lp-eminem-cd/wapi/106446930|archivedate=October 15, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and on 11 September 2000, by [[Polydor Records]] in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"Tower2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tower.com/marshall-mathers-lp-eminem-cd/wapi/106447372|title=Music: Marshall Mathers Lp (CD) by Eminem (Artist), 106447372|publisher=Tower Records|accessdate=September 26, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926045926/http://www.tower.com/marshall-mathers-lp-eminem-cd/wapi/106447372|archivedate=September 26, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' was released with two different album covers. The original features Eminem sitting on the porch of the house he lived in during his teenage years.<ref name=\"Eminemvh1\" /> He reflected on the photo shoot by saying, \"I had mixed feelings because I had a lot of good and bad memories in that house. But to go back to where I grew up and finally say, 'I've made it', is the greatest feeling in the world to me.\"<ref name=\"Eminemvh1\" /> The other cover features the rapper seated in a fetal position beneath a [[loading dock]] with alcohol and prescription pill bottles at his feet.<ref name=\"EW review\" /> Will Hermes of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' likened Eminem's appearance on the cover to a \"dysfunctional [[Our Gang|Little Rascal]]\", viewing the image as indicative of the rapper's musical evolution: \"Easy to read, right? The debut: a violent fantasy, the acting-out of a persona. The follow-up: the vulnerable artist unmasked.\"<ref name=\"EW review\" />\n\n''The Marshall Mathers LP'' sold 1.76 million copies in its first week, which made it the fastest-selling rap album in history and also was fastest selling album by a solo artist until [[Adele]] surpassed the record with ''[[25 (Adele album)|25]]'' in November 2015, selling over 3 million copies first week.  It sold twice as much as the previous record holder, [[Snoop Dogg]]'s 1993 album ''[[Doggystyle]]'', and also topped [[Britney Spears]]' record for highest 1-week sales by any solo artist.<ref name=\"Sales\">{{cite web |author=Skanse, Richard |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5923810/eminem_bounces_britney_from_top_spot |title=Eminem Bounces Britney From Top Spot |accessdate=December 20, 2008 |work=Rolling Stone |date=May 31, 2000 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080503141820/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5923810/eminem_bounces_britney_from_top_spot |archivedate =May 3, 2008}}</ref> The album sold over 800,000 in its 2nd week, 600,000 in its 3rd week, and 520,000 copies in its 4th week for a 4-week total of 3.65 million. It also became one of the few albums to sell over half a million copies for 4  consecutive weeks. In total, the album spent 8 weeks at #1 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] music chart, good enough for 4th on the current all-time list of weeks spent at #1 by a Hip-Hop album.<ref name=\"billboard7-3-2016\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7424028/drake-views-no-1-for-ninth-week-on-billboard-200-album-chart|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|title=Drake's 'Views' No. 1 For Ninth Week on Billboard 200 Chart|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=July 3, 2016|accessdate=July 3, 2016}}</ref> By the end of 2000, ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' had become the second highest-selling album of the year with over 8 million sold.<ref name=\"Soundscan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.avrev.com/news/0101/03.soundscan.shtml|title=SoundScan List of Best Sellers \u2013 2000|accessdate=December 22, 2008|date=January 3, 2001|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222171637/http://www.avrev.com/news/0101/03.soundscan.shtml|archivedate=December 22, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe album's 1st single, \"[[The Real Slim Shady]]\", became Eminem's biggest hit up to that point and peaked at #4 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] music chart and topping the UK Singles Charts.<ref name=emUKcharts>{{cite web|title=Eminem UK charts|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/eminem/|publisher=Official Charts Company}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite magazine|title=Eminem Chart History|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/301722/eminem/chart?page=3&f=379|magazine=Billboard}}</ref> \"The Way I Am\", which was released as the album's second single, peaked at #8 on the UK Singles Chart<ref name=emUKcharts/> and #58 on the Billboard Hot 100 music chart. \"Stan\", the 3rd single released from the album, became a #1 hit in both the United Kingdom<ref name=emUKcharts/> and Australia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stan chart position|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Eminem+feat.+Dido&titel=Stan&cat=s|publisher=Australian-charts.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, the Nielsen Company reported that up until November 2009, ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' had sold 10,216,000 copies in the US, making it the 4th-best selling album of the decade.<ref>[http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20100106007077/en/2009-U.S.-Music-Purchases-2.1-2008-Music \"2009 U.S. Music Purchases up 2.1% over 2008; Music Sales Exceed 1.5 Billion for Second Consecutive Year\"]. January 6, 2010. businesswire.com. Business Wire. Retrieved July 14, 2010.</ref> By February 2014, ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' had sold 10,818,000 copies in the United States, being Eminem's best selling album in his home country.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Tardio|first=Andres|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.27372/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-2-2-2014|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: Week Ending 2/2/2014|magazine=[[HipHopDX]]|date=February 5, 2014|accessdate=February 5, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222021817/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.27372/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-2-2-2014|archive-date=February 22, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' sold at least 10 million copies in the United States.<ref name=\"SalesintheUSA\" /> ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' has sold 21 million copies worldwide, making it one of the [[List of best-selling albums|best-selling albums of all time]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hypable.com/how-much-risk-is-eminem-taking-by-releasing-mmlp2/|title=How much risk is Eminem taking by releasing The Marshall Mathers LP 2?|date=2013-08-28|website=Hypable|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://planetradio.co.uk/metro/entertainment/music/rihanna-guests-eminem-marshall-mathers-lp-2/|title=Rihanna Guests On Eminem's 'The Marshall Mathers LP 2'|date=2013-10-11|website=Metro Radio|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/eminem-tweets-marshall-mathers-lp-2-artwork-20130921|title=Eminem Tweets Marshall Mathers LP 2 Artwork|last=Cashmere|first=Paul|date=2013-09-21|website=Noise11.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref><ref name=\"pitchfork review\"/> A sequel to the album, ''[[The Marshall Mathers LP 2]]'', was released on November 5, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|author=Erin Coulehan |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/eminem-announces-new-album-mmlp2-20130825 |title=Eminem Announces New Album 'Marshall Mathers LP 2' &#124; Music News |work=Rolling Stone |date=August 25, 2013 |accessdate=January 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 78/100<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n| title = Contemporary reviews\n| rev1 = ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4540882.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180914165348/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4540882.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 14, 2018 |title=Eminem, 'The Marshall Mathers LP' (Interscope) |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=June 4, 2000 |accessdate=September 14, 2018 |last=Kyles |first=Kyra |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev2Score = A\u2212<ref name=\"EW review\" />\n| rev3 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref name=\"Hilburn\" />\n| rev4 = ''[[Melody Maker]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"MelodyMaker\" />\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5Score = 9/10<ref name=\"NME review\" />\n| rev6 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Qmag\" />\n| rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"RS review\"/>\n| rev8 = ''[[The Source]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Eminem: ''The Marshall Mathers LP''|magazine=[[The Source]]|issue=131|date=August 2000|pages=225\u201326}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[USA Today]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref name=\"Jones\"/>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev10Score = A<ref name=\"Christgau review\" />\n}}\n''The Marshall Mathers LP'' was met with generally positive reviews. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 78, based on 21 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-marshall-mathers-lp/eminem |title=Reviews for ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' by Eminem |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=March 19, 2009}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's [[Tour\u00e9 (journalist)|Tour\u00e9]] complimented Dr. Dre's production and Eminem's varied lyrical style on what is a \"car-crash record: loud, wild, dangerous, out of control, grotesque, unsettling\", but ultimately captivating.<ref name=\"RS review\" /> ''[[Melody Maker]]'' said that Eminem's startlingly intense vision of \"rap's self-consciousness\" is truly unique,<ref name=\"MelodyMaker\">{{cite journal|title=Eminem: ''The Marshall Mathers LP''|journal=[[Melody Maker]]|date=June 6, 2000|page=54|quote=No one else puts such a rocket under rap's self-consciousness or makes it so shocking...}}</ref> while Steve Sutherland of ''[[NME]]'' praised the album as a [[misanthropy|misanthropic]] and \"gruelling assault course of lyrical genius\" that critiques malevolent aspects of contemporary society.<ref name=\"NME review\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.nme.com:80/reviews/reviews/20000530100111.html |title=Eminem \u2013 ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' |work=[[NME]] |date=May 30, 2000 |accessdate=October 1, 2009 |last=Sutherland |first=Steve |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000816103739/http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/20000530100111.html |archivedate=August 16, 2000 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Chuck Eddy]] from ''[[The Village Voice]]'' said that Eminem is backed by attractive music and displays an emotionally complex and witting quality unlike his previous work.<ref name=\"Voice review\">{{cite news |author=Eddy, Chuck |title=Motor Suburb Madhouse |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2000-07-04/music/motor-suburb-madhouse/1/|date=July 4, 2000 |newspaper=[[The Village Voice]] |accessdate=August 25, 2010 |authorlink=Chuck Eddy}}</ref> In the newspaper's consumer guide column, [[Robert Christgau]] called him \"exceptionally witty and musical, discernibly thoughtful and good-hearted, indubitably dangerous and full of shit\", while declaring the album \"a work of art whose immense entertainment value in no way compromises its intimations of a pathology that's both personal and political\".<ref name=\"Christgau review\">{{cite news |last=Christgau |first=Robert |title=Getting Them Straight |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2000-08-15/music/getting-them-straight/1/|date=August 15, 2000 |work=[[The Village Voice]] |accessdate=August 25, 2010 |authorlink=Robert Christgau}}</ref> [[Will Hermes]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' wrote that as the first significant [[popular music]] album of the 2000s, ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' is \"indefensible and critic-proof, hypocritical and heartbreaking, unlistenable and undeniable\".<ref name=\"EW review\">{{cite news |last=Hermes |first=Will |authorlink=Will Hermes |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,276305,00.html |title=''The Marshall Mathers LP'' |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=June 2, 2000 |accessdate=October 1, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, music journalist [[Greg Kot]] said the reaction to ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' was \"mixed\", or reluctantly positive, among critics who praised Eminem's \"verbal skills and [[Transgressive art|transgressive]] humor\" but decried some of the subject matter.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kot|first=Greg|authorlink=Greg Kot|date=July 2, 2000|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-07-02/news/0007020281_1_slim-shady-lp-eminem-dr-dre|title=The Rap That Dre Built|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref> In his review for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', [[Robert Hilburn]] reserved his praise because of homophobic lyrics on what he felt is an otherwise conceptual and personal work, \"docked a half star because of the recurring homophobia\u2014something that may be [[de rigueur]] in commercial rap, but which still is unacceptable.\"<ref name=\"Hilburn\" /> Steve Jones of ''[[USA Today]]'' opined that Eminem's \"vicious and patently personal lyrical assaults\" would \"almost grow tedious if he weren't as inventive as he is tasteless.\"<ref name=\"Jones\">{{cite news |author=Jones, Steve |url=https://www.usatoday.com:80/life/music/rap.htm |title=Eminem's 'Mathers LP' luridly lyrical |work=[[USA Today]] |date=May 23, 2000 |accessdate=October 1, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000815210414/http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/rap.htm |archivedate=August 15, 2000 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' magazine felt that the subject matter does not make for an enjoyable listen, even though Eminem's disaffected and nihilistic lyrics can be provocative.<ref name=\"Qmag\">{{cite journal|last=Lowe|first=Steve|url=http://www.qonline.co.uk/reviews/server.asp?id=18934|title=Eminem: ''The Marshall Mathers LP''|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|issue=167|page=98|date=August 2000|accessdate=June 4, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001205064000/http://www.qonline.co.uk/reviews/server.asp?id=18934|archivedate=December 5, 2000}}</ref> ''[[Slant Magazine]]''{{'}}s Sal Cinquemani was more critical in a one-and-a-half star review and found his raps extremely distasteful: \"The only thing worse than Eminem's homophobia is the immaturity with which he displays it\".<ref name=\"Slant review\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/eminem-the-marshall-mathers-lp/63|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|author=Cinquemani, Sal|title=Eminem: The Marshall Mathers LP |date=January 16, 2001|accessdate=August 25, 2010}}</ref> On the other hand, ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' felt that the rapping is excellent, but plagued more so by unremarkable music and lackluster tracks.<ref name=\"Spin\">{{cite journal|title=Eminem: ''The Marshall Mathers LP''|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date=May 20, 2000|quote=Funny how so much controversy can spring up over an album that is, musically, not all that noteworthy ... what could have been a brilliant statement, instead elevates Eminem to the rarefied air of true platinum rappers: ie, those that drop outstanding rhymes over frustratingly mediocre beats.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' won in the Best Album category at the [[MTV Europe Music Awards]].<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1428564/.jhtml|title=Madonna, Eminem Lead American Romp Through EMAs |accessdate=September 14, 2011 |work= |publisher=|date=November 17, 2000}}</ref> It also won in the [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Album|Best Rap Album]] category at the [[43rd Annual Grammy Awards]] in 2001.<ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/story/2001/02/22/grammy_list010222.html|title=Complete list of Grammy Award winners |accessdate=September 14, 2011 |work= CBC News|publisher=|date=February 22, 2001}}</ref> ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]], but lost to [[Jazz fusion|jazz-rock]] duo [[Steely Dan]]'s ''[[Two Against Nature]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/awards/43rd-annual-grammy-awards|title=43rd Annual GRAMMY Awards|publisher=Grammy.com|access-date=2016-07-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Reappraisal ===\n{{Album ratings\n| title = Retrospective professional reviews\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic review\">{{cite web |author=Erlewine, Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-marshall-mathers-lp-mw0000062949 |title=''The Marshall Mathers LP'' \u2013 Eminem |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 1, 2009}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin (writer)|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]|page=959|chapter=Eminem|year=2011|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|isbn=0857125958|edition=5th concise}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Great Rock Discography]]''\n| rev3Score = 9/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/061024/A1082.htm|title=The Marshall Mathers LP|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev4Score = 9.4/10<ref name=\"pitchfork review\">{{cite web |author=Larson, Jeremy D. |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/eminem-the-marshall-mathers-lp/ |title=Eminem: ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=April 15, 2018 |accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"RSguide\">{{cite book|editor1-last=Brackett|editor1-first=Nathan|editor2-last=Hoard|editor2-first=Christian|last=Hoard|first=Christian|chapter=Eminem|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t9eocwUfoSoC&pg=PA276#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=June 12, 2012|title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|edition=4th|isbn=978-0-7432-0169-8|pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/276 276\u201377]}}</ref>\n| rev6 = [[Sputnikmusic]]\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Iai|date=January 16, 2005|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/1440/Eminem-The-Marshall-Mathers-LP/|title=Eminem - The Marshall Mathers LP (album review 16)|website=[[Sputnikmusic]]|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\nSince its initial release, ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' has been met with widespread critical acclaim in retrospective reviews. According to [[Sputnikmusic]]'s Nick Butler, ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' stands as a culturally significant record in American popular music, but also \"remains a truly special album, unique in rap's canon, owing its spirit to rock and its heritage to rap, in a way I've rarely heard\".<ref name=\"Sputnikmusic review\">{{cite web|url=http://sputnikmusic.com/review/1440/Eminem-The-Marshall-Mathers-LP/|work=[[Sputnikmusic]]|author=Butler, Nick|title=Eminem \u2013 The Marshall Mathers LP (staff review)|date=January 16, 2005|accessdate=August 25, 2010}}</ref> In ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]'' (2004), Christian Hoard said that the album \"delved much deeper into personal pain [than ''The Slim Shady LP''], and the result was a minor masterpiece that merged iller-than-[[wikt:ill|ill]] [[flow (music)|flow]]s with a brilliant sense of the [[macabre]].\"<ref name=\"RSguide\" />\n\nIn 2003, ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' was ranked number 302 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''<nowiki/>'s list of [[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]];<ref name=\"RollingStone1\">[https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5938174/the_rs_500_greatest_albums_of_all_time/4 The RS 500 Greatest Albums of All Time: Rolling Stone] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100407053745/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5938174/the_rs_500_greatest_albums_of_all_time/4|date=April 7, 2010}}</ref> it was moved up to number 244 in the magazine's revised 2012 edition of the list.<ref name=\"RollingStone2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/eminem-the-marshall-mathers-lp-20120524|title=Eminem, 'The Marshall Mathers LP'|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> [[IGN]] named it the twenty-fourth greatest rap album of all time in a 2004 list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.ign.com/articles/754/754994p2.html|title=''IGN.com'' \u2013 Top 25 Rap Albums|author=Spence D. + Miscellaneous IGN Editors|publisher=Music.ign.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527122217/http://music.ign.com/articles/754/754994p2.html|archivedate=May 27, 2011|accessdate=August 3, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  In 2006, ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' was included by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' in its list of the 100 Greatest Albums of All Time.<ref name=\"TIME1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/2006/100albums/index.html |title=''TIME.com'' \u2013 The All-TIME 100 Albums |publisher=Time.com |date= November 2, 2006|accessdate=August 3, 2011}}</ref> That same year, ''Q'' ranked it number 85 on a list of The Greatest Albums of All Time, the highest position held by any hip hop album on the list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mp3sparks.com/awards/awards_q100.shtml |title=''2006 Q Magazine'' \u2014 100 Greatest Albums Ever |publisher=Mp3sparks.com |date= |accessdate=August 3, 2011}}</ref> ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' was also the highest ranked hip hop album on the [[National Association of Recording Merchandisers]] & the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]'s list of the 200 Definitive Albums of All Time, where it was placed at number 28.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.definitive200.com/200_list.php |publisher=Definitive200.com (Rock and Roll Hall of Fame) |title=The Definitive 200 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070309200014/http://definitive200.com/200_list.php |archivedate=March 9, 2007}}</ref> It has been named one of the Top 100 Albums of the Decade (2000s) by ''Rolling Stone'', who ranked it seventh,<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\">{{cite web |author=Nigel D. |url=http://realtalkny.uproxx.com/2009/12/topic/topic/discussions/rolling-stones-top-100-albums-of-the-decade/ |title=Rolling Stones Top 100 Albums Of The Decade &#124; RealTalkNY |publisher=Realtalkny.uproxx.com |date=December 10, 2009 |accessdate=August 3, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725101858/http://realtalkny.uproxx.com/2009/12/topic/topic/discussions/rolling-stones-top-100-albums-of-the-decade/ |archivedate=July 25, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] Magazine'', who ranked it fourth,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://best.complex.com/2000s/Top-100-Albums/the-marshall-mathers-lp |title=The Marshall Mathers LP &#124; Top 100 Albums &#124; Best of the 2000s |publisher=Best.complex.com |accessdate=May 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090912053928/http://best.complex.com/2000s/Top-100-Albums/the-marshall-mathers-lp |archive-date=September 12, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'', who ranked it 119th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/7707-the-top-200-albums-of-the-2000s-150-101/4/|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|author=''Pitchfork'' staff|title=The Top 200 Albums of the 2000s: 150\u2013101|date=September 28, 2009|accessdate=October 1, 2009}}</ref> In 2010, [[Rhapsody (online music service)|Rhapsody]] ranked it at number 1 on their list of \"The 10 Best Albums by White Rappers\".<ref>[http://blog.rhapsody.com/2010/06/whiterappers.html The 10 Best Albums By White Rappers] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120716211119/http://blog.rhapsody.com/2010/06/whiterappers.html |date=July 16, 2012 }} Retrieved June 26, 2010</ref> In 2015, the album was ranked number 81 by ''About.com'' on their list of 100 Best Hip-Hop Albums of All Time.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adaso|first1=Henry|title=100 Best hip-hop albums|url=http://rap.about.com/od/toppicks/tp/100-Best-Hip-Hop-Albums.01.htm|website=About.com|accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>  The album was also included in the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Robert Dimery|author2=Michael Lydon|title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die: Revised and Updated Edition|accessdate= |date=23 March 2010|publisher=Universe|isbn=978-0-7893-2074-2}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n===Reactions from politicians===\n{{Quote box|align=right|width=25em|quote = \"Nobody is excluded from my poking at. Nobody. I don't discriminate, I don't exclude nobody. If you do something fucked up, you're bound to be made fun of. If I do something fucked up, I'll make fun of myself\u2014I'm not excluded from this.\"|source =\u2014Eminem, on the album's controversy.<ref name=\"Bozza61\">Bozza, 2003. p. 61</ref>}}\nAt a [[United States Senate]] hearing, [[Lynne Cheney]] criticized Eminem and sponsor [[Seagram]] for \"promot[ing] violence of the most degrading kind against women\", labeling him as \"a rap singer who advocates murder and rape\".<ref name=\"hearing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1428579/eminem-targeted-at-senate-hearing.jhtml|title=Eminem Targeted At Senate Hearing|last=Mancini|first=Robert|work=MTV News|publisher=Viacom|date=September 13, 2000|accessdate=February 9, 2014}}</ref> She specifically cited lyrics from \"Kill You\", explaining, \"He talks about murdering and raping his mother. He talks about choking women slowly so he can hear their screams for a long time. He talks about using [[O.J. Simpson|O.J.]]'s machete on women, and this is a man who is honored by the recording industry\".<ref name=\"hearing\" /> Cheney drew a link between the [[Columbine High School massacre|Columbine massacre]] and violent music, mentioning artists Eminem and [[Marilyn Manson]] as musicians who contribute to the United States' culture of violence.  Although she stated that she has \"long been a vocal supporter of free speech\", Cheney called for the music industry to impose age-restrictions on those who can purchase music with violent content.<ref name=\"hearing\" />\n\nOn October 26, 2000, Eminem was to perform at a concert in Toronto's [[SkyDome]].<ref name=\"B\">{{cite news|title = Ontario wants rap star banned|first = Richard|last = Mackie|author2 = Marissa Nelson|type = newspaper|work = The Globe and Mail|location = Toronto|date = October 26, 2000|pages = A1, A4}}</ref> However, [[Ontario]] Attorney General [[Jim Flaherty]] argued that Canada should stop Eminem at the border. \"I personally don't want anyone coming to Canada who will come here and advocate [[violence against women]]\", he said.<ref name=\"B\" /> Flaherty claims to have been \"disgusted\" when reading transcriptions of Eminem's song \"Kill You\", which includes lines like \"Slut, you think I won't choke no whore/till the vocal cords don't work in her throat no more?\"<ref name=\"B\" /> Eminem's fans argued that this was a matter of [[free speech]] and that he was unfairly singled out.<ref name=\"B\" /> [[Michael Bryant (politician)|Michael Bryant]] suggested that the government let Eminem perform and then prosecute him for violating Canada's [[hate crime]] laws, despite the fact that Canada's hate-crime legislation does not include violence against women.<ref>Hiatt, Brian. [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1428569/canadian-officials-asked-stop-eminem-at-border.jhtml \"Canadian Officials Asked To Stop Eminem At Border\"]. MTV.com., October 26, 2000.</ref> In an editorial in ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', author Robert Everett-Green wrote, \"Being offensive is Eminem's job description.\"<ref name=\"A\">{{cite news|title = Bad rap for a rapper|first = Robert|last = Everett-Green|type = newspaper|work = The Globe and Mail|location = Toronto|date = October 26, 2000|page = A25}}</ref> Eminem was granted entry into Canada.<ref>ABC News. [http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/story?id=114066&page=1 \"Eminem vs. Canada\"]. October 26, 2000.</ref>\n\nA 2001 and 2004 study by Edward Armstrong found that of the 14 songs on ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' eleven contain violent and misogynistic lyrics and nine depict killing women through choking, stabbing, drowning, shooting, head and throat splitting. According to the study, Eminem scores 78% for violent misogyny while [[gangsta rap]] music in general reaches 22%.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Armstrong | first1 = Edward G | year = 2001 | title = Gangsta Misogyny: A Content Analysis of the Portrayals of Violence against Women in Rap Music, 1987\u20131993 | url = http://www.albany.edu/scj/jcjpc/vol8is2/armstrong.html | journal = Journal of Criminal Justice and Popular Culture | volume = 8 | issue = 2| pages = 96\u2013126 }}</ref><ref name=\"armstrong2\">{{cite journal | last1 = Armstrong | first1 = Edward G | year = 2004 | title = Eminem's Construction of Authenticity | url = | journal = Popular Music and Society | volume = 27 | issue = 3| pages = 335\u2013355 | doi = 10.1080/03007760410001733170 }}</ref> Armstrong argues that violent misogyny characterizes most of Eminem's music and that the rapper \"authenticates his self-presentations by outdoing other gangsta rappers in terms of his violent misogyny.\"<ref name=\"armstrong2\" /> A fifteen-year-old boy in [[Fresno, California]] was arrested in September 2015 for making terrorist threats, after sharing the Columbine-related lyrics to \"I'm Back\" on [[Instagram]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mays|first1=Mackenzie|title=Boy, 15, arrested in Instagram post that closed San Joaquin Memorial High|work=Fresno Bee|date=September 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Reactions from other artists===\n[[File:Elton John 2011 Shankbone 2.JPG|thumb|190px|[[Elton John]] performed \"Stan\" with Eminem at the Grammys despite negative reactions from the LGBT community.]]\nProtests against the album's content reached a climax when it was nominated for four [[Grammy Awards]] in 2001 including [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]].<ref name=\"GLAAD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1438949/20010201/eminem.jhtml|title=Gay Activist Group Plans Pre-Grammy Eminem Protest|date=February 1, 2001|work=|publisher=[MTV.com]|accessdate=December 21, 2008}}</ref> At the ceremony, Eminem performed \"Stan\" in a duet with openly gay artist [[Elton John]] playing piano and singing the chorus. This performance was a direct response to claims by GLAAD and others who claimed his lyrics were homophobic, with Eminem stating, \"Of course I'd heard of Elton John, but I didn't know he was gay. I didn't know anything about his personal life. I didn't really care, but being that he was gay and he had my back, I think it made a statement in itself saying that he understood where I was coming from.\"<ref name=\"performanceelton\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1439705/eminem-performance-with-elton-was-statement-enough/|title=Eminem: \"Performance With Elton Was Statement Enough\"|last=Basham|first=David|work=MTV News|publisher=Viacom|date=February 21, 2001|accessdate=May 26, 2018}}</ref> GLAAD did not change its position, however, and spoke out against Elton John's decision.<ref name=\"EltonJohn\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1439280/20010210/eminem.jhtml|title=Eminem, Elton John To Duet At Grammys|accessdate=December 24, 2008 |work= |publisher=MTV.com|date=February 10, 2001}}</ref> Despite significant protests and debate, ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' went on to win [[Best Rap Album]].\n\nSinger [[Christina Aguilera]] was upset about the lyric, \"Christina Aguilera better switch me chairs so I can sit next to [[Carson Daly]] and [[Fred Durst]] / and hear 'em argue over who she [[Fellatio|gave head]] to first\" from \"The Real Slim Shady\", calling the rapper's claim \"disgusting, offensive and, above all, not true\".<ref name=\"happybday\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2011/10/happy-birthday-eminem-heres-every-celebrity-youve-ever-dissed/246802/|title=Happy Birthday Eminem, Here's Every Celebrity You've Ever Dissed|last=Richards|first=Jason|date=October 17, 2011|accessdate=February 10, 2014|work=The Atlantic}}</ref> Eminem included this line after becoming angry with the singer for informing the public during an MTV special without his consent about the rapper's secret marriage to Kim Mathers.<ref name=\"happybday\" /> However, the two later settled their differences after hugging backstage at the [[2002 MTV Video Music Awards]], with the singer appearing at the premiere of ''[[8 Mile (film)|8 Mile]]'' months later.<ref name=\"happybday\" />\n\nIn 2002, French [[jazz]] pianist [[Jacques Loussier]] filed a $10 million lawsuit against Eminem, claiming the beat for \"Kill You\" was stolen from his song \"Pulsion\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/1904507.stm|title=Eminem sued by jazz star |accessdate=December 24, 2008 |work=BBC News|date=March 31, 2002}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\nCredits adapted from the album's [[liner notes]]<ref name=\"Album booklet\">{{cite AV media notes|title= The Marshall Mathers LP |year= 2000 |type= booklet |publisher= [[Aftermath Entertainment|Aftermath]], [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}</ref> and [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]<ref name=\"Tidal\">{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/586938/credits|title=The Marshall Mathers LP |year= 2000|website=Tidal}}</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| headline = ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' {{nobold|\u2013 Standard edition}}\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 72:04\n\n| title1 = Public Service Announcement 2000\n| note1 = performed by [[Jeff Bass]] and [[Eminem]]\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Eminem|Marshall Mathers]]|[[Jeff Bass]]}}\n| extr